<PB REF="00000009.tif" N="[1]">
<HEAD>S. Editha (Dialect von Wiltshire) aus Ms. Cotton Faustina B III.<NOTE PLACE="foot"><P>Diese Legende ist bereits edirt von Black u. d. T. Chronicon Vilodunense, 1830. Dem Dichter dieser Legende geh&ouml;rt auch die von S. Etheldrede in dems. Ms. fol. 260 ff. (ed. in A. L. N. F. p. 282 ff.) an.</P><P>Im Ms. sind y und &thorn; oft vertauscht, so 21 yat, ye st. &thorn;at, &thorn;e, 50 &thorn;nne st. ynne, 58 &thorn;w&thorn;s st. ywys u. a. Black in s. Ed. beh&auml;lt die Schreibweise des Ms. &mdash; Auf fol. 194 u. 5 ist oft corrigirt und radirt v. a. H.</P></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Almy&yogh;ty god in trinite, &verbar; fader &amp; sone and holy goste,<MILESTONE N="194" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Helpe and spede and conselle me, &verbar; as &thorn;ou art god of my&yogh;tus moste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">spede aus rede corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &yogh;eue me grace to brenge &verbar; to godde heyndynge,</L>
<L>Jhesu, for seint Edus sake, &verbar; &thorn;ys werke, &thorn;at y, so vnconnynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Edus in Edys corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="5">Presumpswysly(che) haue vndere-take.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in lyche ist che ausra|dirt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For y considere and knowe welle hytte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at thyngus &thorn;at haue ben fer (I)-paste<NOTE PLACE="foot">hinter fer sind zwei Buchst. ausradirt, vor past ein Buchst. (I); a. R. steht hertherto.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ley&yogh;tely(che) slydyth from monny(s) wytte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in lyche ist che ausra|dirt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">m&omacr;nys in mannys corr. Ms. urspr. whytte, h ist ausradirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bote &yogh;if &thorn;ey ben in story (y)-wryton or caste;<NOTE PLACE="foot">y ist ausradirt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="10">Wherfore y thenk in story to wry&yogh;te<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. thenk, e in y corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of kingus &thorn;at haue (y)-ben herbyfore<NOTE PLACE="foot">y ist ausradirt.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. byfore u. ybore mit n nach r &uuml;berschr. (byforne, yborne).</NOTE></L>
<L>Here in Westesexe, to touche a lyte,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor lyte sind zwei Buchst. ausrad. u. <I>ly</I> aufgetragen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sey&yogh;the kynge Egbert(e) was furste y-bore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. byfore u. ybore mit n nach r &uuml;berschr. (byforne, yborne).</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">furste in fyrste corr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For sump tyme in Westesexe &thorn;ere was a kinge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in kinge ist i in y corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="15">Egberte was &thorn;at kynges name,<NOTE PLACE="foot">e in Egberte &uuml;ber Rasur &uuml;berschr. kynges in kyngys corr.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>A dou&yogh;ty kny&yogh;t and of godde gouernynge,</L>
<L>And a mon he was of ry&yogh;t godde fame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ys dou&yogh;ty kny&yogh;t Egbert, Alquimundy (ys) sone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ys ist ausrad. u. an Alquimundy s angeh&auml;ngt.</NOTE></L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyngdome of Westsex was corond kynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. corone? in crownyd corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">In &thorn;e ay&yogh;te hundreth &yogh;ere saue on</L>
<L>After &thorn;at Jhesu of Mary ded sprynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ded in dyd corr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also he was &thorn;e twolthe kynge<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor also ist after ausgestr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at in Westsex cristyndam nome</L>
<L>After Kyngylf, &thorn;at holy thynge,</L>
<L N="25">&thorn;at by seynt Byryn crystyn be-come.
<PB REF="00000010.tif" N="2"></L>
<L>And at Wynchester y-cronyd he was</L>
<L>Of Elmestone, &thorn;at was bysshoppe &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e thryd &yogh;ere after thoro goddys grace<NOTE PLACE="foot">an thoro ist w angeh&auml;ngt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seynt Swythyn was I-bore also.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. bore in borne corr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="30">Byfore his tyme in Bretayne &thorn;er were</L>
<L>Syxe kyngdomus more &thorn;en his;</L>
<L>Bot foure &thorn;is kyng knytte y-fere,</L>
<L>As in trewe story wryten hit is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyngdam of Kent he wonne firste,<NOTE PLACE="foot">in kyngdam ist a in o corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="35">W<SUP>t</SUP> mony a batelle strong and sore,</L>
<L>And drof owte &thorn;e kyng, &thorn;at he neuer dirste</L>
<L>Chalange &thorn;at kyngdam after more;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyngdam of &thorn;e Marche he wonne also,</L>
<L>&thorn;is dou&yogh;ty knyght Egbert &thorn;e kynge,</L>
<L N="40">And &thorn;e kyngdam of Exsex he wonne &thorn;erto:</L>
<L>And hade &thorn;use foure in his gouernynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also by-fore his tyme y-wys</L>
<L>&thorn;is lond was clepyt alle-hole Bretayne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at now Englond y-clepyt ys</L>
<L N="45">For kynge Egberd &thorn;at name dede downe layne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fiue moner of pepull here dwellyd &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dwelt in dwellyd corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>To wex &thorn;e Bretones for hurre synne:</L>
<L>Pictis, and Scottys, and Hyrysshe also,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Denmarkes come &thorn;o first ynne,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="50">And &thorn;e Saxsones were &thorn;o clepud ynne also<NOTE PLACE="foot">tilge &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L>In kyng Wortynger is tyme, hym to helpe;</L>
<L>And so &thorn;ai deden hym seruice &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Bot how &thorn;ay deden after, y nylt not &yogh;elpe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For afterward &thorn;ai drevyn &thorn;e Brytones hou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="55">Fro herre owne habitacyone in &thorn;is lond here</L>
<L>And drevyn hem in-to Walys, w<SUP>t</SUP>-outen dou&yogh;te,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hom?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; in-to &thorn;is day &thorn;ay dwelle &yogh;et &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>From Saxsonye in Almayne &thorn;er comen y-wys</L>
<L>Thre maner of pepulle of one tonge:</L>
<L N="60">Saxones, &amp; Jutys, and Englysshe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at thralles weren here fulle longe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot afterward &thorn;ey weren long lordys and kyngys here<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>And hadden alle &thorn;is hole reme in her gouernaunce,</L>
<L>Tylle Wyllyam Bastard, as &yogh;e &yogh;et mowe yche day here,</L>
<L N="65">Come owt of Normandy in Fraunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And slow kyng Haralde in &thorn;e batelle of Hastynge,</L>
<L>And alle his ost he scomfytyd &thorn;ere also;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &omacr;st = host?</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;o of alle Englonde he was y-cronyd kynge</L>
<L>And put &thorn;e Saxsones a-&yogh;eyn in to thraldam &amp; wo.
<PB REF="00000011.tif" N="3"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="70">Kny&yogh;tes and swyers he made &thorn;o bounde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wyche gentyls and lordys byfore &thorn;at were;</L>
<L>Dukys and herles he drof owte of &thorn;is lond &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey durst not here abyde for fere &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And made mony of hom lordes &thorn;o</L>
<L N="75">&thorn;at comen w<SUP>t</SUP> hym fro Normondy,</L>
<L>And put &thorn;e Saxsones a&yogh;eyn in thraldam &amp; wo</L>
<L>By-cause of here synne (&amp;) of here foly &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For pryde, couetyse and lechery<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L>God toke opon hem suche vengeaunce &thorn;us;</L>
<L N="80">And falslyche to for-swere hem &thorn;ey nere neuer wery &mdash;</L>
<L>Here owne kyng Haralde &yogh;affe hom ensampulle of &thorn;is. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">haralde &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot kynge Egberde, of &thorn;e wyche I speke to &yogh;ov of &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Vsede no poyntes of suche synnes ny of suche foly:</L>
<L>Wherfore he knytte foure kyngdomus y-fere,</L>
<L N="85">And gouerned hem welle and fulle monfully.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he had brou&yogh;t &thorn;o foure kindamus to hepe<MILESTONE N="195" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And won &thorn;e cyte of Chester also,</L>
<L>He commaundede alle men to clepe</L>
<L>Alle his lond Englonde &thorn;o,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="90">And he commandede his men also</L>
<L>To clepe alle &thorn;e Saxsones Englisshemen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. saxsons.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e Britones &thorn;at were &thorn;ere &thorn;o</L>
<L>To ben y-clepud Wallisshemen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Britones were long I-clepud Cadwallesmen,</L>
<L N="95">After Cadwalle &thorn;at was hure kynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">hure in there corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot Saxsones clepud hom &yogh;ey&yogh;then Walshemen<NOTE PLACE="foot">hom in them corr.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;ey&yogh;then = sythen.</NOTE></L>
<L>By-cause of sherte spekynge.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Engestis in Engistis corr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Saxsones were y-clepud Engestis men,</L>
<L>Englys and Jutys bothe y-fere,</L>
<L N="100">For Hengestis was &thorn;e first duke of hem</L>
<L>And in to &thorn;is lond he dede hem lere;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For ry&yogh;t as Walshemen token hure name</L>
<L>Of Cadwalle &thorn;at &thorn;o hure kyng wys,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t so Englisshemen token hure name<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. token token.</NOTE></L>
<L N="105">Of here owne duke Hengestis.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Engestis in Engistis corr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;us Englonde toke first his name</L>
<L>In &thorn;e gode kyng Egbertys tyme,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as we clepe &yogh;et &thorn;e same</L>
<L>And herrafter shulde w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te lyme.<NOTE PLACE="foot">w<SUP>t</SUP> ist &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="110">And when kyng Egbert, as I sayde heyre,</L>
<L>Had set in pese &thorn;us alle his lond</L>
<L>And scomfidid his enmyes w<SUP>t</SUP> batel &amp; monhode y-fere</L>
<L>&amp; made alle &thorn;is reme to ben y-clepud alle-hole Englonde,
<PB REF="00000012.tif" N="4"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He satte &thorn;o in grete rest and peys:</L>
<L N="115">For nomon durst w<SUP>t</SUP> hym werre &mdash;</L>
<L>For he was a monfulle kny&yogh;t w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te leys &mdash;</L>
<L>His name was knowe bothe ne&yogh;e and ferre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For when he had &thorn;us foure kyngdamus to-geder satte,</L>
<L>He dwelte at Wyltone w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te leys</L>
<L N="120">Nyne wynter longe after &thorn;at</L>
<L>In gode rest &amp; in gode peys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">ist hinter 120 geschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And other-whyle at Wynchester he dwelte also,</L>
<L>And eke at Salisbury in &thorn;at tour,</L>
<L>And in mony other places mo,</L>
<L N="125">As a kyng ou&yogh;te of suche honour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An holy mon, forsothe, he was,</L>
<L>And gret almys he dede for goddes sake;</L>
<L>Religyose houses in mony a plase</L>
<L>For goddys loue he let &thorn;o make.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="130">In &thorn;e toune of Wyltone let make one<NOTE PLACE="marg">Henricus Cr&omacr;pe.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e worshippe of owre lady,</L>
<L>By consel of Bysshop Elmestone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was bysshop of Wynchester &thorn;o, sycurlye,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And threttene sustren he sette &thorn;ere-Inne,</L>
<L N="135">To serue &thorn;ere god bothe nyght and day;</L>
<L>A Religiose house &thorn;ey clepte hit &thorn;enne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">A ist vorgeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Seynt Mary chirche &thorn;erto &thorn;o laye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For Elburwys loue he made &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e erle of Wyltones wyf by-fore,</L>
<L N="140">And kyng Egbertys sustre also he was,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere-inne also hee was y-bore; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Erle Wolstones wyff, forsothe, hee was,</L>
<L>Or he toke &thorn;e mantelle and &thorn;e rynge;</L>
<L>And to make a relygiose house of hur owne place,</L>
<L N="145">He prayede hur brother Egbert &thorn;e kynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kyng Egbert grauntede hit anone</L>
<L>By conselle of Elmestone, as I sayde &yogh;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;is ordinaunce was &thorn;us y-done</L>
<L>Of his regnynge &thorn;e threttythe &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="150">&thorn;is Religiose house was foundyd &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;e threttythe &yogh;ere of his regnynge,</L>
<L>And ay&yogh;te hundryd and thretty &yogh;ere</L>
<L>After &thorn;at Jhesu of Mary dud sprynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seuene &yogh;ere lenger &yogh;et left his lyffe<NOTE PLACE="marg">Henricus Cr&omacr;pe.</NOTE></L>
<L N="155">In his remys gouernynge, w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te blame.</L>
<L>A sone he had by Osyth, his wyffe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Black left.</NOTE></L>
<L>Atwolf was &thorn;at chyldis name.
<PB REF="00000013.tif" N="5"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot afterwarde, when he was ded,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dede mit ausrad. e.</NOTE></L>
<L>At Wynchester was his byryenge,</L>
<L N="160">And Atwolf his sone, as I haue red,</L>
<L>Anone after was made her kynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is Atwolf was croned kyng here</L>
<L>After &thorn;at goddis sone was bore</L>
<L>Ay&yogh;te hundreth &amp; ay&yogh;te &amp; thretty &yogh;ere</L>
<L N="165">And thre monethus &amp; nyne dayes more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kyng Atwolff was an harlasmon<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. man, &uuml;ber a ist o &uuml;bersch. harlas = harmless.</NOTE></L>
<L>And loued ry&yogh;t welle to serue god;</L>
<L>Forsothe, harme nolde he do none,</L>
<L>Bot he wold do meche gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="170">&thorn;is kyng had in hys leuynge</L>
<L>Foure sones by hys weddyd wyff &mdash;</L>
<L>Osburwe he het, &thorn;at semely thynge,</L>
<L>Children had he nomo in alle his lyffe; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>After he was kynge, he wedded hure sone &mdash;</L>
<L N="175">His owne spencers dou&yogh;ter he was;</L>
<L>In Westsex he dwellyd &thorn;o alle-one</L>
<L>At Wylton in his owne place.<MILESTONE N="196" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For Wyltone was a gode toune &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And meche pepulle &thorn;eder drowe,</L>
<L N="180">&thorn;e kynge duellud &thorn;ere meche also,</L>
<L>For plentythe of vitel &thorn;ere was y-nowe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. plentyche.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hit was meche &thorn;e better for his sake,</L>
<L>For he was a fulle honest mone;</L>
<L>Chirches and Abbays he ded do make</L>
<L N="185">W<SUP>t</SUP>-inne his reme mony one.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to holy chirche &thorn;is kyng &yogh;aff &thorn;an</L>
<L>&thorn;e tenthe part of his lond,</L>
<L>By conselle of seynt Swythan,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;o was bysshop of Wynchester, I vnderstonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="190">&thorn;e religiouse house of Wyltone he encreset also</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche his fader had I-made byfore,</L>
<L>And mo religiouse wymen he sette &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;aff londes and rentes welle more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For men of holy chirche he loued fulle welle</L>
<L N="195">And gret chere to hem euer he made;</L>
<L>And also, w<SUP>t</SUP> seynt Elmistone when he dede dwelle,</L>
<L>Ordour of sodekyn forsothe he hade &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For a mone of holychirche he wolde haue be,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e reme nold not consent &thorn;erto,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="200">For &thorn;ere was non other heyre bot he &mdash;</L>
<L>For kynge Egberde had sones no mo.
<PB REF="00000014.tif" N="6"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore afterwarde he went to Rome</L>
<L>To Leo, &thorn;at was pope &thorn;ere &thorn;anne,</L>
<L>To be assoyled of &thorn;at by his dome &mdash;</L>
<L N="205">For &thorn;at was &thorn;e conselle of seynt Swythanne &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP> hym he toke Alured his sone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;ongest was of hem alle,</L>
<L>And a twolmonthe at Rome he dud wone &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e pope Leo men dede &thorn;o calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="210">He graunted also &thorn;o to pay to Rome</L>
<L>Euery &yogh;ere a peny y-wys</L>
<L>Of yche an house in his kyngdom &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;at "Peter pounse" y-clepud &yogh;et is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For byfore his tyme &thorn;e lawe was suche:</L>
<L N="215">&thorn;at, what mon had don ony opone horribulle synne,</L>
<L>As smytten his fader or mone of holy chyrche,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e pope he most go, his pardone to wynne;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I-fedryd to-gedere &thorn;ey most &thorn;edur go,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as thewys gone to &thorn;e galowe-tre.</L>
<L N="220">Kynge Athwolffe sawe hem oft so do,</L>
<L>And had of hem ry&yogh;t gret pete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o he gate to Englond suche a priuilage</L>
<L>&thorn;at non Englysshemone shulde go more &thorn;eder in suche a manere;</L>
<L>He granted &thorn;o to &thorn;e Pope Leo suche a talage:</L>
<L N="225">Offe euery howse in his kyndam a peny by &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot quen he had dwelled &thorn;ere alle &thorn;at &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>Home thoro Fraunce he come y-wys.</L>
<L>Kyng Charlys dou&yogh;ter he weddede &thorn;o &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And in to Englonde w<SUP>t</SUP> hure y-comen he ys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. come, Ms. com&emacr;.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="230">He regned here two &amp; twenty wyntre,</L>
<L>In grete worship and in gret prosperite;</L>
<L>He dyed and byreyd was at Wynchester.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is plase byfore y-sayde &thorn;e secund founder was he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Athelbalde his sone was mad kyng &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="235">He regned here bot on &yogh;ere, yche vnderstonde.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Athelbaldus.</NOTE></L>
<L>His owne stepmoder was wedded hym to,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyns &thorn;e lawes of &thorn;is londe:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He wedded Judyth, &thorn;at was his fader wyffe.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wherfore alle thyng felle to hym a-mys;</L>
<L N="240">He dyede for vengaunce of his synnefulle lyffe,</L>
<L>And at Shirburne y-buryed he ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;en was Ethelbryt y-croned hure kynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">Ethelbri&yogh;tus.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">hure st. here.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of alle Westsexus londe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was in his brother leuynge</L>
<L N="245">Kyng of Kent, as I vnderstonde;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And regned after hym fyue &yogh;ere ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And had Westsex and Kent bothe yn fee;</L>
<L>And dyed &thorn;o thoro goddys my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And at Wymburne y-buryed was he.
<PB REF="00000015.tif" N="7"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="250">Bot when Ethelbry&yogh;t was &thorn;us forthe past,</L>
<L>Hys brother Etheldrede was y-croned &thorn;o kynge.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Etheldredus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Anone after &thorn;at in gret hast</L>
<L>Gret grace he hade thoro gode leuynge &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For an holy mon, forsothe, he was</L>
<L N="255">And loued fulle welle goddys seruyse;</L>
<L>Euery day he wold here a masse,</L>
<L>As sone as he ded vp ryse; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore hit fel hym oft by grace</L>
<L>To haue of god what &thorn;at he bedde.</L>
<L N="260">In experience hit felle by case</L>
<L>At Asshedone, wase hath &thorn;e story redde:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For at Asshedone a tyme hit felle by case</L>
<L>&thorn;at Osegys, &thorn;at kyng of Denmarke was &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Come to Asshedone w<SUP>t</SUP> grete manasse,</L>
<L N="265">W<SUP>t</SUP> other lordys mony on mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot kyng Etheldrede was &thorn;ere redy y-wys,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> Alured, his brother, and other mo,</L>
<L>Forto a&yogh;eyn-stonde alle his malys</L>
<L>And to kepe &thorn;at countre fro hem also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="270">Herlyche in &thorn;e moretyde forsothe hit was<MILESTONE N="197" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is batel shuld &thorn;ere ydo be.</L>
<L>Bot Etheldred went to chyrche a gode pas,</L>
<L>To here a masse &thorn;ere of &thorn;e Trynite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;at whyle &thorn;e Danys in &thorn;e feld chesen hure place</L>
<L N="275">Ry&yogh;t at hure owne wylle;</L>
<L>Bot kyng Etheldred a-bode and herd his masse</L>
<L>And made his prayers knelyng fulle stylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote Alured his brother was in &thorn;e felde</L>
<L>Monfullyche w<SUP>t</SUP> alle his men,</L>
<L N="280">Wel arayed w<SUP>t</SUP> spere and shelde;</L>
<L>&thorn;e mynstrals blwe hure trompus &thorn;en.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;us men bygonne &amp; scarmysshute fast,</L>
<L>&thorn;e twey hostes bothe y-fere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e Englysshemen &thorn;ey woxe a-gast</L>
<L N="285">And bygunne to falle alle hure chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e Englysshe lordys lokedone after hure kyng</L>
<L>And speke and prayden hym come to hem anone.</L>
<L>Bot he nold not &thorn;en for no-thynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. loke don.</NOTE></L>
<L>Tyl alle &thorn;e masse were fully done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="290">Bot when &thorn;e masse was alle y-dee,</L>
<L>Kyng Etheldrede hey&yogh;ede hym fulle fast;</L>
<L>&thorn;e Englysshemen by-gonne to fle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dee, Bl. doe.</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;ey were fulle sore a-gast.
<PB REF="00000016.tif" N="8"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng toke &thorn;o to hym his horse,</L>
<L N="295">And in &thorn;e trinites holy name</L>
<L>He hym blessed and mad a crosse,</L>
<L>And bad his men to do &thorn;e same;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He prekede in to &thorn;e felde &thorn;o fulle snelle</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e Denmerkys so kene,</L>
<L N="300">And alle &thorn;at he met adon he felle,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. adon oder ado&umacr;?</NOTE></L>
<L>And slowe hem alle by-dene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e Dane kyng he slowe y-wys,</L>
<L>And alle his lordys &thorn;at were &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;e victory was his,</L>
<L N="305">&thorn;orowe help of &thorn;e trinite &amp; of &thorn;e masse &thorn;at he dud here. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By whyche ensawmpulle I may welle see<NOTE PLACE="foot">I st. &yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>How gracyose hit is a masse to here,</L>
<L>And nomlyche of &thorn;e trinite,</L>
<L>To euery worthy kyng or bachelere. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="310">Bot &thorn;en sone after dyed &thorn;is kyng</L>
<L>Etheldrede, &thorn;at was &thorn;e elder brothere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ay&yogh;the &yogh;ere of his regnynge.</L>
<L>Alured was heyre &thorn;o &mdash; &thorn;ere nasse non othere. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Alrudus.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot nowe y chulle &yogh;ow telle by goddys grace</L>
<L N="315">For whom &yogh;e ben y-holde to prey&yogh;e fore</L>
<L>And who were first funders of &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche y spake of byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e ay&yogh;te hundreth after &thorn;e incarnacyone hit felle by case</L>
<L>&thorn;at Ethelmunde, &thorn;at of &thorn;e Marche &thorn;o was kynge,</L>
<L N="320">Come in to Westsex w<SUP>t</SUP> gret manasse,</L>
<L>To make &thorn;e erle of Wylteshyre his vnderlynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Wolstone, &thorn;at was erle of Wylteshyre &thorn;oo,</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynestode hym w<SUP>t</SUP> gret strenthe and mayne,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mony a mon of Wylteshyre mo,</L>
<L N="325">And drof hym to his lond a&yogh;ayne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot in &thorn;at batelle was slawe y-wys</L>
<L>Alquimundy, &thorn;at holy mone, &mdash;</L>
<L>Erle Wolstonus wyffus fader he wys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">fader &uuml;bergeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hym he made gret soro and mone,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="330">And for his soule a chyrche lette make</L>
<L>In Wyltone fast by his owne place,</L>
<L>To syng and red for his sowle sake;</L>
<L>&thorn;at a collage y-clepud &thorn;o hit wasse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot in &thorn;e honour of owre lady</L>
<L N="335">Hit had ben foundyd ferre byfore,</L>
<L>Bot thorow strong werre, securlye,</L>
<L>Hit was almost clene forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so for seynt Alquimoundyes loue hit was fyrst y-made</L>
<L>Off Walstone, &thorn;at was erle of Wylteshyre &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="340">And afterwarde for Elburwys loue, as y ere sayde,</L>
<L>Kyng Egberde made &thorn;e religyose house &thorn;erto.
<PB REF="00000017.tif" N="9"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so erle Walstone was furst founder of &thorn;at chirche</L>
<L>For seynt Alquimoundyes loue ywys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Henricus Cr&omacr;pe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Elburwe &thorn;at religyose house let after whirche,</L>
<L N="345">And so &thorn;e fyrst founder &thorn;erof he was, &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By consent of Egberde &thorn;e kynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was hure owne brother;</L>
<L>&amp; so he was furst cause of &thorn;at house makynge &mdash;</L>
<L>He preyde hym so feyre, he my&yogh;t non other,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="350">Bot grauntede for (to) be hure patrone</L>
<L>And mayntenere of &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>And Elburwe hure-self dede &thorn;er-inne w&omacr;ne,</L>
<L>Sone after &thorn;at &thorn;e erle ded was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; kyng Egbert &yogh;affe bothe londys &amp; rente</L>
<L N="355">To &thorn;at place and &thorn;e chirche, y-wys,</L>
<L>For his loue &thorn;at alle thyng sente;</L>
<L>And &thorn;us &thorn;e furst founder of kynges he ys.<MILESTONE N="198" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Atwolfe his sone, &thorn;at holy mon,</L>
<L>&YOGH;aff londys and rentys &thorn;erto, as y sayde ere.</L>
<L N="360">And Ethelbalde his son, when he was gone,</L>
<L>Of kynges was &thorn;e thryd founder.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And kyng Ethelbry&yogh;te, &thorn;at worthy kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;e fourthe founder he was &thorn;erto.</L>
<L>And Etheldrede, &thorn;at holy wy&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="365">Was &thorn;e fyuethe founder also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of kyngys founders fynd I no mo</L>
<L>Y-wryton in no story y-wys &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot Wolstone and Elburwe &thorn;at weren &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;e first causes off alle &thorn;is. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="370">Bot after Etheldrede Alured, his brother, was y-croned kynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e &yogh;ongust brother of alle,</L>
<L>A fulle wysmon, and of fulle gode gouernynge &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alurde &thorn;e gode kynge, men dedon hym calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For quen he was a &yogh;onge thynge,</L>
<L N="375">To Rome w<SUP>t</SUP> his fader he went,</L>
<L>And of Leo &thorn;e pope was anyntyd kynge &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e gretter grace god hym sent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is Alrud lyued &amp; regnyd kyng here</L>
<L>Nyne and twenty wyntre ny&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="380">In grete trauayle and werre y-fere &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;us Danes weren fulle fals and sly&yogh;e</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And werreden w<SUP>t</SUP> hym euer fulle fast;</L>
<L>Bot he was euer a dou&yogh;ty kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And ouer-come hem at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L N="385">&thorn;oro &thorn;e grace of goddys my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An holy mone forsothe was he</L>
<L>&amp; seruede god bothe ny&yogh;t and day,</L>
<L>For he dipartede hem (in) &thorn;ree &mdash;</L>
<L>In what maner y chulle &yogh;ow say.
<PB REF="00000018.tif" N="10"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="390">Of foure and twenty houres y-wys</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;e nombre be departyd in &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Ey&yogh;te, ey&yogh;te, and ey&yogh;te hit ys &mdash;</L>
<L>Counte hit welle and &yogh;e mowe se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e first ey&yogh;t houres of &thorn;e day</L>
<L N="395">He serued god, heuene kynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;e secunde ey&yogh;te houres in reste and play,</L>
<L>&thorn;e thryd ey&yogh;te houres in his remes gouernynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thre waxe-candels he let make &thorn;en,</L>
<L>Euery candelle y-leyche of wey&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="400">In his chapelle forto bren</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e day and eke &thorn;e ny&yogh;t:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;use thre candels weren ordeyned &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Forto depart &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;ree</L>
<L>In maner ry&yogh;t as I sayd ere,</L>
<L N="405">As &thorn;e story telleth welle me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kyng Alured &yogh;et dude more &thorn;en &thorn;is:</L>
<L>He departed his rentys in two:</L>
<L>Hym-selfe &thorn;e to halfe and no more ywys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. to(ke) &thorn;e?</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e to&thorn;er half in almys-dede was do:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="410">To chirches and abbays &thorn;at weren pore</L>
<L>&thorn;e ton half &thorn;us &yogh;affe he,</L>
<L>&thorn;ay to haue hit for euermore</L>
<L>In possessyon and in fee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>After &thorn;e Incarnacyon ay&yogh;te hundreth &yogh;ere fenty and fyue hit was</L>
<L N="415">&thorn;at kyng Alured was cronyd here kynge,</L>
<L>For heyre of Westsex non other &thorn;ere nasse</L>
<L>Bot Alured, &thorn;at worthy thynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;e moneth after &thorn;is</L>
<L>&thorn;at Alured kyng of Westsex was made,</L>
<L N="420">&thorn;e Danys comen to Wyltone y-wys,</L>
<L>And a grete batelle &thorn;ere he hade.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot kyng Alured was redy at Wyltone &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e st. &thorn;o.</NOTE></L>
<L>And Edwarde his sone, &thorn;at worthy kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mony an other dou&yogh;ty lord mo,</L>
<L N="425">&thorn;at fou&yogh;te w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e Danys w<SUP>t</SUP> alle hure my&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A gret batelle &thorn;at day &thorn;ere was y-wys,</L>
<L>And mony a mone &thorn;ere &thorn;at day was slawe:</L>
<L>For &thorn;at day felle to eyder part amys,</L>
<L>And mony a mon was &thorn;at day y-do to (!) dawe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">to st. of.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="430">Bot first quen &thorn;e pepulle &thorn;e sothe herde</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e Danys to Wyltone y-comen were,</L>
<L>For-sothe &thorn;ey were fulle sore a-drede,</L>
<L>And cryeden and wepto alle y-fere;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wymen and children &thorn;ay cry&yogh;eden fast<NOTE PLACE="marg">Walterus Oxfordiensis.</NOTE></L>
<L N="435">And prayed god to help hem for his grace &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey weren fulle sore a-gast</L>
<L>Bothe of hem-self and of here place.
<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="11"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Edwarde Senior, &thorn;at dwelte &thorn;ere &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Had a &yogh;ong chylde to dou&yogh;ter y-wys,</L>
<L N="440">&thorn;at w<SUP>t</SUP> hure norse was &thorn;ere also;</L>
<L>For sothe, w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre hit felle amys:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;at day &thorn;at childe was dede,</L>
<L>Hurre soule past vp to heuen blysse.</L>
<L>Bot as I haue in story oft redde,<MILESTONE N="199" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="445">&thorn;e cause of hurre deyth, forsoth, was &thorn;is &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ry&yogh;t as hit was, y chulle &yogh;ov lere,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e story doth me telle.</L>
<L>Water and herbus were sodone y-fere,</L>
<L>To han wasshe &thorn;at chyld euery delle;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="450">Bot &thorn;e norse &thorn;at shulde &thorn;e chyld haue kepte,</L>
<L>Herd crye and sorwe on ycha syde:</L>
<L>&thorn;e chylde in &thorn;at water leyge he lette</L>
<L>And for-&yogh;at hit in &thorn;at tyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is childe nasse bot &thorn;re &yogh;ere of age</L>
<L N="455">When hit was dede at Wyltone &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Of hurre fadres first mariage,</L>
<L>Elflede was hurre name y-wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;is childe was &thorn;is &thorn;er .deyde,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t gret sorowe was made &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L N="460">Bot when &thorn;ey sey&yogh;e non other redde,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey thongedone god &amp; mournedone no more,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And burydone &thorn;at chylde fulle honestly,</L>
<L>Bothe erlys &amp; barnesse &amp; ladyes clere,</L>
<L>In seynt Maryes chyrche &thorn;er fast-by,</L>
<L N="465">&thorn;ere as &thorn;e religiose wymmen were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot alle-&thorn;awe &thorn;is childe were &thorn;is deyed &amp; buryed &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And &thorn;at gret batelle at Wyltone y-do,</L>
<L>Mony gret batels after &thorn;at &yogh;et &thorn;ere were</L>
<L>Y-don bytwynne Alured &amp; &thorn;e Danys mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="470">Bot in &thorn;e fourthe &yogh;ere after hit felle by case</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey comen to Chypenham and distry&yogh;edo &thorn;e contre clene</L>
<L>And dystry&yogh;ede &amp; brenden vp &thorn;e kyngys place,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;erof nasse &thorn;ere no-thyng sene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And kyng Alured dwelt in Selwode &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="475">To haue had &thorn;ere summe rest, in pore aray;</L>
<L>Bot twenty men had he w<SUP>t</SUP> hym no mo;</L>
<L>By fysshyng and hondynge &yogh;et leuedone &thorn;ere &thorn;ey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot sone after hit felle by case</L>
<L>In Selwode, in &thorn;at wylde countraye,</L>
<L N="480">&thorn;at kyng Alured fulle heuy was</L>
<L>And in a preueye place alle-one he lay,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And his men one fysshyng from hym weron gone;</L>
<L>Bot in his preyers he knelyd fulle stylle.</L>
<L>&thorn;o by hym come an olde hore mone</L>
<L N="485">And sayde: "syr kyng, rest &yogh;ov wylle!<NOTE PLACE="foot">wylle aus welle corr.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000020.tif" N="12"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syre kynge, he sayde, ychaue ferre gone,</L>
<L>Somme meyte &yogh;eme for charyte!"</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng loked vpon on (!) &thorn;at old mone</L>
<L>And sayde: "y thonk god in trynite"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &yogh;&emacr;me = &yogh;if me.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="490">And lufte vp his hondone two<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. vpon on; Bl. l. nur vpon.</NOTE></L>
<L>And thonked god mekely of his grace</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde fouchesafe to send hym to</L>
<L>A nother as pore a mone as he hym-self was,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To aske of hym gode &thorn;at had nou&yogh;te hym-self to take to,</L>
<L N="495">Bot as a pore beyger shulde, askethe, of an no&thorn;ere.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng clepte after his mon &thorn;o</L>
<L>And sayde: "&thorn;owe schalte haue, myn owne brother;"<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. pore <SUP>a</SUP> st. a pore (a an falscher Stelle &uuml;bersch.).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng sayde: "syre, &yogh;e shull fayn haue</L>
<L>Suche gode as god has &yogh;eue to me;</L>
<L N="500">Y thonke god &thorn;at yche ou&yogh;te haue</L>
<L>For his loue to &yogh;eue nowe to &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Panterere, yche &thorn;e prey, quod &thorn;e kynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">pantenere = pantler.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;eue &thorn;owe somme mete to &thorn;is mon,</L>
<L>For his loue &thorn;at made alle thynge,</L>
<L N="505">Let hym not hongry no furre gone!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His panterere to a lofe &thorn;o ywys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. to st. toke.</NOTE></L>
<L>And brake hit euene an-two,</L>
<L>And sayde: "syre, &yogh;e shulde haue &thorn;is,</L>
<L>For loues haue y no mo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="510">&thorn;is pore mon toke &thorn;is bred, and his leue also,</L>
<L>And forthe on his way con passe &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey nyste neuer where he was a-go,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne of his trodus no sygne &thorn;er nasse,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot sodenlyche he vanysshede a-way &mdash;</L>
<L N="515">None of hem wyst whoder-warde.</L>
<L>&thorn;e bred &thorn;at he reseyued, stylle &thorn;ere laye,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at loffe toke he no parde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en come &thorn;us fysshers home a-swythe</L>
<L>And plenteythe of fysshe &thorn;ey hadden y-nowe;</L>
<L N="520">And etone and drongone and made hem blythe.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng afterwarde to slepe he hym drowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e kyng was y-fole a-slepe,<NOTE PLACE="foot">y-fole = fallen, vgl. 897.</NOTE></L>
<L>A wonder sy&yogh;t hym tho&yogh;t he saye:</L>
<L>&thorn;at a semely prelet stode at his fete,</L>
<L N="525">Lyke to a bysshop in his araye,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayde: "syre kyng, take &yogh;e gode hede</L>
<L>To serue god in ry&yogh;twysnasse,</L>
<L>And pore men loue to clethe &amp; fede</L>
<L>And alle men of holy chirche, bothe more and lasse,
<PB REF="00000021.tif" N="13"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="530">And loue religiose w<SUP>t</SUP> alle &yogh;oure myght<MILESTONE N="200" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And loke &thorn;at &yogh;e done hem encrese:</L>
<L>And &thorn;owe shalde ouercome &thorn;y enmyes anon ry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. shalle.</NOTE></L>
<L>And leue afterwarde in gode rest and pese."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kynge askede anone what was his name</L>
<L N="535">And what mon and whethen &thorn;at he wasse.</L>
<L>"Cudberth of Dereham, he sayde, ychame</L>
<L>&thorn;at telle &thorn;e nowthe of &thorn;is casse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;ou art in &thorn;y prosperite</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t at &thorn;yn owne left,</L>
<L N="540">Loke &thorn;at &thorn;owe thenk &thorn;en vpone me,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ow shalle fynd &thorn;at for &thorn;e beste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Icham &thorn;e pylgrym &thorn;at bad &thorn;e brede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at god hath send nowe to &thorn;e.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ow do as ychaue &thorn;e rede,</L>
<L N="545">And lowe welle god, and he wylle loue &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he knowyth &thorn;y conscyens ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L>And &thorn;y gode hert he knoyth also;</L>
<L>He wolle &thorn;e whyte euery delle,</L>
<L>Fulle welle &thorn;ou my&yogh;t trust &thorn;erto."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="550">&thorn;e kyng a-woke anone after &thorn;is,</L>
<L>And a gret charge he toke hym vpone:</L>
<L>For in a Jogulers lykenesse y-wys</L>
<L>He went to aspye what dede his fon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;e kynge had aspyet ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L N="555">Ry&yogh;t at his owne plesaunce and lefte,</L>
<L>Hom a&yogh;eyn he come fulle snelle</L>
<L>And tolde his mone alle &thorn;at he sawe, both most &amp; leste.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mone st. mene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;o come Hampshyre, Wylteshyre, &amp; Somerset to,</L>
<L>To help &thorn;e kyng in his nede.</L>
<L N="560">And anone to here enmyes &thorn;ey wenton &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And slowe hem &amp; toke hem euery hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng of Denmarke &yogh;olde hym anone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And granted cristenmon euer to be;</L>
<L>And thretty gret lordys mo</L>
<L N="565">Weren ycrystonyd in &thorn;e nome of &thorn;e trinite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alured toke vp &thorn;e kyng from &thorn;e fonstone</L>
<L>And his godefader by-come ry&yogh;t &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>And clepte &thorn;e same Ethelstone</L>
<L>&thorn;at Gurmunde was y-clepud by-fore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="570">And &yogh;affe hym lonndys and rentys y-wys,</L>
<L>Bothe to hym and to his wyffe.</L>
<L>And Alured lyued after in rest and peys</L>
<L>&thorn;e most part of alle his lyffe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And kyng Alured went to Wylton &thorn;o</L>
<L N="575">From &thorn;e yle of Hethelynge;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e bysshop Swytheline was &thorn;ere also,</L>
<L>For at Wyltone &thorn;o was his dwellynge.
<PB REF="00000022.tif" N="14"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng dyd maken abbeys &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
<L>For to werre he thoghte nomore;</L>
<L N="580">At Wyltone he let make one of &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;at honestlyche stont &yogh;et ry&yogh;t &thorn;ore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of his owne maner w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te wene</L>
<L>He let &thorn;ere a nabbay &thorn;o make</L>
<L>&thorn;orow preyer of Egwne &thorn;e quene</L>
<L N="585">For Elflede, &thorn;at chyldys sake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also Edward his sone graunde &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>By preyour of Elflede, his suster dere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was godmoder and aunte also</L>
<L>Of Elflede &thorn;e chylde &thorn;at was ded &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="590">And Swythelyne, &thorn;at was bysshop &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Will. Ryualensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Was made cheffe procutour of &thorn;at place;</L>
<L>And so he was procutour and gret helper &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>For a fulle holy mone forsothe he was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Merche forsothe &thorn;e seueneth day</L>
<L N="595">At Wyltone &thorn;is batelle was &thorn;us y-do;</L>
<L>&thorn;e same tyme dyede &thorn;at lytille may,</L>
<L>&thorn;e story tellyth and sayth ry&yogh;t so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In august &thorn;e II &yogh;ere after &thorn;e twenty day</L>
<L>Kyng Alured leyd &thorn;e first ston,</L>
<L N="600">In &thorn;e name of owre lady, &thorn;at blest May,</L>
<L>And of seynt Bartholomey, &thorn;at holy mone &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For by-twene &thorn;e Assumpsyon &amp; his day hit was</L>
<L>&thorn;e secunde ffery &thorn;at &thorn;ay be-gone to wyrche;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e kyng was &thorn;ere &thorn;o in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="605">And leyd &thorn;ere &thorn;e first stone of &thorn;at chyrche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>After &thorn;e Incarnacyon ay&yogh;te hundreth &yogh;ere</L>
<L>&amp; foure score &yogh;ere mo &amp; ten</L>
<L>&thorn;is abbay was fyrst set here</L>
<L>By syre Alured &thorn;at was kynge then;<MILESTONE N="201" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="610">And after &thorn;e bygynnyng of &thorn;e first priory</L>
<L>Thre score fulle &yogh;ere and thre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was fyrst foundyd in kyng Egberdys day</L>
<L>For Elburwes loue, his sustre free.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne two &yogh;ere &thorn;is abbey was wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="615">And brou&yogh;t to a parfytte hende &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot of &thorn;e dedycacyon spake y ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For euery &yogh;ere hit comys in mynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Radgunde was first sacryd abbas &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e erlys dou&yogh;ter of Wylteshyre, Ethelstone;</L>
<L N="620">And &thorn;e relygyose wymen &thorn;at weron at seynt Mary chirche byfore</L>
<L>Weren bro&yogh;t &thorn;eder &thorn;o euerychone;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And other maydones mony mo also</L>
<L>Weron veylled &thorn;o in &thorn;at abbay:</L>
<L>Radgund &amp; twelffe other maydones mo</L>
<L N="625">Weron y-weylled &thorn;ere in on day.
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="15"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So &thorn;at in &thorn;e first bygynnynge</L>
<L>Syxe and twenty wemen &thorn;ere were</L>
<L>And hadden &thorn;ere hurre leuyng,</L>
<L>To serue god &thorn;ere alle y-fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="630">Bot &thorn;en in short tyme after &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kyng Alured felle in gret age;</L>
<L>He send bysshop Swytelyn y-wys</L>
<L>In to Yende for hym on pilgremage,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Ethelstone, &thorn;at was erle of Wylteshyre &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="635">To &thorn;e courte of Rome was sent</L>
<L>In pylgremage for &thorn;e kyng also &mdash;</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;is he dede in gode entent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot quen kyng Alured had regnyd &thorn;us here</L>
<L>A-bou&yogh;te a thretty long wynter,</L>
<L N="640">He was ded and leyde on bere;</L>
<L>And buryed he was at Wynchester.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot fyue abbeys he let make</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was ded:</L>
<L>Pollesworth and Whytteby for seynt Modwynus sake,</L>
<L N="645">As ychaue ofto in story red:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e whyche dwelt seynt Ede, his aunte, y-wys,</L>
<L>Seynt Modewyne &amp; Ede &amp; Osyth y-fere;</L>
<L>Bot seynt Ede y-schryned &yogh;et &thorn;ere ys &mdash;</L>
<L>Who so wolle go &thorn;edur, may fynde hit &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="650">And &thorn;e abbay of Wyltone he made also.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e abbay of Shaftysbury also made he,</L>
<L>And &yogh;affe londys &amp; rentys gret won &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>Bycause of Ethelgore, his dou&yogh;ter free.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e vniuersyte of Oxenford forsothe he made,</L>
<L N="655">As trewe story telle&thorn; wel me;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e abbotys Neotys conselle he had</L>
<L>&thorn;at vniuersite to make w<SUP>t</SUP> lawys fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e abbey of Ethelyngiseie he let make</L>
<L>And set &thorn;er-inne monchus &thorn;o mony y-fere.</L>
<L N="660">And &thorn;e abbey of Glastynbury, as Bede dothe spake,</L>
<L>And Elfryde his dou&yogh;ter made abbas &thorn;ere. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when alle &thorn;is was &thorn;us y-wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And his sowle to heuen y-past,</L>
<L>&thorn;e crone was to his sone y-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="665">And cronede hym kynge in gret hast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when his sone was crownede kynge,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Edwardus Senior.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche was clepte Edward Seniore:</L>
<L>&thorn;e neynthe hundred &yogh;ere w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te lesynge</L>
<L>After &thorn;at god of Mary was bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="670">And regned after Alured, his fader fre,</L>
<L>Hollyche twenty wynter and fyue;</L>
<L>And fourteyn children by wyffus &thorn;re</L>
<L>Kyng Edwarde had in his lyue.
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="16"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Towns and abbeys and castels fre</L>
<L N="675">Mony one in his lyff he made.</L>
<L>A dou&yogh;ty kny&yogh;t forsothe was he</L>
<L>And in his lyffe meche worshepe hade.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He regned here in prosperite</L>
<L>&thorn;e &yogh;erys y-nombred byfore,</L>
<L N="780">And atte his day y-sette &thorn;o dyede he,</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e abbey of Wynchester his body was bore. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue I tolde &yogh;ow opynly here</L>
<L>Who was &thorn;e fyrst founder off &thorn;is abbay,</L>
<L>And why hit was made &amp; in what &yogh;ere,</L>
<L N="685">And how Elfled was ded and in what day;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wolly telle &yogh;ow forther-more</L>
<L>&thorn;e nomes of &thorn;e founders euerychon,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e mowe haue of hem knowynge &thorn;e more,</L>
<L>In &yogh;our preyours for hem &thorn;e rather to done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="690">Athelstone was Edwardys sone fyrst ybore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Athelstanus.</NOTE></L>
<L>And of alle Englonde furst kyng he was &mdash;</L>
<L>And so nasse neuer non hym bifore<MILESTONE N="202" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sey&yogh;th Hengestys and Orsus come inne by casse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e thryd founder forsothe he was</L>
<L N="695">Of &thorn;is newe y-made abbay<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. nowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And meche gode he dede to &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>As in &yogh;our Mynymentys fynd &yogh;e may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sexstene &yogh;ere he regned here kyng;</L>
<L>He was a mone of ry&yogh;t gret grace.</L>
<L N="700">&thorn;e fyrst &yogh;ere of his regnynge</L>
<L>Seynt Dunstone also ybore he was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when he had regnyde here sexstene &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>As ichaue redde in trewe story,</L>
<L>He was ded and layde one bere,</L>
<L N="705">And I-buryed at Malmesbury.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And after hym was made kyng &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Edmundus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Edmund, his halfe-brother, ywys:</L>
<L>Seuene &yogh;ere he regnede and nomo,</L>
<L>And at Glastonbury y-buryed he is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="710">Twey sones he had in hys lyffe,</L>
<L>Edwyge and Edgar, his hole brother,</L>
<L>By Eluine, his weddede wyffe &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey Regneden eyther after o&thorn;er.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Cantyrbury he come by casse:</L>
<L N="715">And &thorn;ere kyng Edmund was ded;</L>
<L>&thorn;e fourtey&thorn; founder forsothe he was,</L>
<L>As ychaue in story red.
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="17"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Edred, his hole brother, was made &thorn;o kynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Edredus.</NOTE></L>
<L>And regnede fullyche ten &yogh;ere here;</L>
<L N="720">For Edwyge nasse bot a &yogh;onge thynge &mdash;</L>
<L>His age nasnot fullyche seuene &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when ten &yogh;ere weren &thorn;us fully paste,</L>
<L>Gret sekenesse to hym come &thorn;o:</L>
<L>And after seynt Dunstone he send in haste,</L>
<L N="725">For he was his consyler and his confessor also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Dunstone hey&yogh;ede hym fulle faste</L>
<L>And &yogh;yrne to god for hym he bedde.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;e furst dayes Jurney was fulle paste,</L>
<L>An angelle hym told &thorn;at he was dede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="730">And ry&yogh;t as &thorn;at voys come to seynt Dunstone here,</L>
<L>His horse felle doune to &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>And dyede anon &thorn;o ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ony stroke, dount or wounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Donston full well knewe &thorn;o in his thou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="735">&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng was ded y-wys.</L>
<L>And to Wynchester &thorn;o was he brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e olde abbey y-buryed he ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;is kynge was &thorn;us forth paste</L>
<L>His sowle to god in trynite,</L>
<L N="740">Edwygys was made kynge &thorn;o in hast<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Edwyg<GAP> mit Schleife f&uuml;r ys; a. R. steht rex Edwicus. Bl. Edwyge.</NOTE></L>
<L>In Kyngeston, in &thorn;at gode cete.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Edwicus.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;e furst day of his crownynge</L>
<L>In to spousebreche he felle anone, &mdash;</L>
<L>And suche on he was alle his leuyng,</L>
<L N="745">For alle &thorn;at seynt Dunstone my&yogh;t done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot for seynt Dunston spake to hym &thorn;eroffe</L>
<L>And conselede hym to leue his synfulle lyffe,</L>
<L>Ou&yogh;te of his reme he hym droffe</L>
<L>In to Fraundrus, w<SUP>t</SUP> soro and stryffe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="750">Abbeys and Monchus he hatede y-wys</L>
<L>By-cause of seynt Dunstone his lore;</L>
<L>&thorn;e abbey of Malmesbury he &yogh;aff his clerkys</L>
<L>And sayde Monchus shulde dwelle &thorn;ere nomore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot by-cause of Eluine, his moder dere,</L>
<L N="755">&thorn;e abbey of Wyltone he dede encresse,</L>
<L>And so he was &thorn;e fyuethe foundere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at Abbey w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te lesse:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he confermyde holyche &thorn;erto</L>
<L>Alle thyng y-&yogh;eue byfore,</L>
<L N="760">And &yogh;affe &thorn;erto londys and rentys mo,</L>
<L>By-cause &thorn;at his fader was &thorn;ere ybore.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="18"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;en &thorn;is kynge dyede after anone:</L>
<L>He regned here bot foure &yogh;ere;</L>
<L>For god toke vengauns hym vpone</L>
<L N="765">For &thorn;e synnes &thorn;at he dede here;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He dyede sodanly for his synne,</L>
<L>And at Wynchester yburyed he was.</L>
<L>Bot seynt Dounstone to prey for hym he nolde neuer blynne,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at his soule y-dampned nasse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="770">For as sone as he was deyde,</L>
<L>Seynt Dunston knewe &thorn;at by vysyon,</L>
<L>And to god for hym so he badde<MILESTONE N="203" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at his sowle was sauyd from dampnacyone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of &thorn;is kyng speke y nomore,</L>
<L N="775">For he dyed &thorn;us, as y dede say,</L>
<L>And to Wynchester he was y-bore</L>
<L>And buryed in &thorn;at olde abbey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when Edwygys was &thorn;us ago,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Edwyg<GAP> mit Schleife f&uuml;r ys; a. R. steht rex Edwicus. Bl. Edwyge.</NOTE></L>
<L>Edgar, his brother, was made &thorn;o kynge:</L>
<L N="780">For alle Englond consentede &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>For he was a vertuose thynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sexstene wynter he was olde</L>
<L>When he was cronyd kynge,</L>
<L>Of seynt Dunstone &amp; seynt Oswolde</L>
<L N="785">Atte Bathe ysacryd, w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te lesynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e nyenthe houndryd &yogh;ere syxsty saue one</L>
<L>After &thorn;at goddus sone was ybore,</L>
<L>Edgar, &thorn;at was Edmundys &yogh;onge sone,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e kyndam of Englonde was y-core;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="790">And seyth &thorn;at &yogh;ere &thorn;at kyng Alured layde &thorn;e furste stone</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is newe abbay, &thorn;at stonte here &yogh;et,</L>
<L>Foure score &yogh;ere &amp; foure saue one</L>
<L>Ben past forthe, sey&yogh;the &thorn;at hit was sette;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seyth Egberde &amp; Elburwe, his suster, y-wys,</L>
<L N="795">Bulden vp &thorn;at religiose house y-fere,</L>
<L>Seuene score &yogh;ere &amp; sex hit is,</L>
<L>For hit nys neyther furre ne nere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sexstene wyntre &amp; more he regnyd here,</L>
<L>In gret worshep and prosperite,</L>
<L N="800">As &thorn;e trewe story wolle &yogh;ow lere;</L>
<L>An holy mon forsothe was he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For when &thorn;at chylde was bore y-wys,</L>
<L>Seynt Dunstone was at Glastynburry,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere he herde an angel say ry&yogh;t tys:</L>
<L N="805">"Now may Englonde be glad and mery!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For rest and pese shalle &thorn;erinne be</L>
<L>By alle &thorn;is kyngys tyme y-wys,</L>
<L>And holy leuyng in prosperite;</L>
<L>God hathe &thorn;at childe y-graundyd &thorn;is.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="19"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="810">And alle &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at &thorn;y lyffe doth last,</L>
<L>&thorn;e prosperite shalle neuer aslake;</L>
<L>Bot quen &thorn;y sowle to heuene ys past,</L>
<L>Meche soro shalle ben for synne sake."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>(. . . . .</L>
<L N="815">Yn hys herte he was ful glad</L>
<L>&amp; cunselyd &thorn;e &yogh;yng kyng &thorn;at he schuld not do amys</L>
<L>But loue wel god euer w<SUP>t</SUP> gode herte &amp; sad.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Where-fore so hyly encresyd &thorn;e kyng yn al godenes</L>
<L>And yn so grete prosperite encressyd al-so</L>
<L N="820">And so muche trow&thorn;e &amp; pees yn hys tyme was,</L>
<L>That no mone to o&thorn;er wulde mysdo.)</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So heylyche encresset &thorn;is kyng in alle godenesse<NOTE PLACE="foot">815-822) sind oben a. R. von &auml;hnlicher Hand nebengeschrieben; der erste Vers oben ist abge|schnitten.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="foot">819-22 sind eine Wiederholung der folg. Strophe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And in so gret prosperyte he encressed also</L>
<L>And so meche pese and trewthe in his tyme wesse,</L>
<L N="825">&thorn;at nomone to other wold mys-do</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ny in alle &thorn;e tyme of his regnynge</L>
<L>Theff ne mycher forsothe &thorn;ere nasse &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ny 1835 ny&yogh;e = nor.</NOTE></L>
<L>So monfulle he was in his gouernyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">mycher one who skulks, a thief.</NOTE></L>
<L>And so fulle of vertu and of grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="830">And also he was a fulle semely mon,</L>
<L>&thorn;awe he off stature nere not fulle hey&yogh;e, &mdash;</L>
<L>An hardyour kny&yogh;t nasse now-where non,</L>
<L>For in dedus of armys he was fulle sly&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A fulle monfulle mon, forsothe, he was,</L>
<L N="835">As by an ensampull y may &yogh;ow telle.</L>
<L>For in a tyme hit felle so by case</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of Scotlonde dud w<SUP>t</SUP> hym dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And vpone a day as he myry satte</L>
<L>In gret murthes, as y chaue redde,</L>
<L N="840">He sayde he meruaylede muche of &thorn;atte</L>
<L>&thorn;at kynge Edgar was so mechel adredde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of all men &thorn;at dweltone hym aboute,</L>
<L>Off kyng or prynce, bothe ferre or nere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. nere st. ney&yogh;e (vgl. V.931).</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at euery yle of hym hadden dou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="845">And &thorn;at homagelyche to hym &thorn;ey dedon so abey&yogh;e,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sey&yogh;t he is of stature so lyte</L>
<L>And also so &yogh;ong of age,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at men &thorn;at hadden gret dyspyte,</L>
<L>Durston donne to hym none ou&yogh;te-rage.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. doun?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="850">In maner of scorne &thorn;use wordes he sayde,</L>
<L>For to him he hadde a preuey&yogh;e enmy&yogh;e</L>
<L>And hulte hym nothynge wel a-payde</L>
<L>&thorn;at so mony kyngys dudon to hym obey&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="20"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot kyng Edgar herde sone of &thorn;at</L>
<L N="855">&thorn;at &thorn;e kyng of Scotlonde had &thorn;us y-sayde:</L>
<L>Wherfore in to a wode he hym gatte,</L>
<L>As &thorn;awe he wolde w<SUP>t</SUP> hym han playde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when he had hym in to &thorn;e wode brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And nomon w<SUP>t</SUP> hem bot &thorn;ey tweyne y-fere,</L>
<L N="860">Kyng Edgar of hym he &yogh;affe ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;aw he meche &thorn;e more mon were,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayde: "syre kyng, haue here a swerde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at of stele ry&yogh;t welle y<SUP>s</SUP> made,</L>
<L>And a-wowe now &thorn;y worde<MILESTONE N="204" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="865">&thorn;at &thorn;ow behynd me has y-sayde!<NOTE PLACE="foot">h in has &uuml;berschrieben.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here ben tweyn, chese &thorn;ow &thorn;e best,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ow schalle fy&yogh;t here, or &thorn;owe go;</L>
<L>For of vs tweyne &thorn;ow arte &thorn;e mest,</L>
<L>Bot loke who ys &thorn;e stronger of vs two."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="870">&thorn;e kyng of Scotlonde was &thorn;o alla-baysshette,</L>
<L>And felle doune anone to his fotte</L>
<L>And mercy mekelyche of hym he ayschette,</L>
<L>And sayde: "syre kynge, fy&yogh;t wolly notte,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of any worde &thorn;at ychaue sayde,</L>
<L N="875">Syre Edgar, y prey&yogh;e &yogh;ow for&yogh;eue hit me."</L>
<L>"Syre, quod Edgar, y holde me well apayde,</L>
<L>Holyche &thorn;y askyng I graunte to &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;ey paston forthe y-fere,</L>
<L>&thorn;use kyngus bothe, w<SUP>t</SUP> play and game,</L>
<L N="880">And to Edgar he swore ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nold neuer hym more blame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also in &thorn;e furst &yogh;ere of his regnynge</L>
<L>Vpone a day hit fell by case</L>
<L>&thorn;at Edgar rode ou&yogh;t on his pleyenge</L>
<L N="885">In to a forest ney&yogh;t to his place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when he come in to &thorn;at forestes syde,</L>
<L>A gret lust he had to slepe:</L>
<L>And vnder a tre he doune hym leyde.</L>
<L>A meruayle sweuene &thorn;o con he mete:<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. swenene?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="890">Hym thou&yogh;t &thorn;at his grebyche lay hym besyde</L>
<L>As gret w<SUP>t</SUP> whelp as he my&yogh;t go,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;e whelpus w<SUP>t</SUP>-in hure body in &thorn;at tyde</L>
<L>Burke fast at &thorn;e kyng &amp; hure also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hym tho&yogh;t also &thorn;at a broke by hym &thorn;ere ron</L>
<L N="895">And &thorn;at vpone &thorn;e bonke &thorn;erof an appultre stode</L>
<L>And &thorn;at twey fayre appullon crowedone &thorn;eron,<NOTE PLACE="foot">crowedone grew.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ey folle doune bothe in to &thorn;at flode;
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="21"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;use appullon were bothe y-falle<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. appullen?</NOTE></L>
<L>In to &thorn;at broke &thorn;at ron hym bysyde,</L>
<L N="900">A voys he herd &thorn;ere clepe and calle</L>
<L>And sayde: "wel &thorn;e betyde, welle &thorn;e betyde!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also he met &thorn;at a lampe so bry&yogh;t</L>
<L>Hongede an hey&yogh;e vpone &thorn;at tre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;aff a-bou&yogh;t hym so gret ley&yogh;t</L>
<L N="905">&thorn;at all &thorn;e contrey &thorn;e better my&yogh;t se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when kynge Edgare had met &thorn;is swene</L>
<L>And seye hit, hym thou&yogh;t, verely in sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He askede hys moder Eluine &thorn;e quene,</L>
<L>What &thorn;is swene signifye my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="910">"Sone, he sayde, y chulle &yogh;ow telle</L>
<L>&thorn;e significacyon of &thorn;is sweuene.</L>
<L>&thorn;use whelpus &thorn;at burken on &thorn;e so snelle</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP>-inne hure moder body, by-semene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And signifyen &thorn;at men w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t dou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="915">&thorn;at after &thorn;is tyme shulle by bore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tilge &thorn;at?</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at w<SUP>t</SUP> alle hure my&yogh;t wolle be a-bou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at holy chyrche were forlore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Her body signifyeth world, so, sire,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whelpus signifyen heretycus y-wys,</L>
<L N="920">&thorn;at wollen w<SUP>t</SUP> alle hure my&yogh;t desire</L>
<L>To peruert &thorn;e lawe, for couetyse;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey wollen desyre w<SUP>t</SUP> all hure my&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cronica Cistrensis.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle Religiose folke forto shende,</L>
<L>And haue gret how bothe day and ny&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">how care.</NOTE></L>
<L N="925">How &thorn;ey my&yogh;t best bryng hit to anynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;y-self, sone, sygnifyeth &thorn;is tre,</L>
<L>For &yogh;e shulle bryng forth fruyte of grace.</L>
<L>And &thorn;us whelpus &thorn;at borken thus at &thorn;e<NOTE PLACE="foot">tilge &thorn;at?</NOTE></L>
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP> alle her my&yogh;t do &thorn;e manasse,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="930">For relygiose heylyche &yogh;e shulle encrese</L>
<L>In al &yogh;our reme both ferre and ney&yogh;e;</L>
<L>Bot men herafter wy&thorn;-ou&yogh;t leysse</L>
<L>Whollen haue &thorn;erto fulle gret enuy&yogh;e</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And couet londys and rentys y-wys</L>
<L N="935">&thorn;at &yogh;e shull &yogh;yff to relygiose place&mdash;</L>
<L>And all &thorn;at shalle be for couetys</L>
<L>And also for defauu&yogh;te of grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot ry&yogh;t as &thorn;us whelpus mow do &yogh;ow no harme</L>
<L>Bot only stere &yogh;ow from &yogh;our rest,</L>
<L N="940">Ry&yogh;t so holy chyrche after &thorn;at starme</L>
<L>Shalle haue &thorn;e maystre atte lest.
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="22"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;us twey&yogh;e appullon, sone, also,</L>
<L>&thorn;at follen from &thorn;is tre so bleyue,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. bleyme.</NOTE></L>
<L>Signifye, my chylde, sones two</L>
<L N="945">&thorn;at &yogh;e shulle haue in &yogh;our lyue;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e ton shalle for &thorn;e to&thorn;er dye<MILESTONE N="205" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And a Martyr be y-wys,</L>
<L>And regne he shalle in heuene an hey&yogh;e;</L>
<L>And &thorn;e to&thorn;er in vrthe w<SUP>t</SUP> lytyl peys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="950">Bot he &thorn;at &thorn;is voys spake to &thorn;o (!) &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;o st. &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Welle &thorn;e betyde, welle &thorn;e be-tyde",</L>
<L>Shalle regne here and in heuene blys</L>
<L>And in &thorn;at Joye euer abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e lamp, sone, &thorn;at is so bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="955">Signifyeth a dou&yogh;ter &thorn;at &yogh;e shall haue,</L>
<L>&thorn;at shall serue god bothe day &amp; ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And clene mayde hure body saue;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ry&yogh;t as &thorn;is lampe &yogh;efth gret ly&yogh;t</L>
<L>To euery creature abou&yogh;t hit dwellynge,</L>
<L N="960">Ry&yogh;t so shall he &yogh;eue to euerry wey&yogh;t</L>
<L>Gret ensampull of gode leuyng."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;e quene had &thorn;us ysayde</L>
<L>And expoundyd &thorn;is sweuene ry&yogh;t tys,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng hulte hym well a-payde</L>
<L N="965">And mekelyche thongede &thorn;e kyng of blys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng lay at Shaftusbury &thorn;o,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e story telleth welle me.</L>
<L>Bot to Wynchester he tho&yogh;t to go,</L>
<L>Forto vysidete &thorn;at contre:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="970">And toke his Jerney and forth con past</L>
<L>To-warde Wynchester, &thorn;at fayre cyte,</L>
<L>And come to Wyltone at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L>And a newe fayre chirche &thorn;ere sawe he;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he was &thorn;ere vpone &thorn;e doune,</L>
<L N="975">&thorn;at chirche was lufty in his sy&yogh;t;</L>
<L>He thou&yogh;t he wolde go doun to toune</L>
<L>And soiorne &thorn;ere he thou&yogh;t alle ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hym he toke a preuey mayneye</L>
<L>And to-warde &thorn;at chirche full sone he went,</L>
<L N="980">For to se &thorn;at feyre abbey</L>
<L>And offerre &thorn;ere in gode entent.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot to &thorn;at chirche when he come was,</L>
<L>Vp to &thorn;e auter he went anone an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere was made a ryal place</L>
<L N="985">In &thorn;e worshepe of owre lady&yogh;e.
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="23"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Religiose wymmen &thorn;o dweltone &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. wymnen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sacryd maydenys and sustren y-fere,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ong maydenys, of boke to lere;</L>
<L>&thorn;ay welcomeden &thorn;e kyng w<SUP>t</SUP> ry&yogh;t gret chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="990">Bot &thorn;e kyng couetede &thorn;o of hem anone</L>
<L>To see hure fayre place w<SUP>t</SUP>-Inne</L>
<L>And in to here cloystre w<SUP>t</SUP> hem to gone.</L>
<L>Mekelyche &thorn;e maydenys grauntede hym &thorn;onne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;enne?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; in to here cloystre &thorn;ey hym brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="995">&amp; after in to &thorn;e fraytre &thorn;o come he;</L>
<L>&thorn;us maydenys mekelyche &thorn;o hym be-sou&yogh;t</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hem to take &thorn;ere charyte.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Legenda sce Edithe.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng was meke and gentyl ywys</L>
<L>And grauntede &thorn;us maydenys alle hure wylle;</L>
<L N="1000">And to &thorn;e meyte now set he is,</L>
<L>And meyte &amp; drynk was brou&yogh;t hym tylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of hem &thorn;at seruede hym at &thorn;e borde</L>
<L>In &thorn;e story ys made no mensyone,</L>
<L>Ny of non other I speke no worde</L>
<L N="1005">Bot of &thorn;e mayden &thorn;at red &thorn;e lessone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For at &thorn;e lectron a mayde satte,</L>
<L>Wltrud was &thorn;at maydonus name,</L>
<L>A barones dou&yogh;ter for sothe was &thorn;at</L>
<L>&amp; a maydene of ry&yogh;t gode fame;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1010">&thorn;at mayden red &thorn;at lesson &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Whyle &thorn;e kyng was atte mete.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng toke ry&yogh;t gode hed &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>For hure voys was bothe myelde &amp; swete,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An angelys voys hym thou&yogh;t hit was:</L>
<L N="1015">And loke vp &thorn;at mayden vpone,</L>
<L>&amp; for alle here veyle he sey&yogh;e here face&mdash;</L>
<L>A feyrer hym thou&yogh;t he sawe neuer none.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so he thou&yogh;t in his hert &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at he was a semely thynge;</L>
<L N="1020">And askede what kynradone he was come fro,</L>
<L>And also of here gode gouernynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"A Barones dou&yogh;ter, my lorde, was he,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was a kny&yogh;t of ry&yogh;t gode fame</L>
<L>And dwelte here in &thorn;is countre,</L>
<L N="1025">Syre Godwyn was &thorn;at kny&yogh;tis name.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here fader ys dede, here moder also,</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayden here w<SUP>t</SUP> vs dothe dwelle,</L>
<L>To serue god here, as we shulle do;</L>
<L>Hit is holyche, my lorde, hure wylle.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="24"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1030">Forsothe y-sacryd he nysnot &yogh;et</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inter">Hier fehlt eine Lage von 12 foll. (c. 980 V.). (Diese 12 foll. enthielten die Liebe Edgar's u. Wultrud, die Geburt der Edith, die Busse des K&ouml;nigs u. der Heiligen, Jugend u. Erziehung Editha's.)</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>And bedon here loue entyerlyche god aboue<MILESTONE N="206" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&amp; all crystone creaturis for his loue, bothe more &amp; lesse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey tau&yogh;tone Woltrud here moder also,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was euermore &thorn;at mayde by</L>
<L N="1035">&amp; toke ry&yogh;t gode hede &thorn;er-to</L>
<L>&amp; lyff euer full vertuosely.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;e gouernyl &thorn;ey token hem to,</L>
<L>&thorn;e moder &amp; &thorn;e dou&yogh;ter y-fere.</L>
<L>&YOGH;et was &thorn;e dou&yogh;ter &thorn;e parfitor of hem two,</L>
<L N="1040">&YOGH;yff ony of hem parfitor were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Euery ny&yogh;t w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t lesynge,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at mateynes weron ydo,</L>
<L>He chaysteyssede hure body w<SUP>t</SUP> displynynge</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> mony a nother afflixione mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1045">&amp; after when &thorn;e day con sprynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyndam of heuene he sou&yogh;t fyrst,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> meke preyeres to heuene kynge,</L>
<L>In whyche was alle hure tryst.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when he had done alle hure seruyse</L>
<L N="1050">&thorn;at ou&yogh;t to be done w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;e chirche,</L>
<L>As gladsome as &thorn;aw he had come ou&yogh;t of paradys</L>
<L>He come forthe, other thyngus to wyrche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; as besy he was in alle thyng</L>
<L>To serue hure sustren w<SUP>t</SUP> alle mekenes,</L>
<L N="1055">As was Martha or Mary in herre seruynge</L>
<L>To Jhesu goddis sone, kyng of grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he couetede neuer in no wyse</L>
<L>To be worshepud for here hey&yogh;e lynage,</L>
<L>Bot euer to be meke in lowe seruyse,</L>
<L N="1060">For all to mekenes was here currage;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; couetede to serue god to plesyng,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms plesyng st. plesans.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; to hurre sustren alle y-fere,</L>
<L>He dud hem to plese alle diligens,</L>
<L>As &thorn;aw he had take of hem gret hyre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1065">So louyng &amp; so lowelyche he was y-wys</L>
<L>To euery crystone creture,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nolde neuer do to hem a-mys,</L>
<L>In worde ny dede, ny dishonour.
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And meyte and drynke he wold hem &yogh;eue,</L>
<L N="1070">For grace w<SUP>t</SUP> hure was euer y-nowe &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;aw he &yogh;aff meche, y-nowe &yogh;et dud leue;</L>
<L>&amp; euery mon to hurre for here godnes drowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So vertuoselyche hurre lyff he ladde</L>
<L>&amp; so furforthe he was forthe-fulte w<SUP>t</SUP> goddis grace,</L>
<L N="1075">&thorn;at euery mone of here Joy hadde</L>
<L>&amp; desyred to see here semely face.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What for here deseruynge &amp; hurre lynage,</L>
<L>Duke, Errelle &amp; eke Barone</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> all hurre faderes holle barnage</L>
<L N="1080">Putten hem-self vnder here subiectione.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And alle &thorn;e reme of Englond, bounde &amp; fre,</L>
<L>Sayden &thorn;at he was worthy to bene a quene;</L>
<L>&amp; quene of Fraunce he my&yogh;t han be,</L>
<L>Bot he nolde neuer consent to bene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1085">&thorn;ere nas no crystone kyng ny emperour,</L>
<L>Bysshop ny legate ny cardinalle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey nadde hure in gret honour,</L>
<L>&amp; herre owne suster &thorn;ey deden here calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also &thorn;e pope, I vnderstonde,</L>
<L N="1090">&thorn;at was pope of Rome &thorn;o,</L>
<L>To hure send lettre in to Englonde</L>
<L>&amp; his blessyng w<SUP>t</SUP> hem also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of worldelyche worshepe he toke none hedde,</L>
<L>Bot to serue god was alle here &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1095">&amp; &thorn;e pore and &thorn;e maymot forto clothe and fede &mdash;</L>
<L>Of o&thorn;er wordelyche honour &yogh;aff he ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For leuer here was &thorn;e pore to fede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e maymot, &thorn;e seke to wasshe &amp; hele,</L>
<L>&amp; blynd la&yogh;erus &amp; croked in chirche to lede</L>
<L N="1100">&amp; from &thorn;e deyth to saue ry&yogh;t fele,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en to han ben emperys of Rome</L>
<L>&amp; bore &thorn;e corone of ony hey&yogh;e astate,</L>
<L>Or ellus quene of ony kyndome &mdash;</L>
<L>So meke and humble he was algate.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1105">&amp; euer he was fulle redy<MILESTONE N="207" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To help ychemon in his nede;</L>
<L>&amp; theuys y-dampnyde for felony</L>
<L>From &thorn;e Galoys he wolde hem lede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To hurre fader he wolde ofto knele</L>
<L N="1110">Vpone here knen doune to &thorn;e grounde,</L>
<L>&amp; dampnyd men he sauede fele,</L>
<L>&thorn;aw &thorn;ey weron dampnyd in &thorn;at stounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For here fader was ry&yogh;twys to forthfulle &thorn;e lawe</L>
<L>&thorn;orw-ou&yogh;t alle his reme y-wys;</L>
<L N="1115">Bot he nolde haue nomon y-slawe,</L>
<L>For he was so mercyfulle &amp; so pytewys;
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot euer when ony mon dude on-mys,</L>
<L>He wolde hit amend w<SUP>t</SUP> alle hure my&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L>So graciose &amp; so godelyche he was y-wys</L>
<L N="1120">&thorn;at hurre wylle was alle wrongus to a-ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ychemone &amp; woman louede here fulle welle;</L>
<L>&amp; wylde bestes &amp; folys of fly&yogh;t</L>
<L>To here clepynge wolde come fulle snelle</L>
<L>&amp; at hurre byddyng &thorn;ei wolde doun ly&yogh;t</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1125">&amp; of hurre hond &thorn;ey wolde meyte take.</L>
<L>Bot dowuys of briddis he louede most</L>
<L>&amp; greste chere to hem wolde make,</L>
<L>By-cause &thorn;ey ben legenyd to &thorn;e holy gost.<NOTE PLACE="foot">legenyd = lykened.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For euer he bare in hert fulle stylle</L>
<L N="1130">&thorn;e gospelle of &thorn;e vtaus of &thorn;e towolthe-day</L>
<L>How &thorn;e holy gost spake seynt Jon tylle</L>
<L>"&thorn;is is my sone", &thorn;e fader dede fay;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For in a dowue likenes he come doune when he spake &mdash;</L>
<L>Jhesu goddys sone was y-folwyd ry&yogh;t &thorn;o;</L>
<L N="1135">"&thorn;is is my sone", &thorn;e fader &thorn;o sayde, "to hym hede take,</L>
<L>For he shalle brynge monys sowle from wo".</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;e cause &thorn;at he louede coleron so welle,</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;ey weron so meke also;</L>
<L>Also, when he hem clepte, &thorn;ey wolde fulle snelle</L>
<L N="1140">Ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e eyer com flee hurre to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Also wylde bestus obeyden hem so louelyche to &thorn;is mayde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ei wolden take meyte at hurre honde</L>
<L>Mekelyche and hendlyche, as y &yogh;ow sayde;</L>
<L>And when he hem bedde, styll &thorn;ey wolde stonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1145">Also for loue of Helie &thorn;e prophet, y-wys,</L>
<L>Rafenys he wolde kepe &amp; oft hem fede,</L>
<L>&amp; for his loue had hem in gret cherysshenys &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">cherysshenys = cherishness.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;us parfite he was in yche gode dede &mdash;:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For when &thorn;at holy profet Helye Tesbitem</L>
<L N="1150">Flow away from Achab, &thorn;at was &thorn;o kynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Tesbitem Beiname des Elias.</NOTE></L>
<L>Rafenys bredde &amp; fleysshe &thorn;ey brou&yogh;t hym</L>
<L>Bothe on &yogh;euen and in &thorn;e morouynge. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He was so vertuose &amp; so fulle of grace</L>
<L>&amp; so meche godenesse he had in herre delyte,</L>
<L N="1155">&thorn;at y naue nouther wytte ny space</L>
<L>All here godenesse forto wryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Here voys was fulle clere in syngynge,</L>
<L>&amp; wryte he couthe &amp; purtrey also,</L>
<L>Fulle parfite he was in selke worchynge,</L>
<L N="1160">&amp; fulle welle enbroudre &amp; leyge golde &thorn;erto.<NOTE PLACE="foot">leyge = lay.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="27"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tunyculus &amp; chesepulus he made mony one</L>
<L>&amp; mantillus, enbroudrid w<SUP>t</SUP> golde fulle redde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. wykens.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; mitrus y-cowchud w<SUP>t</SUP> mony a ryalle ston;</L>
<L>Bot of worldlyche clothus of pryde he ne toke hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1165">Worldelyche clothus he wolde none worche</L>
<L>To fader ny brother by no maner wey,</L>
<L>Bot in plesaunce of god &amp; holy chirche</L>
<L>Fast he wolde worche euery dey.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dey mit a &uuml;ber e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Harp he couthe &amp; syng welle &thorn;erto,</L>
<L N="1170">&amp; carff welle ymagus, &amp; peyntede bothe &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche virtuose werkus he wolde welle do</L>
<L>Fulle sotelyche w<SUP>t</SUP>-owte ony wothe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of here virtuose worchyng, as y sayde ere,</L>
<L>Ynam not sufficiant to wryte here alle;</L>
<L N="1175">Wherfore &thorn;eroff to speke ychulle steynte here,</L>
<L>&amp; som-what how he lyuede, &yogh;ow telle y schalle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For fulle parfite he was in herre leuynge,</L>
<L>&amp; gret penaunce vpon herre he toke;</L>
<L>Bot euer he louede ouer alle thynge</L>
<L N="1180">To rede and syng vpon here boke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ofto he fast &amp; lytull he ete,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et euery ny&yogh;t he wolde vp ryse &mdash;</L>
<L>He faylede neuer bot &yogh;yff he were seke<MILESTONE N="208" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ony ny&yogh;t from hurre seruyse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1185">A bedde he hadde ry&yogh;t welle y-dy&yogh;t</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> ryche clothus of ry&yogh;t gode aray,</L>
<L>Bot seldon he lay &thorn;ere-in ony ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot on an harde borde welle ofter he lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He went y-clothud fulle honestly</L>
<L N="1190">In ryalle clothyng to yche monus sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot an harde hayre fulle securlye</L>
<L>Was nexst here fleysshe both day and ny&yogh;t;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is hard hayre he wered hurre body nexst</L>
<L>Vnder a curtull of purpur byse</L>
<L N="1195">Enbroudrid w<SUP>t</SUP> golde, as saythe &thorn;e text,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> other clothus aboue &thorn;at were of gretter pryse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fulle honestlyche euer he went y-cladde</L>
<L>In blake clothyng, hurre ordur leyke,</L>
<L>Bot in gret mekenesse hurre lyff he ladde,</L>
<L N="1200">In lowe seruyse to euery mon, bothe hole &amp; seke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot seynt Adelwolde, &thorn;at holy mone,</L>
<L>Spake to &thorn;at mayde vpon a day</L>
<L>&amp; sayde &thorn;at he herde neuer of non</L>
<L>&thorn;at went to Paradys one &thorn;at aray;
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1205">"Ny &thorn;y heuenelyche spouse, dou&yogh;ter, quod he,</L>
<L>Delytede hym neuer &yogh;et in suche clethynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. clothynge?</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot in lowenesse, in mekenesse &amp; in charite,</L>
<L>&amp; not in ryalte of clothus weryng."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at mayde mekelyche ouswered hym &thorn;o</L>
<L N="1210">&amp; sayde: "holy fader, vnder suche clothus of honeste,</L>
<L>&yogh;yf hit were plesyng to &yogh;ov to take hede &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>Mowe ben virtwys werkus gret pleynte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fader, wher &thorn;e holy gost wolnot as gladlyche wone</L>
<L>Vnder a mantyl y-furned w<SUP>t</SUP> beuer ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L N="1215">And w<SUP>t</SUP> as gode wylle take &thorn;ere his habitacyon,</L>
<L>As vnder a mantyl y-furned w<SUP>t</SUP> a row gotus felle?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu, holy fader, &thorn;at vs dere bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Take not only hede to monnys clothynge,</L>
<L>Bot also to bothe his hert &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1220">&amp; also to his gode worchynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y chaue my lord god in my &thorn;ou&yogh;t as redy</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;enk vpon his gret passione both ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP> as gode wylle y cholde hym seruy,</L>
<L>As &thorn;aw y were arayed in ry&yogh;t pore aray."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1225">When &thorn;is holy mayde had &thorn;us y-sayde</L>
<L>&amp; mekelyche to hym &thorn;is tale y-tolde,</L>
<L>&thorn;is holy bysshop holde hym ry&yogh;t welle apayde</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;onkede &thorn;erfore god mony a folde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; lette &thorn;e grace of god w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne here worche</L>
<L N="1230">After his owne graciose wille;</L>
<L>Knowyng &thorn;at he loued better god &amp; holy chirche</L>
<L>&thorn;en ony wordelyche ryche appayreylle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; leuer he had, as &thorn;ey trowedone ychone,</L>
<L>To sytte vpon a matte of &thorn;e Angoras</L>
<L N="1235">&thorn;at for seynt Paules loue was y-closud in stone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">angoras = anchoress.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;en to haue ben duchasse, quene or Emperas. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Jhesu, what is mekenesse &amp; lowenesse worthy</L>
<L>To euery mon and woman &thorn;at leuys here,</L>
<L>Seythe allmyghty god in heuene an hey&yogh;e</L>
<L N="1240">Hath had hit euer in so gret chere!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of alle &thorn;e virtwys &thorn;at euer mon wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Mekenes is best &amp; most worthy;</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mekenes god monnys sowle hath bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>By-cause of mekenes he was y-bore of owre lady.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1245">&thorn;er nys non virtwe &thorn;at god louythe more</L>
<L>&thorn;en mekenes, whoso wolle take hede;</L>
<L>By-cause of pryde monnys sawle was lore,</L>
<L>Tylle goddus sone was for vs dede.
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="29"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore we shulde loue hit most &amp; lest,</L>
<L N="1250">Seythe hit is cause of alle honeste.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at god of alle virtwys louythe hit best,</L>
<L>By &thorn;is ensampulle &yogh;e mowe wel y-see</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at he preysede his owne modur ouer alle thynge,</L>
<L>As we redon in &thorn;e psalme of Magnificat,</L>
<L N="1255">For hurre mekenes &amp; lowe berynge;</L>
<L>&amp; for &thorn;at euer-lastyng worshepe he hath,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; bare &thorn;e sone of god most of my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Mekenesse was &thorn;e first cause &thorn;erof y-wys</L>
<L>&thorn;at he is made quene of heuene so bry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1260">&amp; dwellud &thorn;ere w<SUP>t</SUP> here sone in blys. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So falle hit by &thorn;is mayden, seynt Ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at mekenes &amp; lowenes dud hurre so encresse</L>
<L>&thorn;at in hurre lyffe, as we done rede,<MILESTONE N="209" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Gret miracles he dud &thorn;oro goddys grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1265">Of &thorn;e whyche on ychull &yogh;ov now telle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sothe as y fynd in story y-wryte,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e cas euery dele ry&yogh;t as hit felle,</L>
<L>To &yogh;ow &thorn;at lustenyth hit to wete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A mayde he hadde in a tyme in here seruyse,</L>
<L N="1270">&thorn;at kepte hurre clothus, here chambur also:</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche had brou&yogh;t &thorn;at Abbay in to gret deseysse,</L>
<L>Nad god hym-self take hede &thorn;at tyme &thorn;erto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For in a ny&yogh;t hit fell &thorn;at tyme by casse</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e cerge &thorn;at stode bryngnyng &thorn;at auter by,</L>
<L N="1275">&thorn;is mayde toke hit &thorn;o from &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&amp; blewe ou&yogh;t &thorn;e ley&yogh;t anone sodanly &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e weke hulte stylle &thorn;e snytte.</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayde hey&yogh;ede fulle fast &thorn;o a-way</L>
<L>&amp; sodenlyche in to &thorn;at wyche hit putte</L>
<L N="1280">Wherenne seynt Edys clothys &thorn;o lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e snotte fast brende, &thorn;e clothys cau&yogh;t hete</L>
<L>&amp; by-gonne to brenne ful fast.</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayde layde herre doune to slepe,</L>
<L>Bot sone after he rosse vp sore agast:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1285">For when he begon to slombre &amp; slepe,</L>
<L>&thorn;e flauour of &thorn;at feyre he tastede sone,</L>
<L>&amp; vp he starte &amp; begon to crye &amp; wepe &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e ladyes werone a-slepe &thorn;o euerychone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e feyre a-bou&yogh;t &thorn;e auter gon brenne</L>
<L N="1290">Alle &thorn;e clothus fulle sone a-way.</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayde to &thorn;e wyche dud fast renne</L>
<L>&thorn;ere as seynt Edys clothus &thorn;o lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e ladyes a-wokon &amp; reson vp fast,</L>
<L>&thorn;e feyre woxe euer more &amp; more;</L>
<L N="1295">&thorn;e ladyes werone alle fulle sore agast,</L>
<L>For drede leste &thorn;ey weron for-lore.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="30"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey besedone hem fast &thorn;is feyre to quenche,</L>
<L>Euery lady w<SUP>t</SUP> alle hurrc my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot euer to god cryede &thorn;at wenche</L>
<L N="1300">To stanche &thorn;at feyre &thorn;at was so ley&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at wyche nasnot brende neuer a delle,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e feyre brende fast alle a-bou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Seynt Ede hurre-self he stod fulle stylle</L>
<L>&amp; of goddes help he nad no dou&yogh;te;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1305">Sayenge w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e prophet on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;yff god hym-selff kepe &thorn;e cyte welle,</L>
<L>Cyte &amp; keperus &amp; alle y-fere</L>
<L>To nou&yogh;t shalle fall euery delle;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; sayde: "lord god, &yogh;yff hit be &thorn;i wylle,</L>
<L N="1310">Stawnche &thorn;is feyre, lord Jhesu, y prey nowe &thorn;e,</L>
<L>At &thorn;yn owne lust, for &thorn;at is skylle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle thyng euer y-do be."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o feyre staunchede &thorn;o after anone</L>
<L>&thorn;orow &thorn;e grace of goddus my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1315">&amp; more harme hit nathe not done,</L>
<L>Bot stanchede anone &thorn;o &amp; left his ly&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is holy mayde stode &amp; by-hulte</L>
<L>How hurre clothus lye vndur hurre fote</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e gledys alle by-swulte,</L>
<L N="1320">Bot he set not by &thorn;at leste a mote;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot onlyche on god was all hurre truste</L>
<L>&amp; on his godenesse he &thorn;ou&yogh;t welle more</L>
<L>&thorn;en in alle &thorn;e to&thorn;er worldelyche burste</L>
<L>Or in ony o&thorn;er gode &thorn;at was &thorn;ere lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1325">Bot hurre mayde come forthe &thorn;o, sore wepynge,</L>
<L>When he sawe &thorn;at clothyng in suche aray,</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e feyre so leygynge</L>
<L>&thorn;e mantyl &thorn;at was furnyd w<SUP>t</SUP> puryd gray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot to &thorn;at mantyl sone he rau&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1330">&thorn;at was welle furnyde, as y sayde ere,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> here honde vp hit cau&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot sone after &thorn;at he chanchede here chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For when he hadde lokede &thorn;is mantylle vpone</L>
<L>&amp; shakede of &thorn;e gledys all by-dene,</L>
<L N="1335">&amp; sawe welle &thorn;at harme hit hadde &thorn;o none,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&amp; st. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>For god had hym kepte allone;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. allone st. al clene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He sayde &thorn;o: "low, here is a wonder thynge!</L>
<L>Lo wheche a marfaylle god hathe here wrou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Y thonk now heyly god, heuene kynge,</L>
<L N="1340">Off &yogh;owre gode, ma dame, is brenne ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="210" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot clene y-kepte lo hit is now here</L>
<L>&thorn;oro goddus grace &amp; his hey&yogh;e my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Y-blessud be &yogh;e, my lady so dure,</L>
<L>For for &yogh;ow &thorn;is miracle is do here &thorn;is ny&yogh;t."
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="31"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1345">&thorn;e ladyes comen rennynge &thorn;o on yche a syde,</L>
<L>To se &thorn;e myracle &thorn;at &thorn;ere was y-do;</L>
<L>&thorn;e furnyd mantylle &thorn;e mayde forth &thorn;o leyde</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e to&thorn;er clothus w<SUP>t</SUP> hit also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e pepulle &thorn;at sey &thorn;at sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1350">Anon &thorn;ey felle doune to &thorn;e grounde</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ongedone heylyche god of my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; also seynt Ede in &thorn;at stounde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; saydon: "lo lo, mayden fulle of grace,</L>
<L>Whyche a myracle god hath y-don here for &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1355">Ry&yogh;t now here in &thorn;is same place,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;e peple mow welle y-see."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ede stode stylle &amp; sayde ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ongede god onlyche of his grace,</L>
<L>&amp; dred &thorn;us laudable wordus more in hure &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1360">&thorn;en all &thorn;e feyre &thorn;at &thorn;ere by-fore was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is whyche &thorn;at ny&yogh;e was &thorn;ere brende,</L>
<L>In witnesse of &thorn;e gret miracle &thorn;at &thorn;ere was do</L>
<L>A lowe in to &thorn;e bouke of &thorn;e chirche was sende<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. of &thorn;e &thorn;e. Nach 1363 fehlt ein Vers.</NOTE></L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1365">&thorn;at euery mon my&yogh;t ry&yogh;t welle see</L>
<L>&thorn;at god hym-self had done &thorn;at myracle dede</L>
<L>For loue of &thorn;at mayde &thorn;at was so fre</L>
<L>&amp; so parfite in yche gode dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is miracle was do &thorn;us as ychaue sayde,</L>
<L N="1370">&amp; more marfeyllogur &thorn;en y telle cone,</L>
<L>By-cause of seynt Ede, &thorn;at holy mayde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche god louede &amp; euery mone. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &yogh;et for &thorn;is mayden &amp; for here moder y-fere</L>
<L>Sone after &thorn;is a no&thorn;er miracle god dud &yogh;et worche &mdash;</L>
<L N="1375">Ry&yogh;t as hit was y-done, ychulle &yogh;ow lere,</L>
<L>&amp; how hit by-felle ry&yogh;t in &thorn;is chirche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At Triuer by-&yogh;ond &thorn;e gret flodde<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at ys y-clepud &thorn;e water of Ryne,</L>
<L>Was made an abbay ryche and gode</L>
<L N="1380">In &thorn;e worshepe of seynt Paulyne;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And Dan Benne was chanone of &thorn;at abbay,</L>
<L>&thorn;at techer of &thorn;is mayde was, as yche vnderstonde.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere was a relyke ryche &amp; gay</L>
<L>&thorn;at was y-brou&yogh;t from &thorn;e holy londe:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1385">A particul of a naylle, forsothe, hit was,</L>
<L>&thorn;is relyke &thorn;at y spake of byfore,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e whyche Jhesu was y-naylled to &thorn;e crasse</L>
<L>To saue monkynd &thorn;at was forlore.
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="32"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; Woltrud &amp; hurre dou&yogh;ter y-fere</L>
<L N="1390">Desireden heylyche bothe day &amp; ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>To haue som part of &thorn;at preciose tresere,</L>
<L>Hit forto honour w<SUP>t</SUP> alle her my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; to Dan Benne fulle ofto con &thorn;ey speke</L>
<L>To go to &thorn;e abbot &amp; to &thorn;e couent,</L>
<L N="1395">To byche hem somme particulle of &thorn;at releke;</L>
<L>&amp; two &thorn;owsonde shyllyngus by hym &thorn;ey sent,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To byche hem somme &thorn;erof, &yogh;yf &thorn;at he my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; so he dude, &amp; sped ry&yogh;t welle;</L>
<L>A litulle particulle sone after he hem dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1400">&amp; closede hit w<SUP>t</SUP>-in a cresce cristelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; to Wyltone anone he hit brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He brou&yogh;t &thorn;at ryche relyke in to &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was muche derre y-bou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;en &thorn;e Juys bou&yogh;t god of Judas.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1405">Bot when seynt Adelwolde herd of &thorn;is</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is releke was &thorn;edur y-brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To Wylton anon &thorn;o come he y-wys</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> myelde wordus &thorn;at ladyes bysou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">ladyes ist &uuml;ber eine Rasur geschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;erof to hym somme part to &yogh;eue,</L>
<L N="1410">&YOGH;yff hit were here gode wylle.</L>
<L>&thorn;us ladyes weron lothe hym to greue,</L>
<L>&amp; alle his askyng &thorn;ey grauntede hym tylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is releke was sone y-brou&yogh;t forthe &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; vpone &thorn;e auter hit was y-leyde;</L>
<L N="1415">&amp; a chalys was brou&yogh;t &thorn;edur anone also,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was made of golde so rede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a file to file &thorn;is nayle a-two.<MILESTONE N="211" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;at nayle a prest toke &thorn;o in honde &mdash;</L>
<L>A&yogh;eynes euone when heuesong was do,</L>
<L N="1420">&thorn;ey dedon &thorn;is werke, y vnderstonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is prest bygon and filede ry&yogh;t fast,</L>
<L>Tylle he some part a-wey &thorn;erof hadde.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ey byholden &amp; seyen &thorn;o at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>How fast &amp; &yogh;erne &thorn;at nayle bledde;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1425">&amp; leke as god was on &thorn;e cresse,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey syen as &thorn;aw his wondys dud blede</L>
<L>Into &thorn;e chaleys, wt-ou&yogh;t lesse,</L>
<L>Tyll hit was fulle of blode fulle rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;ey seyn &thorn;is merfeyle sy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1430">And sey&yogh;e verylyche &thorn;at hit was so,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey cryede god mercy alle &thorn;at ny&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L>And meraclelyche god toke hede &thorn;erto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;e prest sey&yogh;e &thorn;e nayle blede so,</L>
<L>He ron awey &thorn;o anone &mdash; so sore he was agast.</L>
<L N="1435">&amp; &thorn;e bysshappe and &thorn;use ladyes were sore a-ferde also,</L>
<L>And towarde hurre chamburs &thorn;ey went fulle fast.
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And weron in soro &amp; penaunce alle &thorn;at ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; preydene mekelyche to god &amp; seynt Ede</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden &thorn;oro here grace &amp; here my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1440">Fore-&yogh;eue hem &thorn;at gret mysdede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e mortyde &thorn;o, whenne hit was day,</L>
<L>To &thorn;at auter &thorn;ey hey&yogh;edone fulle fast:</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at nayle alle-hole in &thorn;e chalys &thorn;o lay;</L>
<L>&thorn;at blode was clene to heuene vp past.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1445">And alle &thorn;e mynyssionys of &thorn;at nayle</L>
<L>&thorn;at weron fyled of &thorn;at nayle w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e file,</L>
<L>Weron foudryd fast a&yogh;ayne w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ony fayle,</L>
<L>Sadelyche y-nowe w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ony gyle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;e nayle was as hole as hit was here,</L>
<L N="1450">And &thorn;e blode was clene y-past a-way also. &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey &thorn;ongedone god hey&yogh;elyche &thorn;o alle y-fere</L>
<L>For &thorn;at miracle &thorn;at was &thorn;us &thorn;ere y-do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;at nayle was halff y-fylyd a-two</L>
<L>Ouer euone, or &thorn;ey sye first &thorn;at sye&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="1455">Bot othemorwyn hit was alle-hole to-gedur y-go<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;oro goddus grace &amp; &thorn;orow his my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;ere was no-thyng senene y-wys</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e trace &thorn;at &thorn;e prest had w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e fyle y-made,</L>
<L>Bot alle-hole to-gedur y-closod a&yogh;eyne hit is.</L>
<L N="1460">Bot &thorn;o weron &thorn;use ladyes in hert fulle glad</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is nayle was &thorn;us alle-hole a&yogh;ayn</L>
<L>As &thorn;aw &thorn;e file had nothynge y-do &thorn;erto;</L>
<L>No wonder hit nas &thorn;aw &thorn;ey weron fayne</L>
<L>&thorn;at god wolde for hem suche miracles do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1465">&thorn;en was &thorn;e bysshop fulle sore a-drede</L>
<L>Lest he hadde displesid god w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;is dede,</L>
<L>And mekelyche for-&yogh;euenesse of hym he bedde,</L>
<L>&amp; also of seynt Woltrud &amp; of seynt Ede,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; sayde: "deytron, ycham fulle heuy</L>
<L N="1470">Bothe in hert and eke in mode</L>
<L>&thorn;at y nam not so worthy</L>
<L>To haue ony part of &thorn;is releke so gowde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;t he dud in his hert anone &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at Woltrud &amp; mayden Ede, herre dou&yogh;ter so fre,</L>
<L N="1475">Meche more skylle hadden &thorn;en he &thorn;is releke to</L>
<L>And better weron by-loued w<SUP>t</SUP> gode &thorn;en was he;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;ou&yogh;t how &thorn;ey hadden payde &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>&amp; how gret tryst &amp; loue &thorn;ey hadden &thorn;ere-Inne:</L>
<L>Wherfore he desyride &thorn;erofe for drede nomore,</L>
<L N="1480">Bot dred left his desyre were to hym gret synne;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; knewe welle &thorn;at &thorn;us holy wymmennus wylle nas not &thorn;erto</L>
<L>&thorn;at he ony thyng of &thorn;at preciose releke shulle haue,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf &thorn;ey hadde wyst ony o&thorn;er wyse to do</L>
<L>And herre worshepe and his loue to saue.
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="34"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1485">&amp; anone &thorn;o he let &thorn;is miracle &thorn;ere wryte,</L>
<L>In memory to haue hit for euer-more,</L>
<L>To haue god &thorn;e more in mynd &amp; &thorn;e feynde in despyte;</L>
<L>&amp; blessede &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at euer &thorn;use wymmen weron bore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And toke his leue &amp; past his wey</L>
<L N="1490">Toward Wynchestre, &thorn;at fayre cyte,</L>
<L>&amp; thongede god &yogh;erne bothe ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>For &thorn;is miracle &thorn;at was don &thorn;ere for &thorn;us ladyes fre;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; knewe welle in his herte &thorn;o y-wys</L>
<L>&thorn;at god loued &thorn;us lady ry&yogh;t entierly,<MILESTONE N="212" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1495">When he wolde kepe &thorn;is releke to hem &thorn;ys</L>
<L>&amp; for hem do &thorn;at miracle so openly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is miracle was at &thorn;is tyme &thorn;us y-do<NOTE PLACE="marg">Legenda Edithae.</NOTE></L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;is holy bysshop seynt Adelwolde;</L>
<L>God dede hit for loue of &thorn;us ladyes two,</L>
<L N="1500">&amp; mony won mo, whose wolle by-holde. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche an other &yogh;et y chulle &yogh;ow telle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>As y in story y-writone haue sey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;e very trewthe ry&yogh;t as hit by-felle,</L>
<L>In Wyltone in seynt Ede abbey&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1505">Euer hoe vsed where-euer hoe went,</L>
<L>In yche werk &thorn;at hoe wrou&yogh;t, erlyche or late,</L>
<L>To blesse hit &amp; here-self in gode entent,</L>
<L>&thorn;e feyndis power so forto &thorn;ere-w<SUP>t</SUP> abate.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot vpon a day hit byfelle ry&yogh;t thys</L>
<L N="1510">&thorn;at &thorn;is holy mayde &amp; virgyne seynt Ede</L>
<L>had y-don meyte in a dysshe,</L>
<L>Pore men &thorn;er-w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;ere to fede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; forth w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at meyte he went fulle tyde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyde = tyte.</NOTE></L>
<L>To seche a pore creture.</L>
<L N="1515">Bot a &yogh;ong chylde-mon come renne a-syde,</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;is holy mayde he dude honure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; askede of &thorn;at meyte somme parte,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as &thorn;aw he had hadde gret nede.</L>
<L>&amp; anone &thorn;is mayde lokede hym towarde,</L>
<L N="1520">&amp; somme of &thorn;is meyte he dud hym bude.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot first he blessed hit w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre honde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. byd in bude corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>As euer hit was herre vse to do.</L>
<L>&thorn;is &yogh;ong chylde &thorn;o, &thorn;at by hurre dud stonde,</L>
<L>Anone vanysshede away &amp; was ago:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1525">So &thorn;at &thorn;ere nasse now&thorn;er childe ny mone</L>
<L>To take &thorn;at meyte of &thorn;at mayde.</L>
<L>Bot he stode alle assmayhede as stylle as stone,</L>
<L>&amp; in hurre hert he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &amp; sayde
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="35"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at hit nas non vrthelyche mone</L>
<L N="1530">&thorn;at &thorn;is meyte of hurre wolde haue take,</L>
<L>Bot a wykkede spirite or an angelle, &thorn;e tone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou&yogh;t to here somme cause to make.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;en he stode stylle &thorn;us in a &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; was alle assmayed of &thorn;is case,</L>
<L N="1535">Where hit were &thorn;us by god y-wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Or how or in whate moner hit do was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot anon he comforde hurre-selfen &thorn;ere &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">he aus hee corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>By &thorn;e ensampulle of seynt Gregory,</L>
<L>How an angelle come hym to</L>
<L N="1540">&amp; askede of hym somme gode fulle petwysly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot what maner of angell &thorn;at hit was</L>
<L>&thorn;at come &thorn;o &thorn;edur &thorn;at meyte to craue,</L>
<L>&thorn;e gret trust &thorn;at he hadde in god &amp; in &thorn;e cresse</L>
<L>From alle dysesse &thorn;at mayde dude saue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1545">For opynlyche in story fynd y not writone</L>
<L>&thorn;at hit a euel spirite was;</L>
<L>Bot euery mon may well knowe &amp; wyte</L>
<L>What he was, by-cause &thorn;at he shynte &amp; dred &thorn;e cresse:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For, and he had ben a' gode angelle,</L>
<L N="1550">he nolde not for &thorn;e crosse han flowe,</L>
<L>Bot rather han stonde by hurre fulle stylle</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e crosse han lowtud fulle lowe;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore y dar wryte &amp; baldelyche say</L>
<L>&thorn;at hit a wykede spirite &thorn;o was,</L>
<L N="1555">&thorn;at come &thorn;edur to a-tempte &thorn;at may,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yff he hade hadde tyme or space.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot what maner spirite &thorn;at hit were</L>
<L>&amp; what &thorn;at euer he purposed hym to done</L>
<L>&amp; by what cause he asked &thorn;at almys &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="1560">Whethen he come &amp; hodere he went, knewe nomone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;et &thorn;is we mow wyton &amp; know seurly</L>
<L>&thorn;at god, knower of all maner thynge,</L>
<L>Wolde take &thorn;at almys fulle worthely</L>
<L>&thorn;at for his loue &thorn;at holy mayde dude &thorn;edur brynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;edur &uuml;berschr. von ders. Hand.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1565">&amp; &thorn;onk here heylyche for hurre gode wylle</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde &thorn;at almys for his loue &thorn;edur brynge or sende,</L>
<L>So preuely, so mekely &amp; so stylle,</L>
<L>For his loue &thorn;at alle thyng has lende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so fulle gretlyche y-&thorn;ongede he was</L>
<L N="1570">&amp; wel by-louede of god &amp; of alle hurre lynage:</L>
<L>For in alle Englonde &thorn;at day &thorn;er nasse</L>
<L>A wysor wommon &thorn;en he of hure age,
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ny vertuoser in leuynge, y dar welle say,<MILESTONE N="213" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;en was &thorn;is holy mayde seynt Ede;</L>
<L N="1575">And &yogh;et hurre godenes encressede euery day.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;e bysshoppus of &thorn;e reme toke hem to rede,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By conselle of seynt Adelwolde &amp; seynt Dunstone,</L>
<L>To encresse hurre in hurre degre</L>
<L>In gouernynge of mo abbeus &thorn;en on,</L>
<L N="1580">For he was so wyse, gentylle &amp; so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also &thorn;e kynge, hurre fader, knew &thorn;at fulle welle</L>
<L>&thorn;at hurre was leuer to here mayteynesse &amp; masse</L>
<L>&amp; vpon hure boke to rede and spelle,</L>
<L>Nen to be duchas, quene or cowntasse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nen, non = than.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1585">Wherfore &thorn;e kynge, here fader, graunded also &thorn;erto</L>
<L>To sacre hurre abbas of &thorn;e abbay of Wynchestre,</L>
<L>Of Berkyng, &amp; of Wyltone also &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et hure age nas &thorn;o bot fyftene wyntre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at mayde onswered &thorn;o fulle mekely</L>
<L N="1590">To &thorn;e kyng, hure fader so dere,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde "syrre, y nam not worthy</L>
<L>Forto bere so gret a cure. "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e bysshopus nolde turne non other-weys,</L>
<L>Bot saydone &thorn;at he shulde for any thyng</L>
<L N="1595">Ben abbas of &thorn;use &thorn;re abbays</L>
<L>&amp; haue &thorn;e couent in hurre gouernynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e abbey of Wynchestre &thorn;o securly</L>
<L>Seynt Adelwolde hym-self repared &thorn;at &yogh;ere</L>
<L>In &thorn;e worshepe of owre lady,</L>
<L N="1600">And made seynt Ede furst abbas &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;at mayde curteys &amp; hende</L>
<L>Durst not a&yogh;eyn-stonde hurre godfadris heste,</L>
<L>Bot grauntede hym &thorn;o at &thorn;e hende</L>
<L>And sayde "syrre, dothe by me as &yogh;ow thyngy&thorn; best!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1605">Seynt Adelwolde sacrede hurre &thorn;o anone</L>
<L>Of seynt Mary abbay of Wynchestre in to abbas,</L>
<L>Of Berkyng also, &amp; eke of Wyltone &mdash;</L>
<L>For of &thorn;use &thorn;re abbeys abbas he was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is hey&yogh;e state he toke mekelyche a&yogh;eyn hurre wylle,</L>
<L N="1610">And of &thorn;use &thorn;re abbeys abbas y-made he ys;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;re &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot euer he dwelte at Wylton stylle,</L>
<L>He nolde not from hurre moder depart, y-wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For leuer he hadde to abyde ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Vndur hurre moder chasteyssynge,</L>
<L N="1615">&thorn;en ony state gretter howherellys to bere<NOTE PLACE="foot">howherellys = o-where els.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of cheffenesse or of hey&yogh;e gouernyng.
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="37"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot two sprytwalle ladyus he ordeynede &thorn;o</L>
<L>To ocupy &thorn;at worshipfulle state in hurre absens</L>
<L>&amp; kepe &thorn;e couentes of &thorn;use abbays two,</L>
<L N="1620">&amp; of gode leuyng hee &yogh;aff hem gret euidens.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he hurre-selff dwelte at Wyltone stylle</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hurre moder, as y sayde &yogh;owe ere;</L>
<L>For hurre moder to serue was holyche hurre wylle,</L>
<L>Welle leuer &thorn;en ony other gret state to bere;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1625">And also for he was norysshut vp in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>&amp; furste y-ordryd he was &thorn;ere &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>And mony miracles &thorn;orow goddus grace</L>
<L>For hurre werone done &thorn;ere also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore hurre wylle was most &thorn;ere forto abyde &mdash;</L>
<L N="1630">Bot &thorn;e couentus were gouerned ry&yogh;t welle alle &thorn;re;</L>
<L>For o&thorn;erwhile he wolde to hem ryde</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e gouernelle of hem he wolde ouer-se. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. euer st. ouer?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot w<SUP>t</SUP>-Inne sherte tyme after &thorn;ys</L>
<L>Kynge Edgar, hurre fadur so dure,</L>
<L N="1635">W<SUP>t</SUP>-Inne &thorn;e &yogh;ere and half y-wys<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;e st. &thorn;re.</NOTE></L>
<L>He was ded and leyde on bere:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When he hadde regnyd here syxstene &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Fullyche complete w<SUP>t</SUP> sommewhat more;</L>
<L>&amp; sixstene &yogh;ere holde &amp; sommewhat more, y trowe, he were</L>
<L N="1640">When he was kyng furst y-kore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bote of his deth and also his burynge</L>
<L>Ychaue ywriton &yogh;owe here-byfore,</L>
<L>&amp; somme-what of his gode gouernynge;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at is &thorn;e cause &thorn;at y wryte here nomore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1645">Bot when &thorn;is mayde herde &thorn;at her fadur was dede,</L>
<L>Gret mowrnyng made &thorn;at mayde &thorn;o;</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t onlyche for hurre-self he ne drede,</L>
<L>Bot also for mony another mon mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He sorowede not onlyche for here-self y-wys</L>
<L N="1650">Bot also for mony a-nother mon mo,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ll.1649, 1650: sind a. R. nebengeschr., 1150 steht auch im Texte; a. R. fehlt mon in 1150.</NOTE></L>
<L>For myche rest, ioy and blys</L>
<L>&thorn;e Reme lafte when he was ago.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lafte, &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e kyng Edgar was &thorn;us deyde,<MILESTONE N="214" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>His sone Edwarde was cronyd kyng</L>
<L N="1655">By alle &thorn;e hole remes redde &mdash;</L>
<L>Ten &yogh;erre elde was &thorn;at semely thyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A blessed kyng forsothe was he!</L>
<L>He leuede not here no whyle y-wys;</L>
<L>Bot of his deth was gret pyete,</L>
<L N="1660">As in his story y-writone hit is.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="38"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he regnede not foure &yogh;ere here,</L>
<L>By sixe wykeus, as yche vnderstonde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nas martrid &amp; leyde on bere,</L>
<L>In grete myscheffe &amp; gret sorwe to alle Englonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1665">Bot a lytulle byfore his deyth &thorn;is mayde seynt Ede</L>
<L>Vpon a tyme hadde gret lust to slepe:</L>
<L>And in to hurre orytorie to slepe he &yogh;ede.</L>
<L>Bot a merueylle swene he dude &thorn;o mete:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at hurre ry&yogh;t hy&yogh;e &thorn;o ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="1670">Felle ou&yogh;te of herre heyde &thorn;o sodenly.</L>
<L>He woke w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at &amp; scrykede for fere,</L>
<L>&amp; woke hurre moder &amp; hurre susteren &thorn;at lye here by.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre moder was sore afferde also</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "dure, god dou&yogh;ter, what eylluth &thorn;e?"</L>
<L N="1675">"A dredefulle sweuene, moder, y mette &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche, moder, gretlyche greuys me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at my ry&yogh;t Ey&yogh;e felle ou&yogh;t of my hedde</L>
<L>Doun in to &thorn;e grounde fast me by.</L>
<L>Hit betokenyth &thorn;at my brothere shalle be dedde</L>
<L N="1680">Sone after &thorn;is tyme now sodenly;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For y knowe hit, he sayde, ry&yogh;t welle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hit nylle turne non other-warde</L>
<L>Bot soden deythe wolle come fulle snelle</L>
<L>To my brother, kyng Edwarde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1685">And ry&yogh;t so hit by-felle afterward sone &mdash;</L>
<L>In what manere, ychulle &yogh;ov say.</L>
<L>&thorn;is &yogh;ong kyng &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he wolde gone</L>
<L>Into a foreste vpon a day hym to play,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to seyn Etheldrede, his brother, also,</L>
<L N="1690">&thorn;e whyche he loued as his lyff.</L>
<L>Bot his stepmoder slow hym &thorn;o,</L>
<L>As he dronge &thorn;ere, w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre knyff.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when seynt Ede tythynges hadde</L>
<L>&thorn;at kyng Edwarde here brother was &thorn;us deyde,</L>
<L N="1695">Myche sorow forsoth he &thorn;o made,</L>
<L>&amp; byde &thorn;at his body to Schaftesbury were leyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In to &thorn;e gouernelle of quene Eluyne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was &thorn;e moder of kyng Edgare;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was &yogh;et &thorn;at tyme alyue,</L>
<L N="1700">&amp;, as y trawe, he dwelt &thorn;o &thorn;are.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;us was forthe-fulde &thorn;e prophecy of &thorn;e sweuene</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e tweyn appullone &thorn;at fellon from &thorn;e tre in to &thorn;e water in his thenkyng,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as hit was expoundud to hym by his moder, Eluyn &thorn;e quene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e first &yogh;ere off his regnynge;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1705">&amp; so was &thorn;e sweuene of his suster seynt Ede</L>
<L>Of hurre ry&yogh;t y&yogh;e ou&yogh;t of here hedde fallyng,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e a lytyl byfore my&yogh;ten rede,</L>
<L>Was very tokene of his martringe. &mdash;
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="39"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when kynge Edwarde was &thorn;us deyde,</L>
<L N="1710">In manere ry&yogh;t as ychaue sayde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lordus of &thorn;e reme token hem to rede</L>
<L>To make hurre quene &thorn;at holy mayde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And saydon: Etheldrede o&yogh;te not to be kynge,</L>
<L>For he was causa of his brotheris deythe,</L>
<L N="1715">&amp; also, for he was so &yogh;onge a thyng</L>
<L>&amp; cou&yogh;the nowthre mesure ny methe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;ey ordeyneden a parlement anone ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>To loke who hadde most skylle to ben herre kynge;</L>
<L>&amp; duden acorde &thorn;o alle &thorn;e reme y-fere</L>
<L N="1720">&thorn;at &thorn;is holy mayde shulde haue &thorn;e reme in gouernynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>By-causa &thorn;at Edwarde for Etheldrede was slave,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey sayden &thorn;at he my&yogh;t not challange &thorn;at heritage,</L>
<L>Ny nomore ry&yogh;t hadde &thorn;erto by ony lawe</L>
<L>Non hadde he &thorn;at nas not of &thorn;at lynage;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1725">Wherfore &thorn;ey acordeden alle to won entent:</L>
<L>Of alle Englonde to make &thorn;is holy mayde quene.</L>
<L>And messangeres ben towarde hurre y-sent</L>
<L>To Wyltone anon, w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;ten ony wene,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To loke what &thorn;is mayde wolde say</L>
<L N="1730">Of &thorn;is matere y-touchyde byfore.</L>
<L>Bot euer continuallyche he sayde nay,</L>
<L>&amp; prey&yogh;ede hem to speke &thorn;erof to her nomore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he had leuer, he sayde, to serue hurre god</L>
<L>And euer to kepe herre maydenhode in clannasse,</L>
<L N="1735">&thorn;en ony other rychesse of worldelyche gode,</L>
<L>Or to ben quene or Emperasse.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Orto.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e messagers seyen herre so stedfaste,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nolde for no thynge change here &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey turden hem a&yogh;eyne at &thorn;e last,</L>
<L N="1740">And suche tythynges to &thorn;e lordus &thorn;ey brou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">turden st. turnden.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayden &thorn;at hurre hert was as hard as ony stone,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;t for no thynge change here &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For othere encresse of lordshepe kepte he none,</L>
<L>Bot onlyche to serue god &thorn;at alle has wrou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1745">And when &thorn;us lordus seyen none other wone</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at Etheldrede most nede be hurre kyng &mdash;</L>
<L>For other heyre forsothe nasse none,</L>
<L>Seythe &thorn;is holy mayde nolde not ben hurre quene for no thyng; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he nolde none suche charge vpone hurre take</L>
<L N="1750">Bot myche leuer he hadde to abyde stylle in hurre abbay,</L>
<L>&amp; myche more &thorn;ou&yogh;t he had a chapelle to make</L>
<L>In worshyppe of seynt Denys &amp; of his day
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="40"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en to bene quene of Englonde &amp; Fraunce y-fere</L>
<L>Or lady of ony gretter astate y-wys,</L>
<L N="1755">&amp; sayde &thorn;at here kyndam nas not here</L>
<L>Bot w<SUP>t</SUP> god hit was in heuene blys;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also euer he bare in hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;e Passyon &thorn;at god suffrud for vs one gode Frydaye</L>
<L>And how dure monkende &thorn;ere he bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="1760">&amp; how myche soro was in his moderes hert &thorn;at day,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also how lytulle his martrus setton by worldelyche gode,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e gret sorowe &thorn;at &thorn;ey suffredone for goddus loue here,</L>
<L>And how gret loue and trust &thorn;ey haddon in godde</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey nolde neuer for no peyne change hurre chere;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1765">He &thorn;ou&yogh;t in hurre hert fulle oft-tymes also</L>
<L>&thorn;at he was y-spoused to goddus sone off heuene</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he hadde hurre maydenhode a-vowyd hym to,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he my&yogh;t neuer a gretter quene bene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;e cause, as ychaue oft redde,</L>
<L N="1770">&thorn;at he nolde not quene of Englonde be</L>
<L>Bot abyde stylle in herre abbay &amp; serue hurre god</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mekenesse &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> virginite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot anone after he let make at Wyltone y-wys<NOTE PLACE="marg">Beda.</NOTE></L>
<L>A fulle fayre chapelle of lyme &amp; stone</L>
<L N="1775">In &thorn;e worshep off seynt Denys;</L>
<L>&thorn;at chapelle was made: sone after hit was done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A porche was made byfore &thorn;at chapelle by gode avyse</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;re lytulle &yogh;ates of entrynge</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche weron set on crosse wyse,</L>
<L N="1780">w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;re crosses also of ry&yogh;t gode peyndynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e passione of god was welle peyndud &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e sepulcre of gode was peyntede &thorn;ere also,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e ymage of seynt Denys w<SUP>t</SUP> o&thorn;er y-fere,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> golde and asere &amp; mony o&thorn;er coloures mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1785">&thorn;is purtatur he bare euer in here clene hert</L>
<L>Of goddus Passion, as y sayde ere, &amp; of his wo</L>
<L>&amp; of his woundys hard and smert;</L>
<L>And in &thorn;is newe chapelle he peyndede hem &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Y-wallud &amp; y-foundyde &thorn;is chapelle was fulle welle</L>
<L N="1790">&amp; ry&yogh;t ryallyche y-peyndyde hit was also</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> golde &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> asere &amp; o&thorn;ere coloures eueredelle;</L>
<L>Dan Benna halp ry&yogh;t welle &thorn;erto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;is chapelle was y-made</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> alle &thorn;e pareylle &thorn;at longede &thorn;erto,</L>
<L N="1795">Seynt Dunstone &thorn;erof sone warnyng hade,</L>
<L>And &thorn;edur he come to halwe hit anone &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot a solempniere dedicacione for-sothe &thorn;er nas</L>
<L>In Wylton neuer byfore &thorn;at day y-done;</L>
<L>For god hym-self &thorn;at day &thorn;ere was</L>
<L N="1800">&amp; blessed &thorn;at Chapelle euery stone.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="41"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> Joy y-crownyd &thorn;at mayde hym sey&yogh;e</L>
<L>Frome aboue come downe w<SUP>t</SUP> ry&yogh;t glad chere;</L>
<L>Bot seynt Denys come furst doune from god an hey&yogh;e</L>
<L>And toke &thorn;at mayde by &thorn;e honde ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere &mdash;<MILESTONE N="216" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1805">A trewe messangere forsothe was he,</L>
<L>To bydde hurre byhold vpwarde towarde god an hy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>For god badde hym take hede to &thorn;at mayden fre,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as seynt Jon dude to owre lady&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For herre keper forsothe he hadde be long byfore</L>
<L N="1810">And sauede hurre body, hurre hert, hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t in chastyte,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nas neuer from &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was bore</L>
<L>Dyffoullyd w<SUP>t</SUP> dede or spotte of sensualyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In spirite he hurre &thorn;at tyme ladde &mdash;</L>
<L>For he lad not here &thorn;ere bodyly.</L>
<L N="1815">Bot seynt Dunstone was &thorn;erof fulle gladde,</L>
<L>&thorn;at went &thorn;o hem fast by.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For seynt Dunstone sawe hit verylyche in sey&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at seynt Denys ladde &thorn;at mayden by &thorn;e honde,</L>
<L>&amp; also he sawe &thorn;e gret, hoge ley&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1820">&thorn;at was in &thorn;at place &thorn;ere &thorn;ey dud stonde;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seynt Dunstone sawe how &thorn;at mayde also</L>
<L>Made fulle oft-tymes a crosse by-fore here throte.</L>
<L>And to &thorn;at ensampulle he toke ry&yogh;t gode hede &thorn;o</L>
<L>And sayde: "dou&yogh;ter, &thorn;at fyngur shalle neuer rote." &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1825">&thorn;us sayde seynt Donstone, &amp; sothe hit ys:</L>
<L>&thorn;at fyngur rotede neuer &yogh;et</L>
<L>Ny neuer hit ne shalle rote here-after y-wys;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at seynt Dunstone afterwarde by vision mete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hit was byfore &thorn;e Translacyon of &thorn;at holy mayde</L>
<L N="1830">To seynt Dunston ysende &amp; by tokon to hym y-tolte,</L>
<L>And also openlyche to kyng Etheldrede here brother y-sayde,</L>
<L>And also to Ordulf &thorn;at was &thorn;e kyngus prince so bolde:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at hurre honde shulde neuer y-rotyd be,</L>
<L>In skynne, bode, flessh, ny&yogh;e bone,</L>
<L N="1835">Bot euer stonde stylle in won dygre,</L>
<L>By-cause of &thorn;e gode dedus &thorn;at he &thorn;er-w<SUP>t</SUP> had donne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e dedicacione was &thorn;us y-donne</L>
<L>In manere ry&yogh;t as ychaue now ysayde,</L>
<L>Seynt Donston went to masse &thorn;o anone;</L>
<L N="1840">For alle thyng was forthe redy &thorn;erto y-leyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when seynt Dunstone was at his masse,</L>
<L>Sone after &thorn;at holy sacryng</L>
<L>A lettre doun to hym y-sende was</L>
<L>By seynt Denys from heuene kyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1845">&thorn;e tenoure of &thorn;e letter was sothely &thorn;is:</L>
<L>&thorn;at sone after &thorn;e &yogh;ende of fowrty dayes &amp; thre</L>
<L>Mayde Edes body shalle dye &amp; hurre sowle come to blys</L>
<L>&amp; dwelle in heuene w<SUP>t</SUP> angels fre;
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="42"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&thorn;at sote rose-blossom, goddus owne spouse,</L>
<L N="1850">Shalle not long w<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;ov in vrthe a-byde,</L>
<L>Bot he shulle come vp to goddus howse</L>
<L>Anon ry&yogh;t after &thorn;is forsayde tyde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when seynt Donstone &thorn;is letter had redde</L>
<L>&amp; follyche consayuyd alle &thorn;e hole entent,</L>
<L N="1855">Sore he wepe &amp; sore he grede;</L>
<L>Bot nomone ellys wyst what he ment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His mynstres dreddone hem fulle sore,</L>
<L>&amp; yche mon &thorn;at abou&yogh;t &thorn;at auter stode,</L>
<L>&amp; merueylledone gretlyche wherfore</L>
<L N="1860">&thorn;is holy bysshop was of so drery mode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot a monke, &thorn;at was hym &thorn;o ny&yogh;e</L>
<L>&amp; also &thorn;at preuey&yogh;e of his conselle &thorn;o was,</L>
<L>Askede of hym, when he time sey&yogh;e:</L>
<L>What was &thorn;e cause of his heuynasse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1865">And he w<SUP>t</SUP> sore sykyng &amp; snobbyng bothe</L>
<L>Vnswered &thorn;e monke, &amp; sayde ry&yogh;t &thorn;us:</L>
<L>"&thorn;is holy mayden Ede w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;ten othe</L>
<L>Shalle hastely ben take a-way from vs.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is mayden is so clene &amp; so vertuose also,</L>
<L N="1870">&thorn;at &thorn;is synfulle worlde, &thorn;at so horry ys,</L>
<L>Maynot kepe hurre body no lengur here in wo,</L>
<L>Bot (god) wolle haue hurre vp to his blys."<NOTE PLACE="foot">god fehlt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when seynt Donstone had &thorn;us ysayde,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e folke &thorn;at hit herde, maden gret soro &amp; dolour;</L>
<L N="1875">Bot &thorn;e mayden kneled at &thorn;e auters &yogh;ende, ry&yogh;t welle apayde,</L>
<L>&amp; abode &thorn;ere to resaue hurre saueour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o when &thorn;is masse was fullyche done</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is holy mayde y-hoselud was,</L>
<L>Seynt Donston lette graue &thorn;is lettre in &thorn;e auter-ston &mdash;<MILESTONE N="217" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1880">&amp; &yogh;et &thorn;at letter is in &thorn;e same place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; also he clepte &thorn;at mayden to hym &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; tolde to herre euerydele &thorn;is case,</L>
<L>&amp; bad hurre take ry&yogh;t gode hede &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>"For ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is worlde &yogh;e shulle hastely pas;"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1885">&amp; badde hurre &thorn;at he shulde make hurre alle redy,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t clerelyche &thorn;at way go</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche lastyth vp to heuene an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>And tolde hurre what day he shulde dye also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when seynt Dunstone, as y sayde &yogh;ow ere,</L>
<L N="1890">Hadde writone &thorn;us day &amp; to hurre eke y-tolde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor to hurre ist &amp; &uuml;berschr.; nach to hurre foigt im Ms.; Bl.: H. w. &thorn;us day to hurre &amp; eke y-tolde.</NOTE></L>
<L>He toke his leue w<SUP>t</SUP> drere chere,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> wepyng hynone &amp; hert fulle colde.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="43"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is mayde past forthe &amp; madde gode chere<NOTE PLACE="foot">hynon = eyes.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;onged god heylyche of his sonde.</L>
<L N="1895">Bot when &thorn;e tyme was come so nere,</L>
<L>Euene &thorn;e seuethe day by-fore, y vnderstonde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Almy&yogh;ty god come from heuene an hey&yogh;e</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> a mery spouse-song knokede at hurre &yogh;ate</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "aryse vp, my colloure, my frend, and hey&yogh;e!</L>
<L N="1900">For &yogh;e shulle come to me nowe for algate."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;us versus &yogh;e shulle &thorn;us expounde &amp; vnderstonde</L>
<L>&thorn;at Jhesu, &thorn;at was of Mary y-bore,</L>
<L>To his spouse, seynt Ede, sende doune a sonde</L>
<L>&thorn;e seuethe day of hurre deythe by-fore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1905">A tokon of sekenesse he send hurre tylle,</L>
<L>To warne hurre &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> hurre day was ney&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&amp; also by a no&thorn;er ensampulle he knewe fulle wylle,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he &thorn;at ny&yogh;t next after by sweuene sey&yogh;e.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sompnium miraculosum.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre thou&yogh;t &thorn;at hurre chaufere, &thorn;e whyche was of ledde y-made,</L>
<L N="1910">In &thorn;e whyche water hurre to wasshe was wonto be hatte,</L>
<L>Was set ouer a feure bothe gret &amp; sadde,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at a nox went &thorn;rey&yogh;e abou&yogh;te alle &thorn;at,<NOTE PLACE="foot">= an ox. Bl. prey&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; euer as he went, he song &thorn;is songe:</L>
<L>"Where-euer a spirite wolle be, he may both breth &amp; blawe,</L>
<L N="1915">&amp; his voys &thorn;ow may&yogh;te here euer amonge,</L>
<L>Bot whethen he cometh &amp; houdere he wolle, &thorn;ou shaltus not knawe."<NOTE PLACE="foot">not &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, what shulde &thorn;is sweuene ellus signify</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at warnyng to herre from god by &thorn;is oxe send was</L>
<L>&thorn;at hurre soule shulde come sone to heuene an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="1920">Ry&yogh;t as Baalam was warnyd of &thorn;e angelle by his asse;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To haue &thorn;e Joy &amp; &thorn;e blys &thorn;at euere shalle last,</L>
<L>As seynt Dunston had tolde hurre &thorn;ere-byfore.</L>
<L>Bot hurre flesshe for drede quakedde full fast,</L>
<L>Bot hurre soule was glad &amp; drede no sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1925">Hurre obyt he let &thorn;o &thorn;ere do anone<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. l. falsch held st. he let.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; for herre prestes he ordeynede to syng &amp; rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. so st. to.</NOTE></L>
<L>He gate to herre tombe no ryalle stone,</L>
<L>Bot mony pore men to clothe &amp; fede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e &thorn;ryd ny&yogh;t after a no&thorn;er sweuene &yogh;et mette he:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sompnium miraculosum.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1930">&thorn;at a fayre Tombe was made &thorn;ere of &thorn;at leyde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at hurre soule was fate to heuene w<SUP>t</SUP> angels fre<NOTE PLACE="foot">fate fatte = fetched.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at hurre body was hollyche in &thorn;at tombe y-leyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;is chaufre, of &thorn;e whyche y dud byfore &yogh;ow telle,</L>
<L>&thorn;is fayre tombe hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t was &thorn;o y-made of &thorn;at leyde</L>
<L N="1935">&amp; closede hurre body abou&yogh;t euery delle,</L>
<L>When hit was w<SUP>t</SUP> -inne hit y-leyde.
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="44"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also in &thorn;e mortyde when &thorn;at ny&yogh;t was gone,</L>
<L>&thorn;e colleron &thorn;at he was wonde to kepe &amp; fede</L>
<L>Weron y-fonde as deyde as ony stone &mdash;</L>
<L N="1940">&thorn;o knowe hurre moder fulle well &thorn;at he wolde be dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre dethe-day hey&yogh;ede vpon herre fulle fast;</L>
<L>Hurre flesshe tremblede &amp; drede fulle sore,</L>
<L>&amp; also he was fulle sore agaste</L>
<L>Lest he nadnot plesud god welle euer-more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1945">Bot euer he cryed to god &amp; prey&yogh;ede fast</L>
<L>And sayde: "lord god, y betake my soule to &thorn;e;</L>
<L>Bryng hym to &thorn;y Joy &thorn;at shalle euer last.</L>
<L>Lorde Jhesu, my trust is alle clene in &thorn;y pyete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu lorde, y drede me fulle sore</L>
<L N="1950">Lest y naue not done to &thorn;e ary&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot, Jhesu, &thorn;at were of Mary y-bore,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue me grace to haue my lampe ly&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu, &yogh;yff &thorn;at my lampe be fonde w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Of whome shall y aske help bot onlyche of &thorn;e?</L>
<L N="1955">Lord, as &thorn;ou art fulle of grace and my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hey&yogh;e now fast &amp; come to me!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For to me now grete tribulacyon comen ys.</L>
<L>Lord god Jhesu, haue pyte of me!</L>
<L>For full well I knowe, non help &thorn;er nys</L>
<L N="1960">Bot onlyche, fadur of heuene, in &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherefore, lord Jhesu, forsake me nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Nowe, lorde, in my greste nede;</L>
<L>For wyth gret payne &thorn;ou hast me bou&yogh;t,<MILESTONE N="218" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For me, lord, &thorn;ou suffrestude &thorn;y woundys blede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. suffreduste.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1965">Lord Jhesu, I pray &thorn;e, forsake me nou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>For holyche my trust is, Jhesu, in &thorn;e.</L>
<L>How dure, lord Jhesu, hast &thorn;ou me bou&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&thorn;ou dyedust for me, Jhesu, vpone &thorn;e tre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Jhesu, &thorn;aw y dede ofto-tymes a-mys,</L>
<L N="1970">Euere to plese &thorn;e was hollyche my wylle;</L>
<L>Y forsoke &yogh;owe neuer, my lorde, y-wys;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e knowe, Jhesu, fulle wylle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Dure moder, quod &thorn;at mayde ry&yogh;t anone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Prey&yogh;e my sustron &thorn;at &thorn;ey comen alle hedure now byfore me,</L>
<L N="1975">&thorn;at y may aske for-&yogh;euenesse of &yogh;ow &amp; of hem also</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e displesaunce &thorn;at ychaue do to &yogh;ow &amp; to hem, my moder fre."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre moder past forthe in to &thorn;e abbay &thorn;o anone,</L>
<L>Wepyng and snobbynge w<SUP>t</SUP> hert fulle sore.</L>
<L>Hurre sustren comen &thorn;edur to hurre &thorn;o euerychone</L>
<L N="1980">&amp; knelledone doune mekelyche &thorn;at mayde byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I prey&yogh;e &yogh;ow, sustren, quod &thorn;at mayden anone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>For-&yogh;eue &yogh;e me alle &thorn;at ychaue a&yogh;eynus &yogh;ow mys-wrou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And y prey&yogh;e &yogh;ow, dere modur, for-&yogh;euyth me also</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at y chaue displeyseyde &yogh;ow, in worde, in dede or &thorn;ou&yogh;t."
<PB REF="00000053.tif" N="45"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="1985">&thorn;o weptone full fast &thorn;us ladyes alle</L>
<L>And snobbedone &amp; sykedone fulle sore;</L>
<L>Hurre modur a-doune assowe dudde falle,</L>
<L>For sorwe he my&yogh;t wepe nomore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And alle &thorn;ey sayden: "lady, what nede was &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="1990">Of vs to aske ony for&yogh;euenesse?</L>
<L>For, treuely, &yogh;e dudone neuere to vs amys,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;eue to vs gouernaunce of gode lore &amp; off grace."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en spake Wultrude, hurre modur dure:</L>
<L>"My dure dou&yogh;ter, what shalle y nowe do?<NOTE PLACE="foot">nowe &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="1995">Whom shall y haue now to my fere,</L>
<L>When &yogh;e arne &thorn;us from me go?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;is monere &thorn;ey sorwedone &amp; sykede sore,</L>
<L>&thorn;us ladyes and hurre modur y-fere.</L>
<L>&thorn;is mayden prey&yogh;ede hem euermore</L>
<L N="2000">&thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde ben of ry&yogh;t gode chere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when hurre mowrenyng was allere-mast,</L>
<L>Seynt Dunston knew full well alle &thorn;is:</L>
<L>&amp; come to Wyltone anone in gret hast,</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e sacramentis to hurre he dede y-wys,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2005">As schroue herre, hoselder, &amp; aneled herre he dude also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hoselder = hoseld her. dude itt &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "dou&yogh;ter, loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be of gode chere!</L>
<L>For vp to &thorn;i spouse &thorn;ou shalt now go</L>
<L>&amp; dwell in heuene w<SUP>t</SUP> angels clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vp to &thorn;at place, dou&yogh;ter, now shaltow go</L>
<L N="2010">&thorn;ere as ioy &amp; blysse shall euer be,</L>
<L>Joy and myrthe, and neuer wo,</L>
<L>In heuene w<SUP>t</SUP> god in trinite;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Reseyue &thorn;at corone &thorn;ou shalt, dou&yogh;ter, also</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;y spouse hath ordeynyd &thorn;ere to &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="2015">And dwelle &thorn;ou shalt &thorn;ere, for euere &amp; ho,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ho, o = ay.</NOTE></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> coronede virginus and maydens fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot herken, dou&yogh;ter, &amp; ry&yogh;t wel be-holde,</L>
<L>For now &thorn;y spouse dothe clepte &thorn;e</L>
<L>To &yogh;elde to &thorn;y mede and meryte a hondrid folde</L>
<L N="2020">&thorn;at longe&thorn; to &thorn;y clene virginite &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;e corone of mayden-hode &thorn;ou shalt were</L>
<L>And dwelle in heuene w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;y spouse &mdash;</L>
<L>For, &thorn;aw &thorn;ou be broune, &thorn;ou art ry&yogh;t wel-shape &amp; fere.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore, dou&yogh;ter, for&yogh;ete &thorn;y peple &amp; eke &thorn;y fadur house.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. pople?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2025">For &thorn;e kyng, &thorn;y spouse, couetyth &thorn;y shappe</L>
<L>&amp; to se also &thorn;i fayre bewete:</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> clothus of ioy he wyl &thorn;e lappe,</L>
<L>For ry&yogh;t welle, dou&yogh;ter, he louys &thorn;e.
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="46"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hey&yogh;e &thorn;e, dou&yogh;ter, &amp; haff y-donne!</L>
<L N="2030">For &thorn;y spouse doth fast &thorn;e calle;</L>
<L>To hym &thorn;ou most come anone</L>
<L>&amp; dwellone in his ioyfulle halle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when seynt Dunstone hadde &thorn;us ysayde</L>
<L>&amp; of his sermon madde ful anynde,</L>
<L N="2035">Into &thorn;is chirche &thorn;ey beron &thorn;is mayde<NOTE PLACE="foot">anynde = an ende.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bytwene herre armus, &thorn;us ladyes heynde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e whyche in &thorn;e worship of seynt Denys</L>
<L>&thorn;at mayde hadde y-made a litulle byfore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">y &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot furst a lady &thorn;edur y-sende is</L>
<L N="2040">To make alle thyngus redy &thorn;ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Inne &thorn;e chirche as he dud go<MILESTONE N="219" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mowrenyng hert &amp; sore wepynge,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;e quere, as hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;o,</L>
<L>He herde queresters fulle mery synge;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2045">So mery songe, as herre &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He ne herde neuer in hurre lyff byfore.</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e quere &thorn;o to gon he &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Bot he seye a litulle childe &thorn;o stond &thorn;ore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So fayre a chylde, hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t, he seye neuer mo</L>
<L N="2050">Ny none so ley&yogh;tsom ny so gladde of chere.</L>
<L>He sayde: "my lady, whodere wolle &yogh;e go?</L>
<L>&thorn;us ben angels &thorn;at syng &thorn;us here,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; abyde &thorn;e soule of &thorn;at mayde clene,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> song to bryng hit in to &thorn;at house</L>
<L N="2055">Where is ioy and myrthe and euer has ben,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> suche song hurre soule to presentone to hurre spouse."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o brou&yogh;t &thorn;ey &thorn;at holy mayden &thorn;edur anone</L>
<L>&amp; leydone hurre in &thorn;at same place.</L>
<L>He toke hurre leue &thorn;o of euery mone,</L>
<L N="2060">&amp; past vp to god &thorn;o in &thorn;at space.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e sixstenethe day of Septembre forsothe hit was</L>
<L>&thorn;at god after hurre sowle &thorn;us sende.</L>
<L>Commendo spiritum meum domine, he sayde, in manus tuas,</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at worde he made a nende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2065">Thre &amp; twenty wynter he hadde of age,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e boke sayth, of &yogh;erres no more,</L>
<L>When he toke hurre leue at hurre lynage</L>
<L>And at hurre modur &thorn;at he was of y-bore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;e fourthe &yogh;erre of hurre brother regnynge,</L>
<L N="2070">Kyng Etheldrede, as ychaue ofto redde;</L>
<L>&amp; after &thorn;e incarnacyone of goddus sone, heuene kynge,</L>
<L>Nyne hondryd foure score &yogh;ere &amp; foure weren fully spedde.
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="47"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;is virgyn was &thorn;us forth past,</L>
<L>Wultrud, hurre modur, wepte fulle sore;</L>
<L N="2075">Hurre hondys he wronge, hurre te&thorn; he gnast,</L>
<L>&amp; cryede &amp; sayde: "my wordly Joy now haue y lore."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre sustron weptone, hurre herre &thorn;ey rende,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ey &thorn;enne for hurre gret sorwe &thorn;ey made.</L>
<L>Erellus and baronus, bothe sybbe and frende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. barouns oder baronus?</NOTE></L>
<L N="2080">Euery mon fore hurre deyth sore hert &thorn;ey hade.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e angelus song &amp; maden gode chere</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;ton hurre soule vp to heuene blys.</L>
<L>&amp; a sote sauore &thorn;e lafte styll &thorn;ere</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at holy maydenus body y-wys;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2085">&thorn;at flauour was as sote to herre a-vis</L>
<L>And as welle smellyng, as hem &thorn;ou&yogh;te &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>As &thorn;aw hit hadde y-come from paradys,</L>
<L>To alle hem &thorn;at stoden abou&yogh;te &thorn;e bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e day come of hurre buryenge,</L>
<L N="2090">Gret noyse men my&yogh;t &thorn;o &thorn;ere here</L>
<L>Of clerkus &amp; religiose wepynge,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> gret lordus of &thorn;e reme y-fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For mony gret lordus of hurre keyne</L>
<L>Comen &thorn;at day to hurre buryenge,</L>
<L N="2095">&amp; sore weptone &amp; snobbedone &thorn;eyne</L>
<L>For &thorn;e deythe of &thorn;at semely thyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a fulle fayre processione &thorn;at day was &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Of bysshoppus, Erellus &amp; baronys bothe,</L>
<L>A fayror as men saydene &thorn;ey sey&yogh;e neuer &yogh;ere<NOTE PLACE="foot">saydene aus saydone corr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2100">&thorn;en was &thorn;ere &thorn;at day w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;tone wothe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A mery masse &thorn;er was y-songe,</L>
<L>Of clerkus w<SUP>t</SUP> voysus bothe hey&yogh;e &amp; clere;</L>
<L>&amp; gret snobbyng &amp; wepyng &thorn;er was among.</L>
<L>Bot seynt Dunston dude hurre body entere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2105">Wt-inne seynt Denys chirche in &thorn;e vrthe colde</L>
<L>Hurre fayre body he dud entere &mdash;</L>
<L>For he fulle ofte had hym y-tolde</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde be buryede ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For w<SUP>t</SUP> myelde wordus hee wolde ofto telle</L>
<L N="2110">&thorn;at in &thorn;at place he wolde y-buryed be &mdash;</L>
<L>Seynt Woltrude herre modur knewe &thorn;at fulle welle,</L>
<L>&amp; ofte-tymes wepe &thorn;ere whenne he dud hurre see.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wh&emacr;ne &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mony a masse &thorn;ere &thorn;at day was songe,</L>
<L>&amp; a thousande pore men were welle y-fedde &mdash;</L>
<L N="2115">For off pore men &thorn;at day was &thorn;ere grete thronge,<MILESTONE N="222" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As ychaue ofto in &thorn;e boke y-redde.
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="48"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot twolf hurre modur hulde w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre algate stylle</L>
<L>To pray for &thorn;at mayden soule y-wys;</L>
<L>And &yogh;et in-to &thorn;is day &thorn;ey done &thorn;er dwelle &mdash;</L>
<L N="2120">At Mary Mawdelaynus herre dwellyng &yogh;et is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To prey&yogh;e for &thorn;at mayden soule he set hem &thorn;ere &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">2119-2121) sind unten zugeschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hurre hert was so tendre of hurre chylde &amp; so fulle of drede,</L>
<L>&amp; for drede of hurre soule he had gret fere,</L>
<L>Albut-&thorn;aw hit nere no nede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2125">Nou&yogh;t-a&yogh;eyne-stondynge, &thorn;at in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Ofto-tyme was y-sey fulle gret ley&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;ere as hurre body enterud was,</L>
<L>Bothe by day &amp; eke by ny&yogh;t,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;et had hurre moder bothe dou&yogh;t &amp; drede</L>
<L N="2130">Of hurre dou&yogh;ter soule y-wys for alle &thorn;at,</L>
<L>&amp; made prestus bothe syng &amp; rede,</L>
<L>And gret penaunce he dud hurre-self algate. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is blessud virgyn, so fulle of grace,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nolde not from hurre moder long dwelle;</L>
<L N="2135">&thorn;e threttyth day forsothe hit was,</L>
<L>Hurre moder he come a&yogh;eyn telle,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; tolde hurre modur of hurre gode fare<NOTE PLACE="foot">telle = till.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e ioy and blysse &thorn;at he was inne,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he was set vpone &thorn;e ry&yogh;t syde &thorn;are</L>
<L N="2140">As myrth and Joy shalle neuer blynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;us visablelyche to hurre modur he dude apere</L>
<L>&amp; spake to hurre in hurre owne langage,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as a ney&yogh;bure doth to a nother here</L>
<L>Or kny&yogh;t or squiere to his page.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2145">&amp; tolde hurre how &thorn;e enuiyus feynte, Sathanas,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Ms. enmyus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Dude hurre &thorn;ere lette w<SUP>t</SUP> alle his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shulnot haue come to &thorn;at ioyfulle place</L>
<L>&thorn;ere-as is euer day &amp; neuer ny&yogh;t;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"And, dure moder, quod &thorn;at mayden &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="2150">&thorn;at feyndus powere y dude &thorn;o spylle</L>
<L>By help of &thorn;o angels, &thorn;at comen me to</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t me to heuene a&yogh;eyn his wylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so, dure moder, ychaue thrast hym doune into his place</L>
<L>&thorn;ere-as meche sorwe, payne &amp; myscheff ys;</L>
<L N="2155">And yche was borone vp w<SUP>t</SUP> angels of grace</L>
<L>To heuene, &thorn;er-as is euer-lastyng ioy &amp; blys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;is blessud virgyn had talyd tys</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hurre dure modur on &thorn;is monere,</L>
<L>He past forthe vp to heuene blys.</L>
<L N="2160">Hurre modur stodde stylle &amp; byhulde ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere,
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="49"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; in hurre hert fulle sore he &yogh;et dredde,</L>
<L>Nou&yogh;t-a&yogh;eyne-stondynge &thorn;at he sey&yogh;e &amp; herde welle</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;at blessed virgyne, hurre dou&yogh;ter, ry&yogh;t welle ferde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;et almys-dede &amp; fastyng he dude euerylyche continuelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2165">He dude not lyge as don mony other wymmen<NOTE PLACE="foot">lyge = he ligen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at atte hurre children dyenge wepon fulle sore</L>
<L>&amp; ry&yogh;t sone after for&yogh;etone hem</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;enk on hem lytulle after &thorn;at more:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he continuede algate stylle in &thorn;is:</L>
<L N="2170">In doyng of masse, of derche, &amp; of almys-dede,</L>
<L>&amp; euer he was hurre-self in fastyng &amp; in gret preyeris, y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; for hurre dou&yogh;ter had algate gret drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;us &thorn;is blessud womman, seynt Wultrude,</L>
<L>Suffrede for hurre dou&yogh;ter long marterdam in &thorn;e abbay,</L>
<L N="2175">&amp; of &thorn;e soule of &thorn;at holy virgyne hee hadde gret dou&yogh;te</L>
<L>&amp; prey&yogh;ede for hurre continuallyche both ny&yogh;t &amp; day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot afterwarde in hurre hert he was fulle gladde,</L>
<L>When he sawe so mony myracles y-do &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at so mony sekemen hurre hele &thorn;ere hadde,</L>
<L N="2180">Of what monere sekenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ey Inne were. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is was &thorn;e furst miracle &thorn;at god wrou&yogh;t after for &thorn;at mayde sake.</L>
<L>For hit byfelle &thorn;us in &thorn;e same thryddy&thorn; day<NOTE PLACE="foot">thryddy&thorn; = thirtieth</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre moder &thorn;ere spake,</L>
<L>&thorn;at a mayde-chylde was boron in &thorn;at contray.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2185">Of rychesse &thorn;at childus frendus werone welle byfore,</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t gode lyuers &thorn;ey werone also;</L>
<L>&thorn;ey hadden prey&yogh;ede seynt Ede fulle ofte, &thorn;at, when hit were bore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde fouchesaue to be godmodur &thorn;erto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e fader and &thorn;e moder of &thorn;e childe &thorn;at day y-bore</L>
<L N="2190">Weron foulke of ry&yogh;t gret astate y-wys</L>
<L>&amp; haddone loued seynt Ede algate byfore</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he alyue here one vrthe was;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore &thorn;ey prey&yogh;edon hurre &thorn;at trauell to do.<MILESTONE N="221" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And he sayde &thorn;at w<SUP>t</SUP> gode wylle he wolde,</L>
<L N="2195">&YOGH;yff god wolde fouchesaue to consent &thorn;erto &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; ellus, he sayde, &thorn;at he do hit nolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot seynt Ede was dede forsothe byfore</L>
<L>And hurre soule fatte to heuene blysse</L>
<L>&thorn;e thrydtythe day or hite were y-bore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">d in thrydtythe aus t corr. od. umgekehrt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2200">Bot &yogh;et &thorn;at holy mayde was &thorn;ere &thorn;at tyme, y-wys!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;e same day &thorn;at chylde was y-bore</L>
<L>&thorn;at seynt Ede w<SUP>t</SUP> Wultrude hurre modur spake.</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e Cathedralle-chirche of Wynchestre he was y-bore,</L>
<L>For seynt Alphege was redy &thorn;ere &thorn;o for hurre sake.
<PB REF="00000058.tif" N="50"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2205">For seynt Alphege was bysshop &thorn;ere &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Nexte after seynt Ethelwolde bysshop &thorn;ere he was,</L>
<L>Ychose by seynt Dunstone &amp; by alle &thorn;e reme also &mdash;</L>
<L>For by a uysione seynt Dunstone was y-warnot of &thorn;at cas</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at Alphege, &thorn;at was Abbot of Bathe abbay,</L>
<L N="2210">Of Wynchester shulde bysshoppe y-sacrid be.</L>
<L>Wherfore he was y-preyd &thorn;at day</L>
<L>To cryston &thorn;at lytyl mayden-chylde so fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e childe was to &thorn;at chirche y-brou&yogh;te</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bysshop was redy &thorn;o &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="2215">&amp; hurre godfader &amp; hurre godmores, ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ey ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Stode &thorn;ere redy &thorn;e bysshoppe byfore:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;e bysshoppe cristenede &thorn;at childe fulle honestlyche,</L>
<L>As he welle cou&yogh;the &amp; ou&yogh;te to do.</L>
<L>Bot in &thorn;e laterhende of &thorn;e office sodenlyche</L>
<L N="2220">Seynt Ede apperede hem bodylyche to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e bysshoppe toke to hym &thorn;e serge w<SUP>t</SUP> ly&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "haue &thorn;ow, mayden, &thorn;is tapur brennynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ou mowe entre Inne w<SUP>t</SUP> god of my&yogh;t</L>
<L>In &thorn;e day of &thorn;y weddynge"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2225">&amp; to &thorn;e childe &thorn;at tapur wolde han take,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e maner of holy chirche ys:</L>
<L>Bot seynt Ede was redy &thorn;ere for hurre sake</L>
<L>&amp; bede forth hurre honde y-wys;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e lytulle childus honde he strey&yogh;te forthe &thorn;o</L>
<L N="2230">To resayue &thorn;at tapre wyth &thorn;e ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;en toke &thorn;at tapre &thorn;e litulle childe fro</L>
<L>&amp; in hurre owne honde he hulde hit forth ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when seynt Alphege had verylyche sey in sy&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at seynt Ede hurre-self was redy &thorn;o &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="2235">To fonge to &thorn;e childe as he had y-tey&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t alyue as &thorn;aw he &yogh;et were:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;o sodenlyche he vanysshede a-way,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> gret ly&yogh;t &amp; sote sauore y-fere;</L>
<L>&amp; bodylyche apperede to hurre modur &thorn;at same day,</L>
<L N="2240">Sone after &thorn;at he hadde y-be &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when seynt Ede was &thorn;us forthe-past</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e seruys was welle y-do,</L>
<L>Seynt Alphege went &thorn;o in gret hast</L>
<L>Thedere as &thorn;at childus frendus were &thorn;o,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2245">And tolde hem ry&yogh;t as he had y-saye,</L>
<L>And chargede hem w<SUP>t</SUP> alle his my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde neuer otherwys mary &thorn;at may</L>
<L>Bot onlyche to &thorn;e sone of god alle-my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ey dedon trewelyche after his redde</L>
<L N="2250">&amp; brou&yogh;tone hurre to Wylton after ful sone,</L>
<L>To lerne bothe to syng and redde;</L>
<L>&amp; afterwarde to religione he was y-done,
<PB REF="00000059.tif" N="51"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; was blessud abbas in &thorn;at same place,</L>
<L>&thorn;e thryd after seynt Woltrude;</L>
<L N="2255">&amp; of gode gouernele he had gret grace &mdash;</L>
<L>Hurre name was y-clepud Bry&yogh;twyde;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot twey &yogh;ere ded he was by-fore</L>
<L>&thorn;e translacyon of &thorn;is blyssud virgyne seynt Ede,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> angels hurre sowle to heuene was bore,</L>
<L N="2260">Euere in ioy herre lyff to lede. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en from &thorn;is tyme forthewarde continually</L>
<L>&thorn;is blessud virgyne seynt Ede</L>
<L>In miraclus schewyng fulle bysyly (!)<NOTE PLACE="foot">schewyng ist &uuml;ber einem radirten Worte (wrought?) &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;aff grace &amp; hele to euery mone &thorn;at hurre bede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2265">So mony myraclus for hurre god wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>To euery mon &thorn;at ony nede hadde,</L>
<L>Of ony bone &thorn;at hurre ry&yogh;twyslyche bysou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>He had anone what-euer he badde. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of on miracule now y chulle &yogh;ow telle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2270">To all &thorn;at han luste to know and wete,<MILESTONE N="222" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;e very trewethe euery delle</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as y fynd in story wryte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre blessud moder, seynt Wultrude,</L>
<L>Toke a twaylle of ry&yogh;t gode aray<NOTE PLACE="foot">twaylle = towel.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2275">&amp; vpon &thorn;at virgenys tombe hit layde,</L>
<L>To hong &thorn;ere both ny&yogh;t &amp; day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is twaylle y-bordryd abou&yogh;t was</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> palle &thorn;e mountenesse ofe han hondbrede:</L>
<L>Abou&yogh;t &thorn;e tombe for honestnas</L>
<L N="2280">Hit was y-sowede in lengthe &amp; brede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">in lengthe &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;us hit byfelle vpon a day</L>
<L>&thorn;at a wommon, &thorn;at dwellede &thorn;ere bysyde,</L>
<L>Come to &thorn;at tombe, hurre bedus to say;</L>
<L>&amp; tylle al men were past awey, he dud abyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2285">&amp; when alle foulke weren &thorn;en ago</L>
<L>&amp; he hurre-self alle-on was lafte,</L>
<L>Hurre holde custoum he &thorn;ou&yogh;t to do &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. custou.</NOTE></L>
<L>For euer to stele was hurre crafte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is palle, enbroudryd w<SUP>t</SUP> golde so rede,</L>
<L N="2290">From &thorn;e twaylle ful sone he hit kytte</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hurre knyff in euel spede</L>
<L>&amp; abou&yogh;t hurre legg fulle fast hit knytte &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In monere of a garthur y-knytte hit was</L>
<L>Abou&yogh;t herre leg, fulle preuely;</L>
<L N="2295">To stele hit &thorn;us preuely from &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Hee hurre by-&thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;us sotelly.
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="52"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he had y-don &thorn;is dede</L>
<L>&amp; wolde han ben past forth vpone hurre wey,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ben st. hen?</NOTE></L>
<L>He my&yogh;t not passe ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at stede,</L>
<L N="2300">He was y-trallyd in suche aray:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre leygus weron fedryd w<SUP>t</SUP> hit so fast,</L>
<L>&thorn;at won fote my&yogh;t he &thorn;ennys &thorn;o go,<NOTE PLACE="foot">won = one. Bl. schiebt not vor he ein, wohl mit Unrecht.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot wepe and cryede &amp; hurre armys cast</L>
<L>&amp; sayde "alas alas, &thorn;at me is wo!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2305">Bot &thorn;e sexsten come to hurre &thorn;o anone</L>
<L>And askede what sorwe hurre was,</L>
<L>And bad &thorn;at he shuld fast &thorn;enne gon</L>
<L>Home to hurre owne dwellyng-place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he my&yogh;t not from &thorn;at place passe,</L>
<L N="2310">For no thyng &thorn;at he my&yogh;t do;</L>
<L>Hurre leygus werone y-fedryd so fast,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t no fote &thorn;ennys go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;o he tolde hem euery delle,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mournynge chere &amp; hert fulle sore,</L>
<L N="2315">Alle &thorn;e cas ry&yogh;t as hit byfelle,</L>
<L>And cryede seynt Ede mercy &amp; ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he had repentyd hurre &thorn;us</L>
<L>And byfore hurre iuge y-knowelachyd &thorn;is dede,</L>
<L>Ou&yogh;te of &thorn;is thraldam y-delyferyd he wys,</L>
<L N="2320">And thongede god mekelyche &amp; seynt Ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;is goldene rebaunde was taken from here &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; in to &thorn;e Minstre hit was &thorn;ere brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; vpon an autre hit was &thorn;o y-do,</L>
<L>In memory of &thorn;is miracule &thorn;at &thorn;us &thorn;ere was y-wrou&yogh;t. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2325">&thorn;o of &thorn;is miracule hurre moder was gladde,</L>
<L>When he sawe verylyche &thorn;at hit was sothe.</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;et in hert he was a-dradde,</L>
<L>And to leue hurre preyerus he was fulle lothe:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; ordeynede &yogh;et &thorn;at euery day</L>
<L N="2330">Twey prestus shulde &thorn;ere twey massus synge</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e auter by-fore &thorn;e whyche he lay,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> certeyne vrrysones for hurre prayng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dilexisti iusticiam, &thorn;e offyce was</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e ton masse, as yche vnderstonde;</L>
<L N="2335">&thorn;e to&thorn;er was Requiem eternam dona eis,</L>
<L>Preyng for euery soule bothe fre &amp; bounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;us twey messus euery day he lette synge</L>
<L>Byfore hurre tombe at anauter y-wys,</L>
<L>Preyng euer ouere alle thynge</L>
<L N="2340">&thorn;at hurre dou&yogh;ter my&yogh;t haue heuene-blys.
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="53"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot sone after &thorn;at worde spronge fulle wyde</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e myraclus &thorn;at for hurre &thorn;ere do were:</L>
<L>For ichemone &thorn;at had ony sekenesse in &thorn;e contre &thorn;ere bysyde,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yff he wolde come to hurre tombe, my&yogh;t haue his hele &thorn;ere.<MILESTONE N="223" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2345">For bleynde men hadden &thorn;ere hurre sey&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; crokette &amp; maymotte fatton &thorn;ere hurre hele &mdash;</L>
<L>Miracules weron do &thorn;ere &thorn;us day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; sekemen come &thorn;edur mony and fele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lepres men weron clansud mony one &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="2350">Frantyke men hadden &thorn;ere hurre wytte &mdash;</L>
<L>Of what sekenesse &thorn;at ony mon inne were,</L>
<L>His bodylyche hele he my&yogh;t &thorn;ere feytte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of what maner diseyse &thorn;at ony mone hadde &thorn;o:</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he wolde mekelyche prey to seynt Ede</L>
<L N="2355">And mekelyche in pylgrimage come hurre to,</L>
<L>He hadde &thorn;ere help, or he &thorn;enne hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when hurre blessude modur had knowynge of &thorn;is</L>
<L>And sey hit welle eueryday w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre hye,</L>
<L>He knewelle &thorn;at hurre soule was in very blysse<NOTE PLACE="foot">knew well.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2360">W<SUP>t</SUP> othere blessud virgyns in heuene on hey&yogh;e,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; thongede god w<SUP>t</SUP> alle hurre my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; fulle gladde in hert he was also,</L>
<L>For euery ny&yogh;t he saw gret ly&yogh;t</L>
<L>Aboute hurre tombe when he dud go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2365">Thredtene &yogh;ere continually forsothe &thorn;ere were</L>
<L>Gret miraclus at hurre tombe y-do,</L>
<L>&amp; pilgrymys comen euere, bothe fer &amp; nere;</L>
<L>&amp; presoners ou&yogh;t of presone weron lousede also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e reme had gret ioy y-wys</L>
<L N="2370">Of &thorn;is blessud virgyn, seynt Ede:</L>
<L>For what &thorn;at euer was done amys,</L>
<L>He wolde hem help, &yogh;yff &thorn;ey hurre bede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mo vertwys werkus forsothe he wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L N="2375">For his loue &thorn;at hurre dere bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;enne y con owther wryte or rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot byfore hurre translacione ychaue wrytone &thorn;is</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche ychaue in storyus ofto redde,</L>
<L>&thorn;e very trewthe ry&yogh;t as hit tys,</L>
<L N="2380">After my connynge, so god me rede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;yff ychaue ony thyng mys-do,</L>
<L>Discrete reder, y &thorn;e mekely prey</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e wolde fouchesaue to correcty hit so<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms. ist &thorn;ow radirt und &yogh;e &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at y naue no vyleny &thorn;ere-by.
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="54"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2385">And alle &thorn;at fauerythe me in &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Y prey to god and to seynt Ede</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue hym grace to haue &thorn;e blys</L>
<L>&thorn;at Jhesu dwellyth inne yn hys godhede.</L>
<L>Amen amen for charite,</L>
<L N="2390">Prey we alle &thorn;at hit so be.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<HEAD>(II.) Hic incipit translacio sce Edithe<NOTE PLACE="foot">Diese &Uuml;berschrift steht am Rande. Im Ms. schliesst das Folgende ohne Absatz oder Init. unmittelbar an.</NOTE>).</HEAD>
<L>&thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L>Twolfe &yogh;ere complete in hurre tombe lay,</L>
<L>As saffe, as hole as he vpone vrthe &yogh;ede,</L>
<L>&amp; gret miraclus wrou&yogh;t bothe ny&yogh;t &amp; day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2395">Bot &thorn;e threttenethe &yogh;ere, as ychaue redde,</L>
<L>Almy&yogh;ty god, &thorn;e kyng of grace,</L>
<L>Nolde let hurre body no lengur be hedde,</L>
<L>Seyth herre soule was in so ioyfulle a place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot by visyon sende hurre brother to,</L>
<L N="2400">Etheldrede, &thorn;at was kyng of Englonde &thorn;at stounde,</L>
<L>&amp; by visyon badde hym to Wyltone go</L>
<L>&amp; takon vp &thorn;at blessed body ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e grounde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayde, &thorn;at body was worthy to haue grettore honour</L>
<L>Among vrthelyche peple in &thorn;is worde here,</L>
<L N="2405">Of &thorn;e whyche &thorn;e soule dwellythe vp in heuene-toure</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e virgyns &amp; angelys so clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is visyon &thorn;e kyng hym-self say firste,</L>
<L>&amp; merueylede &thorn;erof meche in his thou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Bot to nomone &thorn;erof speke he ne dyrste,</L>
<L N="2410">Bot hulte hym stylle, as he nou&yogh;t rou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor nou&yogh;t ist ry&yogh;t ausgestrichen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tylle hit come to &thorn;e thrydday &mdash;</L>
<L>For thre ny&yogh;tys arowe he sey&yogh; &thorn;at same sy&yogh;t;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. sey&yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;en dudde &thorn;e Duke of Cornuayle to &thorn;e kyng say:</L>
<L>"Syre, y mette a merueylle sweuene to ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2415">Me thou&yogh;t &thorn;at assemely lady come me to</L>
<L>&thorn;is same ny&yogh;t thre tymes y-wys</L>
<L>&amp; badde &thorn;at y chulde hey&yogh;e &amp; to &yogh;ow go</L>
<L>&amp; grete &yogh;ow welle &amp; say &yogh;ow &thorn;ys:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at hit was goddus owne wylle seurly<MILESTONE N="224" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2420">&thorn;at &thorn;e body shulde be here in vrthe in greter honour</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche &thorn;e soule was in heuene on hey&yogh;e</L>
<L>Ychosyn in-to his owne hey&yogh;e toure."
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="55"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"For sothe, Ordulfe, quod &thorn;e kyng &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;is same sweuene verylyche mete y</L>
<L N="2425">&thorn;us thre ny&yogh;tys arowe now last a-go,</L>
<L>And suche a fayre lady me &thorn;ou&yogh;t y sey,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at badde me hey&yogh;e to Wyltone for my suster sake,</L>
<L>Ede, &thorn;at was ded mony day a-go,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde y shulde hurre body vp take,</L>
<L N="2430">&amp; do hit gretter worshuppe he badde also."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot ry&yogh;t as &thorn;use twey princes talodone &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. taledon.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; gretlyche in hurre hert merueyldedone also,</L>
<L>A letter from seynt Dunstone to hem comen ys &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was archebysshoppe of Caunturbury &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2435">I-send by a worshipfulle kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche hadde sey &thorn;e same visione also</L>
<L>Thre tymes byfore in won ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;e duke hadden y-do;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Certyfyenge &thorn;e kynge of his vision also</L>
<L N="2440">&thorn;e whyche he hadde y-sey w<SUP>t</SUP> his hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>How allmy&yogh;ty gode had send hym to</L>
<L>A messyngere from heuene an hy&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is messyngere was &thorn;at mayde seynt Ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was sende from &thorn;e kyng of grace</L>
<L N="2445">Furst to hurre brother, kyng Etheldrede,</L>
<L>&amp; nexte to syre Ordulf, &thorn;at duke of Cornuayle &thorn;o wase,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; nexte after to &thorn;at worshipfulle kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whiche y spake of here byfore.</L>
<L>Bot when &thorn;us thre wittenesse weron &thorn;us y-dy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2450">By &thorn;e blessud trinite vs lore,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vs st. is.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o afterwarde he come sone anone,</L>
<L>Bry&yogh;tore &thorn;enne &thorn;e sonne in May,</L>
<L>To &thorn;is bysshop seynt Dunstone</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;use wordus to hym dude say:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2455">"Almy&yogh;ty god, maker of alle thynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;orwe mynde of his mercy &amp; of his grace</L>
<L>Hathe take vp my soule to his dwellynge</L>
<L>In heuene into &thorn;at Joyfull place;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &yogh;et hit pleseth to his benignite</L>
<L N="2460">To clarifye &thorn;at to monus hele here:</L>
<L>Wherfore to &yogh;ow he hath send me,</L>
<L>Byddyng &thorn;at ze shulde my body vp rere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he st. &yogh;e.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In hast to Wylton he bytte &yogh;ow gon</L>
<L>To parforme &thorn;e fette, of his owne wylle,</L>
<L N="2465">And take vp my body from &thorn;e vrthe anone</L>
<L>&thorn;at lyth &thorn;ere, as &thorn;ow leydyst hit, stylle,
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="56"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To claryfy &thorn;e powere of goddus my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In to monnus hele &amp; his hereynge:</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere shulle be wrou&yogh;t myracles day &amp; ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2470">&thorn;orw &thorn;e godenesse of heuene kyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e dou&yogh;t no-thyng of &thorn;is</L>
<L>Ny holde hit for no fantasy,<NOTE PLACE="foot">no &uuml;berschrieben.</NOTE></L>
<L>&YOGH;e shulle fynd my body &thorn;ere y-wys</L>
<L>As hole lygyng as euer aliue &yogh;e hit seye &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2475">&thorn;e organys of &thorn;e lemys ou&yogh;t-take</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche childlyche y vsede when y was chylde,</L>
<L>As felyng and sey&yogh;t ys from hem take,</L>
<L>From &thorn;e fyngers w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e whyche y fedde bestes wylde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot alle &thorn;e remanent of my body as hole hit ys,</L>
<L N="2480">Excepte &thorn;e organys of &thorn;e lemys &thorn;e whyche gouernede my wyttus fyue,</L>
<L>And as clene w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ony corrupcione hit is</L>
<L>As hit was whenne yche was on vrthe alyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;e thombe of my ry&yogh;t honde forthere-more</L>
<L>Ys as hole in fel &amp; flesshe and blode,</L>
<L N="2485">W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e whyche y was y-wonde to blesse me byfore</L>
<L>Where-euer y went, sete or stode,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; also freysshe hit is to lokon now also,</L>
<L>As euer hit was in my lyff-day &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e godenesse of god hath y-kepte hit so</L>
<L N="2490">&amp; more better &thorn;enne y con &yogh;ow now say.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot more for my fader gulte forsothe hit is</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e organys of my nother lemys ben take away,<NOTE PLACE="foot">my nother = myn other (Bl. erkl&auml;rt falsch nother = nether).</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;en for ony thynge &thorn;at y dud my-self amys</L>
<L>Owthere by ny&yogh;t or ellus by day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2495">Another tokon &yogh;e shull haue more &thorn;erto</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche &yogh;e shulle redylyche se w<SUP>t</SUP> &yogh;our hey&yogh;e:<MILESTONE N="225" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;e vrthe &thorn;at my body ly&yogh;t on, is mevyd, also,</L>
<L>Y-mevyd alle from &thorn;e grounde an hy&yogh;e,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To shew welle &thorn;at my body is redy &thorn;enne to go.</L>
<L N="2500">&amp; &thorn;at hit is hollyche goddus owne wylle,</L>
<L>&thorn;use signus &yogh;e shulle se &thorn;ere, &amp; &yogh;et welle mo,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche y nulle not &yogh;ow now telle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when seynt Dunstone had herde &amp; sey alle &thorn;is,</L>
<L>&amp; kyng Etheldrede hadde send hym letters also,</L>
<L N="2505">Towarde Wylton he toke &thorn;e way y-wys</L>
<L>Also blyue as he my&yogh;t &thorn;ederwarde go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot syxscore myle to Wyltone he hadde &mdash;</L>
<L>For he dwelt at Caunturbury &thorn;o.</L>
<L>&amp; fyue dayes iorneys he &thorn;ederwarde madde</L>
<L N="2510">Ore he come Salysbury to.
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="57"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;e same ny&yogh;t &thorn;at seynt Dunstone to Salesbury come,</L>
<L>He saw by vysione alle &thorn;at he saw here, &amp; myche more, &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">here = ere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; grettur credence to hym he &thorn;ere nome</L>
<L>&thorn;en he dudde ony tyme &thorn;erby-fore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2515">For as sone as he was y-leyde y-wys</L>
<L>In his bedde &thorn;ere to slepe,</L>
<L>Bot fullyche as-slepe &yogh;et he nys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. a-slepe. nys = ne was.</NOTE></L>
<L>When he &thorn;is sweuene dude &thorn;ere mete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hym thou&yogh;te &thorn;at he was at Wyltone &thorn;o</L>
<L N="2520">In &thorn;e chirche &thorn;ere hurre body in tombe was,</L>
<L>And gret ly&yogh;t hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t he sey &thorn;ere, &amp; angels to,</L>
<L>&amp; seynt Denys, &thorn;at holy marter, stode in &thorn;at plase;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bytwene &thorn;e tombe, hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &thorn;at marter &thorn;o stode,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> angelus &amp; aposteles dignite,</L>
<L N="2525">Byfore &thorn;e auter fayre and gode</L>
<L>Y-halwyde in &thorn;e name of &thorn;e trinite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He saw stonde among hem also</L>
<L>&thorn;at blessud virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche honestlyche spake seynt Dunstone to;</L>
<L N="2530">&thorn;at sayde, "lowe, syre, take &yogh;e gode hede!<NOTE PLACE="foot">lowe = lo.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fadur, &yogh;e knowel what hit plesithe god to do by me;</L>
<L>&amp; for &yogh;e shulde knowe &thorn;e trewthe alle veryly,</L>
<L>God hath sende vs now hedur to &thorn;e:</L>
<L>For &thorn;is is &thorn;e expounder of goddus wyll &thorn;at stond me by."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2535">Seynt Denys spake to seynt Dunston &thorn;o</L>
<L>And sayde: "brother, &thorn;e wylle of god is &thorn;ys</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e take vp &thorn;ys body &amp; gretter worshippe do &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche &thorn;e soule is worshippud in heuene blys;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hit ou&yogh;te welle to haue gret worshepe in vrthe here</L>
<L N="2540">&thorn;e wheche was keper off so clene virgynyte</L>
<L>And &thorn;e clene habitacyon of god also y-fere.</L>
<L>Go forthe, brother, &amp; herre-of witenesse take of me!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at seynt Dunstone from slepe a-woke</L>
<L>&amp;, verylyche, trewe by-leue &thorn;erof he hadde &thorn;o.</L>
<L N="2545">And anone as hit was day, &thorn;e way he toke</L>
<L>Towarde Wylton, as fast as he my&yogh;t go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Etheldrede &thorn;e kyng, hurre brother, he founde &thorn;ere &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&amp; he tolde to seynt Dunstone his sweuene anone.</L>
<L>Ordulf, &thorn;e duke of Cornuaylle, &amp; &thorn;e errelle of Dorsed also;</L>
<L N="2550">&thorn;ey tolden hym hurre sweuenes euerichone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e bysshop off Wynchester, seynt Alphege, was &thorn;ere &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Bycause of a vision &thorn;at he hadde y-sey &thorn;re ny&yogh;tys byfore,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bysshop of Wylton w<SUP>t</SUP> other prelatus mo.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere was rehersed &thorn;e miracle &thorn;at was do when Bry&yogh;twyde was bore.
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="58"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2555">&amp; when &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;use bysshoppus were gedered &thorn;us y-fere</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is miracle rehersede byfore y-sayde,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mony othur miraclus &thorn;at &thorn;ere do were,</L>
<L>&THORN;ey wenton to &thorn;e Tombe of &thorn;is blessude mayde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; heuyn vp &thorn;e stone &amp; leyden hit a-syde,</L>
<L N="2560">&thorn;e vrthe also &thorn;ey caston from &thorn;at plase away</L>
<L>&amp; voudeden &thorn;at place, &amp; made hit ryde,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;ey &thorn;at blessud body hadden y-saye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey founde &thorn;o alle thyng sothe ysayde byfore:</L>
<L>&amp; hurre blessud body alle-holle &thorn;ey hit founde y-wys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">y-wys ist nachtr&auml;glich zugesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2565">And a-rerede vp from &thorn;e grounde two fote &amp; more<NOTE PLACE="foot">two st. foure corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle redy to take vp forsothe hit &thorn;o was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is blessude body as hole &thorn;ey hit founde</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as alyue hit was goynge here y-wys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">2565-8) sind unten a. R. nach|getragen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; as sote a sauore come ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at grounde</L>
<L N="2570">As &thorn;aw hit hadde come ou&yogh;t from paradys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;us bysshoppus thre</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> other prelatus &amp; lordus monyone mo</L>
<L>Seyen &thorn;at hurre body was as feyre, as hole, as bry&yogh;t in ble</L>
<L>As hit was alyue when hit dude here go &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2575">Excepte &thorn;e organus as y sayde &yogh;ow ere:</L>
<L>As sey&yogh;t and felynge weron y-taken hem fro<MILESTONE N="226" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e same organus &thorn;at &thorn;ey inne were &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e ry&yogh;t thome was as freysshe as hit aliue were &thorn;o:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o were &thorn;ey glad &amp; &thorn;ongedon god &yogh;erne,</L>
<L N="2580">&amp; hurre moder w<SUP>t</SUP> other maydenus song Te deum an hy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&amp; other pepulle fast abou&yogh;t dudde renne</L>
<L>To se how holle &thorn;at feyre body &thorn;ere lye.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; seynt Dunstone toke vp &thorn;at fayre body &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;at was so sote, so fayre and so bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2585">W<SUP>t</SUP> other bysshoppus mony mo,</L>
<L>&amp; leyden hit vpon Gabriel auter ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e chirche was so fulle &thorn;o of swetnesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at come from &thorn;at blessud body &thorn;at lay byfore hem &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> so grete ioy, song &amp; gladnesse</L>
<L N="2590">&thorn;at ychemone made w<SUP>t</SUP> other y-fere,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at euery mon my&yogh;t han ben fulle glad in hert,</L>
<L>Cryston mon or hethone, or what-euer he were,</L>
<L>&thorn;at gret ioy and myrthe to haue yseye or herde<NOTE PLACE="foot">haue y vor seye ist nachtr&auml;glich zugesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at was amonge &thorn;at peple &thorn;o &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2595">&thorn;us was &thorn;e blessud body of &thorn;is holy virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> suche Joy ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e vrthe y-take,</L>
<L>As hole, as fayre as hit vpon vrthe vde;</L>
<L>&amp; gret myrth was y-made &thorn;ere for hurre sake.
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="59"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e thrydday of Nouembre forsothe hit was</L>
<L N="2600">&thorn;at &thorn;is blessede body vp of &thorn;e vrthe was take,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e Nyenthe hondryd foure score &amp; syxstethe &yogh;ere of grace<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hondrys.</NOTE></L>
<L>After &thorn;at Jhesu was bore of Mary for owre sake,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;e fyftenethe &yogh;ere of hurre brother rengnynge,</L>
<L>Etheldrede, &thorn;at kyng was in Englonde &thorn;o:</L>
<L N="2605">&thorn;e whyche gret tribulacione hadde in his leuynge</L>
<L>After &thorn;at seynt Dunstone to heuene was y-go. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of kyng Etheldrede now speke y nomore,</L>
<L>Bot of a fayre meracle ychulle &yogh;ow telle</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was done &thorn;at same day &thorn;ore,</L>
<L N="2610">As &yogh;e mowe in &thorn;e legende rede &amp; spelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e abbot of Glastynbury &thorn;at day was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; of his monchus tweyne or thre;</L>
<L>Bot on of hem brou&yogh;t hym-selff in to gret fere &mdash;</L>
<L>Edulff was &thorn;at monchus nome, as &yogh;e in boke mowe se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2615">&thorn;is monke &thorn;ou&yogh;t in his hert &thorn;o</L>
<L>Somme releke of &thorn;at blessud body to kete &thorn;at day:<NOTE PLACE="foot">ketc = get.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; wyth his knyffe he went hurre to</L>
<L>&amp; kotte a pese of hurre curtylle a-way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as he kotte &thorn;at pese from hurre curtyl away,</L>
<L N="2620">W<SUP>t</SUP> his knyff he towchede somme-what hurre brestbone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at of &thorn;at blessede virgyn, &thorn;ere as he lay,</L>
<L>&thorn;e redde blode from &thorn;at touche so fast ron</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;aw hit hade come from a lyuyng mone</L>
<L>&thorn;at hadde be lette blode in a quyke veyne y-wys,</L>
<L N="2625">&amp; so fast &thorn;e blode from hurre body ron</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle hurre clothus &thorn;erof wete wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;e monke sey &thorn;at alle &thorn;e pament was redde</L>
<L>&amp; alle his clothus &amp; huron weron wete also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">huron = hers, wie ouren ours 3941.</NOTE></L>
<L>For sorwe he felle doune a-swowe, as &thorn;aw he were dede.</L>
<L N="2630">Bot his brethron token hym vp from &thorn;e vrthe &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; he cryede god mercy and eke seynt Ede</L>
<L>&amp; repentede hym of &thorn;is dede fulle sore;</L>
<L>&amp; alle men for hym also &thorn;o bede</L>
<L>To Jhesu &thorn;at was of Mary y-bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2635">&amp; when he hadde repentyd hym &thorn;us</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e processione ydo for hym also,</L>
<L>&thorn;e pament was as clene as hit byfore was,</L>
<L>&amp; no-thyng senene &thorn;at &thorn;ere was do;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre clothus were hole as &thorn;ey ere were,</L>
<L N="2640">&amp; &thorn;e blode from hem was clene ago,</L>
<L>&amp; hurre lappe was hole a&yogh;eyn ally-fere,</L>
<L>&amp; no-thyng senene of &thorn;at &thorn;at &thorn;e knyff had y-do.
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="60"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;e monke had seye alle &thorn;is</L>
<L>&amp; knewe verylyche in hert &thorn;at hit was so,</L>
<L N="2645">Fulle ioyfulle in hert he was &thorn;erfore y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; alle other men &thorn;at were w<SUP>t</SUP> hym &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot kyng Etheldrede was fulle glad in his hert &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And Alphege &amp; seynt Dunstone bothe y-wys,</L>
<L>For &thorn;at gret myracle &thorn;at &thorn;ey sey &thorn;ere y-do,</L>
<L N="2650">&amp; thongedone heylyche &thorn;erfore kyng of blys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is miracle was in &thorn;e day nexste after hurre translacyon ydo,<MILESTONE N="227" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whyle kyng Etheldrede, hurre brother, was &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; seynt Dunston &amp; &thorn;at holy marter seynt Alphege also,</L>
<L>&amp; also in presence of seynt Wultrude, hurre moder dere. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2655">Sone after a nother miracle was do &thorn;ere &yogh;et:<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>For a lady of &thorn;at same abbay</L>
<L>Wolde han kotte awey a gobet of &thorn;e vylette</L>
<L>&thorn;at vpon &thorn;at blessud virgynes hedde &thorn;at tyme lay,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; a litul particule &thorn;erof he wolde fayne han hadde,</L>
<L N="2660">&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre knyff &thorn;edur &thorn;erfore dudde go.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at blessud virgyn sodenlyche heue vp here hedde,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as &thorn;aw he hadde ben alyue &thorn;ere &thorn;o,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And schewede &thorn;at lady w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre chere also</L>
<L>&thorn;at hit nas not &thorn;e wylle of god ny for hurre hele</L>
<L N="2665">&thorn;at he wolde so prowdelyche &thorn;edere so go</L>
<L>Or ony pece of hurre blessud clothus to stele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;is lady hadde y-seye &thorn;at sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He repentede hurre &thorn;erof fulle sore,</L>
<L>&amp; was sore aferde &amp; eke affry&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2670">&amp; mekelyche cryede hurre mercy and hore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; of &thorn;at miracule he was fulle glad also.</L>
<L>Seynt Wultrude hurre moder was also ful glade in hert y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; alle o&thorn;er peple &thorn;at was in &thorn;at place &thorn;ere &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; knewell hurre soule had gret ioy &amp; eke blys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2675">Bot &thorn;at lady was euer after fulle sore adredde</L>
<L>&amp; gret penaunce euer to hurre he toke</L>
<L>&amp; mercy euer of seynt Ede he bedde</L>
<L>&amp; alle wordelyche lustes fulle clene forsoke,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; euer after forsothe a parfyt leuer was he,</L>
<L N="2680">&thorn;e whyche hadde be a ful rechelesse womon byfore,</L>
<L>&amp; wel louede and wel worshepede &thorn;at mayde fre</L>
<L>&amp; blessud &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was in y-bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore &thorn;at blessud virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L>Comfordede &thorn;at lady afterwarde in suche manere:</L>
<L N="2685">"God hath grauntyd &thorn;e heuene-blys to mede</L>
<L>For &thorn;y gode werkus, Elbry&yogh;t, &thorn;at &thorn;ou worchest now here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And wyth-in &thorn;ys fourty dayes ywys</L>
<L>&thorn;ou shalt come to heuene on hy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; dwelle &thorn;ere euer &thorn;ou shalt in blys</L>
<L N="2690">W<SUP>t</SUP> god &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> his blessud mayney&yogh;e."
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="61"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Ede warnede &thorn;is lady thus,</L>
<L>For he shulde knowelle &thorn;at he had kete of god mercy &amp; grace</L>
<L>&amp; kete w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre repentaunce heuene blys</L>
<L>&amp; to dwelle w<SUP>t</SUP> god in his holy place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2695">&thorn;e foure &amp; threttythe day after &thorn;at y-wys</L>
<L>Bodylyche sekenesse come &thorn;at lady to,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e fourthe day after here soule past forthe is</L>
<L>To heuenelyche ioy from wordelyche wo;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> heuenelyche ly&yogh;t &amp; angelys song</L>
<L N="2700">Hurre soule was fatte vp to heuene-blys;</L>
<L>&amp; seynt Ede hurre-self was &thorn;use angelys amonge &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="marg">Marianus Scotus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bodylyche he was &thorn;ere y-sey&yogh;en y-wys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is lady, for &thorn;e whyche &thorn;use myraclus weron wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Elbry&yogh;t was &thorn;at ladyes name y-wys.</L>
<L N="2705">Whoso wolle trust to god &thorn;at hym dure bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>His sowle may ry&yogh;t sone come to blys. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;is blessud woman seynt Wultrude</L>
<L>Had y-sey &thorn;use gret myracles &thorn;us y-do,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at mekenesse &amp; leuyng of pryde</L>
<L N="2710">My&yogh;t breng mones soule to blys so:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Blessedlocurre, &yogh;yf he my&yogh;t, he ladde hurre lyff</L>
<L>&thorn;en he dudde &thorn;ere euer by-fore,</L>
<L>Euer in mekenesse, w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t stryff,</L>
<L>Mekelyche he leuede after &thorn;e gospelles lore,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2715">&amp; plesede god euer w<SUP>t</SUP> alle hurre my&yogh;t</L>
<L>In penaunce doynge &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> almys-dede</L>
<L>&amp; in gode preyerys bothe day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; thongede euer god for hurre dou&yogh;ter Ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so he continuede euer in vertwys leuynge</L>
<L N="2720">Alle &thorn;e dayes of hurre vertwys lyff.</L>
<L>Bot god, &thorn;at is knower of alle thynge</L>
<L>&amp; maker of pesse &amp; stauncher of stryff,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Nolde not let hurre vertwys leuyng no lengur be hude,</L>
<L>Bot to shewe hit ou&yogh;t to mones hele he &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2725">&amp; ofte-tymes, as ychaue y-rudde,</L>
<L>Gret myracules for hurre he wrou&yogh;te. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche on y chulle &yogh;ow telle,<MILESTONE N="228" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As ychaue redde in trewe story.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;e countre &thorn;ere as Benna dudde dwelle,</L>
<L N="2730">A byson mon dwelt fast hym by,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e whyche hadde ben bleynte alle his lyue,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et thretty wyntre he was of age,</L>
<L>Ny comforde nad non of childe ny wyue;</L>
<L>&YOGH;et he was come of hey&yogh;e lynage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2735">Bot to &thorn;e chirche of Treues he wolde ofte go &mdash;</L>
<L>A litull childe ofto-tymes &thorn;edur hym ladde &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;ere as Benne was chanon &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&amp; so in holy lyuynge his lyff he ladde.
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="62"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot whenne he herde Benne speke, he knew hym welle;</L>
<L N="2740">&amp; Benne wolde talke w<SUP>t</SUP> hym w<SUP>t</SUP> gode chere</L>
<L>&amp; gode tales of Wultrude &amp; of seynt Ede he wolde hym telle,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is bleynde mon wolde hym full gladlyche here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot hit byfelle so vpone a day</L>
<L>&thorn;at he was for-&yogh;ete fulle long at chirche &mdash;</L>
<L N="2745">For his childe was gone forthe to play &mdash;</L>
<L>For few other werkus wolde he wyrche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is bysone mone full wery of sete he was</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t gret lust he hadde to slepe:</L>
<L>He layde hym doun &thorn;o ry&yogh;t in &thorn;at place.</L>
<L N="2750">&amp; a graciose sweuene &thorn;ere dude he mete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hym thou&yogh;t &thorn;at a lady fayre and bry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Lyke to a prelet as &thorn;aw hit were,</L>
<L>Come to hym &thorn;ere as he lay ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde "sone, why lyste &thorn;ou here?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2755">Ryse vp, he sayde, &amp; &thorn;e way asshe</L>
<L>To Wyltone &amp; to &thorn;at abbas Wultrude,</L>
<L>&amp; prey&yogh;e hurre &thorn;at he wolde hurre honden wasshe,</L>
<L>&amp; washe &thorn;ou &thorn;i nynon w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at water, as yche &thorn;e rude:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou shalt haue clerely &thorn;y sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="2760">&YOGH;yff &thorn;ou wult do as y &thorn;e rede.</L>
<L>Go forthe &amp; trauelle bothe day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; smartlyche do as y &thorn;e bydde!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is bysone mon woke of his slepe,</L>
<L>And a full gladmon in hert was he,</L>
<L N="2765">&amp; for ioy he brake ou&yogh;t and wepe,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ony mon my&yogh;t haue pety to se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Benne sone herde &thorn;at wepyng noyce &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; come to hym sone after anone,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "Beteryke, what deseysse is come &thorn;e to</L>
<L N="2770">&thorn;at &thorn;ou art now so sorwefolle a mone?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Nay&yogh;e, syre, hit is for Joy &amp; not for deseysse, no,</L>
<L>Bot for ioy of a sweuene &thorn;at y haue mette now ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at a fayre lady come me to</L>
<L>&amp; sayde &thorn;at y shulde haue my sy&yogh;t,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2775">&YOGH;yf y cholde &thorn;e way to Wyltone asshe</L>
<L>&amp; prey&yogh;e Wultrude, &thorn;at is now abbas &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde in water hurre honden waffhe</L>
<L>&amp; blesse &thorn;at water w<SUP>t</SUP> gode chere,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; take to me &thorn;at water &thorn;enne,</L>
<L N="2780">&thorn;at y my&yogh;t wasshe &thorn;er-w<SUP>t</SUP> my nynon two:</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;enne my sy&yogh;t &thorn;ere sholdy wynne,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf y wolde, he sayde, do ry&yogh;t so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore, Benne, mekelyche y prey&yogh;e now &thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e wolde now &thorn;edur w<SUP>t</SUP> me go</L>
<L N="2785">&amp; speke to &thorn;at lady for me,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is thyng my&yogh;t &thorn;us be do."
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="63"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Benne stode stylle &amp; herkenede alle his speche,</L>
<L>&amp; fulle gladde in hert he was &thorn;o also,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "Beteryche, where he be by-come suche a leche</L>
<L N="2790">&thorn;at he may hele &thorn;yn nynon two?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;e forsothe, syre, quod Beteryche to Benne &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;is feyre lady trewelyche dude to me so telle;</L>
<L>Wherfore y prey &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e wolden now w<SUP>t</SUP> me go,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor wolden ist wolde auspunktirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>For y thenk no lengur here to dwelle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2795">Benne hadde gode wylle Wultrude to se,</L>
<L>&amp; grauntede &thorn;us bysone mon &thorn;at he wolde w<SUP>t</SUP> hym to Wyltone go.</L>
<L>&amp; forthe &thorn;ey wentone, &thorn;is bysone mone &amp; he,</L>
<L>&amp; comen to Wyltone sounde &amp; saue bothe two;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And foundon Woltrud anon redylyche &thorn;ere,<MILESTONE N="229" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="2800">Abbas, as he ou&yogh;te forto be.</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche welcome Benne w<SUP>t</SUP> ry&yogh;t gode chere</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bysone mon &thorn;at my&yogh;t not se.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; Benne tolde to Wultrude anone &thorn;at sweuene</L>
<L>&thorn;o whyche &thorn;e bysone mon hadde mette in Treues chirche,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;o st. &thorn;e.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2805">&amp; prey&yogh;ede hurre for &thorn;e kyngys loue of heuene</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde fouchesaf his hele to wyrche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wultrud sayde: &thorn;at he nas not worthy</L>
<L>Suche maystryes to wyrche or make,</L>
<L>Ny durst not tempte hurre god so heyly</L>
<L N="2810">Ny suche presumpsuisnas vpone here take.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Benne consulede herre euer &thorn;erto</L>
<L>&amp; prey&yogh;ede hurre to do hit, so fast,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he conscendede &thorn;ere-to also;<NOTE PLACE="foot">= consentede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; so he dude hit at &thorn;e last.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2815">A basyn w<SUP>t</SUP> water &thorn;o forthe was fatte,</L>
<L>&amp; Wultrud &thorn;erinne hurre honden dude wasshe;</L>
<L>&thorn;at bysone mon &thorn;o by hurre satte</L>
<L>&amp; mekelyche after &thorn;at water dude asshe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he hadde &thorn;us hurre honden y-wasshe,</L>
<L N="2820">He knelyng made hurre preyours to god of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; in hurre preyours euer he dude asshe</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is bleynde mon my&yogh;t haue his sy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when he hadde &thorn;us hurre preyours y-made</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre hond blessude &thorn;is water also,</L>
<L N="2825">&thorn;is bysone mon to &thorn;at water he ladde</L>
<L>&amp; wosshe &thorn;ere-w<SUP>t</SUP> his ynon two.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when he hadde wasshe his ynon two</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;is blessud water so clere,</L>
<L>Anon he lokede vp: and sawe alle &thorn;o</L>
<L N="2830">&thorn;at by hym stoden &thorn;at tyme &thorn;ere.
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="64"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when he saw alle thyng as clerely</L>
<L>As &thorn;aw he nad neuer ben bleynde byfore,</L>
<L>He &thorn;ongede god fulle myeldely</L>
<L>&amp; blessede &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was in y-bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2835">And &thorn;o he sayde to seynt Wultrud:</L>
<L>"Y-blessede mot &thorn;ou, my lady, be;</L>
<L>For y may now se in alle &thorn;e worlde so wyde</L>
<L>What &thorn;at euer me nedyth to se."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; Benne was fulle glad &thorn;o in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="2840">&amp; thongede god &thorn;o w<SUP>t</SUP> all his my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at suche a meracule for hurre hadde wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;eue for hurre loue &thorn;at bysone mon his sy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e sexstenes rong &thorn;e belles &thorn;o alle abou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e ladyes song Te deum an hy&yogh;e;</L>
<L N="2845">And euerychemone to hurre lowe dude low&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lowedude.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is grete meracle &thorn;ere y-do sey&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In seynt Ede chirche of Wyltone &thorn;is meracle was done,</L>
<L>Trewelyche, as y &yogh;ow telle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e secund &yogh;ere of hurre translacione,</L>
<L N="2850">Wose wolle &thorn;e trewthe rede or spelle. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A nother miracule &yogh;et y chul &yogh;ow lere,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at wollen take hede &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>How hit byfelle &thorn;at same &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere in &thorn;at chirche also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2855">Twey prestes, &thorn;e whyche were in &thorn;at chirche seruyng,</L>
<L>A litulle offense &thorn;ey hadden y-do</L>
<L>To &thorn;e meyer &thorn;at was &thorn;o in Wylton dwellyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">dieser V. ist u. a. R. nachgetragen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wherfore &thorn;ey weron arestyd bothe two,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in &thorn;e preson &thorn;ey weron y-cast<NOTE PLACE="marg">Istorum sacerdotum ista fuerunt nomina: Osmundus et Adel|mannus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2860">&amp; fast y-fedryd &thorn;ey weron &thorn;ere also.</L>
<L>Bot seynt Woltrude badde &thorn;e meyer to to-lyuere hem fast<NOTE PLACE="foot">to-lyuere st. delyuere (Bl. l&auml;sst ein to aus).</NOTE></L>
<L>Ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at penaunce &amp; ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is meyer was fulle of pryde</L>
<L>&amp; onswerede seynt Wultrude &amp; sayde hurre nay,</L>
<L N="2865">"Nay, quod &thorn;e meyer, &thorn;ey shulle here abyde</L>
<L>&amp; suffre penaunce alle &thorn;is day."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t hurre leue he hem from &thorn;e chirche fatte a-way</L>
<L>&amp; in strong presun &thorn;us hem &thorn;ere cast,</L>
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ey weron payned &thorn;ere alle &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="2870">&thorn;at of hurre lyff &thorn;ey weron sore agast;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And of seynt Wultrud he toke non hedde,<MILESTONE N="230" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot hult hem styll so in preson stronge.</L>
<L>Seynt Wultrud to god he prey&yogh;ede &amp; bedde</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nolde not suffre hem abyde &thorn;ere longe,
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="65"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2875">Bot to delyuer hem &thorn;enne &thorn;orow his grace</L>
<L>From &thorn;at peyne &thorn;at &thorn;ey weron &thorn;ere inne,</L>
<L>&amp; to restore hem a&yogh;eyne in-to hurre place.</L>
<L>Anon god herde hurre bone &thorn;ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Wultrude preyours god toke gode hede</L>
<L N="2880">&amp; de-lyuerde hem sone from &thorn;at preson so strong,</L>
<L>Mawgrey &thorn;at proude meyeres hedde;</L>
<L>Anone after &thorn;at he bodde not long</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; to &thorn;at meyer &thorn;at was so proude</L>
<L>Suche a sekenesse god him &thorn;o sende,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hem st. him.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2885">&thorn;at of his lyff he was in gret dou&yogh;tde;</L>
<L>&amp; also he hadde clene lefte his mynde.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lest.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when he was turmentyd w<SUP>t</SUP> sekenesse so,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t in &thorn;e same maner as ychaue &yogh;ow sayde,</L>
<L>To seynt Wultrude he send messengerus &thorn;o</L>
<L N="2890">&amp; of hurre grace mekelyche he prayde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayde &thorn;at he wolde senden &thorn;us prestes hurre to</L>
<L>And euer after hurre seruande he wolde be,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at &thorn;at he wolde delyuer him ou&yogh;t of his wo;</L>
<L>"Y beseche &yogh;ow, lady, &thorn;at &yogh;e wolde prey&yogh;e so for me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2895">And when &thorn;is meyers frendus hadden &thorn;us y-sayde,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. srondus.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wepyng &amp; sorwyng in yche a syde,</L>
<L>Seynt Wultrude holde hurre ry&yogh;t wel apayde</L>
<L>&amp; badde hem sende home &thorn;e prestes anone in &thorn;at tyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;enne weron &thorn;us prestes delyuerde ou&yogh;t of preson anone</L>
<L N="2900">And brou&yogh;t home a&yogh;eyne to &thorn;at blessud lady &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Bot gret pety hit was to seyn &thorn;at proude mon</L>
<L>&thorn;o whyche was tourmentyd w<SUP>t</SUP> sekenesse so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;us prestes weron brou&yogh;t a&yogh;eyn home &thorn;is</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e meyer for his mysdede had repentyd hym sore,</L>
<L N="2905">Wultrud mekelyche prey&yogh;ede to &thorn;e kyng of blys</L>
<L>To send hym suche hele as he had byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; god herde hurre meke preyours anone</L>
<L>&amp; send him as gode hele as he hadde eyer.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hem st. him.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e meyer was euer after a gode mone</L>
<L N="2910">And worshepud euer seynt Woltrude bothe ferre and nere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And alle other men weren gladde to plese hurre &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; forte displese hurre &thorn;ey dredden fulle sore,</L>
<L>For &thorn;is miracle &thorn;at &thorn;ey seyn &thorn;ere &thorn;us y-do;</L>
<L>Bot alle men duden hurre worshepe, lasse and more. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2915">A nother meracle &yogh;et sone after &thorn;is was do<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>By-cause of &thorn;at blessud lady, seynt Wultrude,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche more drede addedde &thorn;is other to.</L>
<L>For vpone a day hit &thorn;us bytydde:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at a theff &thorn;at had long y-ley in preson strong,</L>
<L N="2920">Was brokon ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at warde fulle preuelye,</L>
<L>And fast ron to chirche among &thorn;e &thorn;rong</L>
<L>And intrede in to seynt Edes seynt-warye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. seynt warye = seyntwarye sanctuary.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="66"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e Jaylardes folowedone &thorn;is theff fulle fast</L>
<L>&amp; purseweden after hym in to &thorn;at chirche,</L>
<L N="2925">&amp; sayden &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden &thorn;e &yogh;ates vp barste,</L>
<L>And other maystrefulle werkus &thorn;ay wolde wyrche,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; sayde &thorn;ey wolden &thorn;at theffe ou&yogh;t fache</L>
<L>For onymone &thorn;at wold say nay,</L>
<L>And breke vp bothe lok &amp; lache</L>
<L N="2930">And fache &thorn;at theffe from &thorn;at chirche a-way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot seynt Wultrude was sore agast &thorn;o</L>
<L>And prey&yogh;ede Jhesu of help and grace</L>
<L>To saue &thorn;is theffe from hongur &amp; wo</L>
<L>&amp; also to kepe hym from &thorn;at derke place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2935">Bot when seynt Wultrud had prey&yogh;ede so</L>
<L>To Jhesu, goddus sone, most of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>God sende suche bleynasse &thorn;us iaylardus to<NOTE PLACE="foot">bleynasse = blyndness.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre ynon &thorn;ey sey no sy&yogh;t,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot wenton in &thorn;e chirche &thorn;ere vp and doune</L>
<L N="2940">&amp; nyst neuer where &thorn;ey wenton ny trede;</L>
<L>Bot alle assmayed &thorn;ey setton hem doune</L>
<L>&amp; wepten &amp; cryeden fast for drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot anone after seynt Wultrude toke &thorn;e ry&yogh;t way</L>
<L>To Etheldrede, &thorn;at was kyng of Englonde &thorn;anne,</L>
<L N="2945">And mekelyche he dude hym &thorn;ere pray</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue hurre &thorn;e lyff of &thorn;at manne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng grauntede hurre here wylle anone<MILESTONE N="231" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at mon he &yogh;aue hurre &thorn;o ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere.</L>
<L>He thonged &thorn;e kyng &amp; went home stylle as stone,</L>
<L N="2950">&amp; founde hem bleynde &yogh;et ry&yogh;t as &thorn;ey were.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;ey herden &thorn;at he was come home,</L>
<L>Mekelyche &thorn;ey prey&yogh;edone hurre both day &amp; ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde haue mercy vpon home</L>
<L>&amp; graunte to hem a&yogh;ayne hurre sy&yogh;t;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2955">&amp; sayden &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden serue hurre for euermore</L>
<L>Mekelyche alle &thorn;e dayes of hurre lyf,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ey repentyd hem wonder sore</L>
<L>&thorn;at euer &thorn;ey maden a&yogh;eyn hurre bate or stryff.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when seynt Wultrude sawe hem repent hem so mekely,</L>
<L N="2960">He pray&yogh;ede to Jhesu, goddus sone, kyng of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To graunte to hem a&yogh;ayn &thorn;enne holy</L>
<L>Bothe hurre hele and eke herre sy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; he graunted to hurre anon hurre bone</L>
<L>&thorn;orow his grace &amp; &thorn;orow his my&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="2965">&amp; &thorn;ey wenten afterwarde home ful sone</L>
<L>&amp; hadden a&yogh;eyn bothe herre hele &amp; eke herre sy&yogh;t;
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="67"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; worshepeden euer afterwarde seynt Wultrude</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> alle herre power, hert and my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; so duden alle other &thorn;e whyche dweltone here bysyde,</L>
<L N="2970">Duden to hurre seruyse &amp; honour, bothe day &amp; ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is meracle was done at Wyltone, as ychaue sayde on &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sexstenethe &yogh;ere of Etheldredus regnynge,</L>
<L>&thorn;at next after seynt Edwarde was kyng here,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was seynt Edes brother, &thorn;at blessud &thorn;yng. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2975">&amp; a nother gretter miracle &yogh;et &thorn;ere was do<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>In &thorn;at same &yogh;ere nexste after &thorn;at folewyng</L>
<L>For seynt Edes sake &amp; for seynt Wultrude also,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e same kyngys Etheldredus regnynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ere come foure clerkes to Wyltone from ferne londe</L>
<L N="2980">W<SUP>t</SUP> a litull beryng-case fulle of relekes gode;</L>
<L>From Pykardye &thorn;ey comen, yche vnderstonde,</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue &thorn;e pardone of herre relekes to diuerse men for herre gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also &thorn;ey comen on pilgremage to seynt Ede,</L>
<L>For meche gode &thorn;ey herden of hurre in hurre owne cuntre,</L>
<L N="2985">And in hope &thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde &thorn;e better spede,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hem &thorn;ey brou&yogh;ton &thorn;ese relekes fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; among &thorn;use relekes &thorn;at y spake of byfore</L>
<L>Weron &thorn;e bones of seynt Ywen &thorn;e confessour,</L>
<L>Y-closud in a litulle shryne, &thorn;at my&yogh;t ben abou&yogh;t bore,</L>
<L N="2990">To kepe &thorn;use relekes in gretter honour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when seynt Wultrude wyst &thorn;at &thorn;use relekes weron comyng,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> procession a&yogh;eynes hem fulle holylyche he went &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t hem to &thorn;e auter, &thorn;e ladyes syngyng,</L>
<L>&amp; set &thorn;at litulle shryne vpone seynt Edes auter also,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="2995">W<SUP>t</SUP> meche worshepe and gret honeste &mdash;</L>
<L>For god tau&yogh;t herre euer to do welle. &mdash;</L>
<L>For god wolde &amp; knew ry&yogh;t welle in preuete</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle thyng shulde be ry&yogh;t as hit felle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For god hit wolde &amp; knewe hit ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L N="3000">&thorn;at &thorn;ulke relekes nolde neuer go &thorn;en a-way,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden abyde ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere &amp; euer &thorn;ere dwelle</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere in seynt Ede abbay. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;use relekes weron &thorn;us vpon &thorn;is auter sette</L>
<L>And &thorn;e masse y-donne also,</L>
<L N="3005">&thorn;use foure clerkes wenton to hurre mette</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> other clerkus mony on mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey maden hem mery &amp; glad also,</L>
<L>And restede hem &thorn;ere alle &thorn;at ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And othe morwe, tyll masse was do;</L>
<L N="3010">And &thorn;en to take herre iorney &thorn;ey hem dy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o to &thorn;e auter after &thorn;use relekes &thorn;ey wenton anone,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> prestes and clerkes in ry&yogh;t gode aray.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is schrene stode &thorn;ere stille as styff as stone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at all &thorn;ey my&yogh;t not drawe hit away.
<PB REF="00000076.tif" N="68"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3015">&thorn;ey houe, &thorn;ey drawe, &thorn;ey shogkeden hit also,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;erne &thorn;ere abou&yogh;t duden renne &amp; lepe;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;enne forsothe hit nolde not go,</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;e help &thorn;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;t hem gete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;ey sey&yogh;e hit nolde not &thorn;enne,</L>
<L N="3020">Bot &thorn;at hit wolde abyde &thorn;ere so stylle,</L>
<L>Sore &thorn;ey wepton &amp; sayden: "wollen go henne,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>wolle<GAP></ABBR> st. wollewe?</NOTE></L>
<L>For we se welle &thorn;at hit is goddes owene wylle<MILESTONE N="232" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;use blessud relekus abyde ry&yogh;t here</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L N="3025">&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> seynt Wultrude, hurre modur dere;</L>
<L>For &thorn;aw we wolden other-weys, we mow not spede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seynt Wultrud for &thorn;is meracle was fulle gladde,</L>
<L>&amp; specyallyche for &thorn;ys holy confessourre, seynt Ywenus sake,</L>
<L>&amp; also as for seynt Edes cosyn &thorn;ey hym hadde;</L>
<L N="3030">Wherfore greter ioy &amp; gladnesse Woltrude made.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to &thorn;use foure clerkus he &yogh;aff &thorn;enne</L>
<L>A thousonde shyllynges of golde fulle rede</L>
<L>For &thorn;e schrene and &thorn;e relekes contened &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L>And to ben of gode comforth &thorn;ese clerkes he badde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3035">Bot &thorn;ey wrongon hurre hondys &amp; weptone for drede</L>
<L>And renden hurre clothus &amp; teren herre here;</L>
<L>Bot euer amonge &thorn;ey blessedone seynt Woltrude.</L>
<L>&thorn;ey wenton anone &thorn;o home &amp; taryeden no lengur &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e contre of Wyltone was &thorn;o fulle gladde</L>
<L N="3040">&amp; thongedon god mekelyche &amp; seynt Ede, &thorn;at blessud may,</L>
<L>For &thorn;use blessude relekes &thorn;at &thorn;ay &thorn;ere &thorn;o hadde &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche ben &thorn;ere &yogh;et in-to &thorn;is day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also &thorn;ey hadden seynt Wultrude in gretter honour</L>
<L>&thorn;en euer &thorn;ey hadden &thorn;at tyme byfore,</L>
<L N="3045">By-cause of seynt Ywen, &thorn;at gode confessour,</L>
<L>&amp; of seynt Ede, &thorn;at blessud virgyn, &thorn;at was of hurre body bore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; also for &thorn;at gret somme of golde so rede</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche he payede to &thorn;use clerkus also,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche weron for sorwe so clene w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t rede</L>
<L N="3050">&amp; so sore wepyng boskede hem hamarde to go;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; also for &thorn;e grette cost &thorn;at he hadde y-do</L>
<L>Vpone seynt Ede chirche &amp; vpone hurre abbay a litulle byfore &mdash;</L>
<L>For he hadde y-wallede welle &thorn;at abbay alle-abou&yogh;t &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; purposede herre forto han y-do &yogh;et gret cost more. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3055">Bot god, &thorn;at is knower of alle thyng clerely</L>
<L>&amp; ordeynyth hit after his owne wylle,</L>
<L>Nolde not suffre herre no lengur to leue here bodyly,</L>
<L>Bot ordeyned &thorn;at he shulde come hurre dou&yogh;ter tylle;
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="69"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And send doune to hurre a messyngere of sekenesse</L>
<L N="3060">And badde her hey&yogh;e and make hurre alle redy,</L>
<L>For he shulde come vp to &thorn;at holy place</L>
<L>&amp; dwell &thorn;ere euer in ioy bothe glad &amp; mery.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;e vtaus of hurre dou&yogh;ter, seynt Ede, hit was</L>
<L>&thorn;at seynt Wultrude was y-clept &thorn;us vp to heuene</L>
<L N="3065">To almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;at is so fulle of grace,</L>
<L>Of a bry&yogh;t angel w<SUP>t</SUP> myelde steuene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e on and twentythe day of Septembre forsothe hit was</L>
<L>&thorn;at seynt Wultrude soule past vp to blys,</L>
<L>A seynt Mathies day &thorn;orwe goddus my&yogh;t &amp; grace</L>
<L N="3070">Hurre soule from hurre body departyde ys</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;t vp to &thorn;e blisse of heuene</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> angels, &thorn;at weron bothe bry&yogh;t &amp; shene;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche song lowde w<SUP>t</SUP> myelde steuene</L>
<L>&amp; brou&yogh;ton hurre to Ede, here dou&yogh;ter, &thorn;at mayden clene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3075">&amp; &thorn;at hit is &thorn;us trew as y &yogh;ow say,</L>
<L>Was afterwarde y-preuyd ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L>When hurre body was y-buryede &thorn;at same day:</L>
<L>For so &thorn;e angel to &thorn;e pepul dude telle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at hurre soule was vp to heuene blys,</L>
<L N="3080">&amp; bad &thorn;at pepull &thorn;erof shulde haue no dou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>"For, forsothe, w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre dou&yogh;ter, seynt Ede, he is,</L>
<L>&amp; a fulIe ioyfulle mayney is herre abou&yogh;te."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o &thorn;ey knew well &thorn;at hurre soule was in &thorn;e folle blys,</L>
<L>&amp; burydon hurre body fast by &thorn;ere as herre dou&yogh;ter lay.</L>
<L N="3085">&thorn;us seynt Woltrude to heuene blys y-past vp is,</L>
<L>In Septembre &thorn;e won &amp; twentythe day;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in &thorn;e &yogh;ere of grace hit was also</L>
<L>After &thorn;at goddus sone was of Mary ybore</L>
<L>A thousonde euene &amp; neron mo,</L>
<L N="3090">&amp; of Etheldrede &thorn;e nyentetene &yogh;ere &amp; nomore. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot now anone after &thorn;is, securly,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at seynt Woltrude was y-buryed fast by &thorn;er as herre dou&yogh;ter lay,</L>
<L>&thorn;er was a lady dwellyng in &thorn;at abbay</L>
<L>&thorn;at wolde vysed hurre tombe eueryche day &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3095">Alflede was &thorn;at ladyes name;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche hadde y-louyd seynt Wultrude ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L>When he was hurre Abbas and hurre dame,<MILESTONE N="233" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And for hurre deth he made gret deylle;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And eueryche day he wolde abyde stylle &thorn;ere in herre stalle</L>
<L N="3100">Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere byfore &thorn;e Tombe of seynt Woltrude,</L>
<L>Tylle he hadde sayde hurre sawter alle,</L>
<L>After &thorn;at maytenys weron y-seyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>From &thorn;e won &amp; twentithe day of Septembre hurre vsse hit was</L>
<L>To say hurre sawter, tylle eystere-day.</L>
<L N="3105">Bot on eyster-day hit felle ry&yogh;t tas:</L>
<L>As he satte &thorn;are, hurre thou&yogh;t he say
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="70"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e clothe &thorn;at honged vpone hurre tombe &thorn;ere &thorn;o</L>
<L>Meue ofte &amp; ftore wondere fast.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. stere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; he was afferde &amp; wolde fayne &thorn;enne han go,</L>
<L N="3110">Bot he durst not meue hurre-self for gast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he loked &thorn;o more entierlocure towarde &thorn;at tombe:</L>
<L>&amp; hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;o &thorn;at he sye by &thorn;e clothe come &thorn;er ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>So fayre and so white &amp; so godelyche a lomb;</L>
<L>&amp; for hit was so fayre, of &thorn;at lomb he nad no dou&yogh;t,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3115">Bot sayde to hurre sustren, &thorn;e whyche setone by-sydus herre &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et to speke hurre was fulle lothe:</L>
<L>"Lowe where is a lomb! a fayre whyte lomb! lo! lo!</L>
<L>See &yogh;e not where &thorn;at whyte lomb abou&yogh;t &thorn;e tombe gothe?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; fel doune asswo &thorn;o to &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L N="3120">Bot hurre sustren reson vp anone &thorn;o in yche a syde</L>
<L>&amp; tokon hurre vp &thorn;o in &thorn;at stounde.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;rye &thorn;e lomb ron abou&yogh;t &thorn;e tomb in &thorn;at tyde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;is lomb had &thorn;is y-ron &thorn;rye &thorn;e tomb abou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Hit went a&yogh;eyn in to &thorn;at same place</L>
<L N="3125">From &thorn;e whyche hit come first ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; aperyd nomore after &thorn;at to hurre face,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot vanysshed away &thorn;o from herre sey&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey seyen &thorn;erof after nomore.</L>
<L>&thorn;is was in &thorn;e mordydy after &thorn;at &thorn;e sonne shone bry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. mortyde.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3130">After &thorn;at &thorn;e Resurreccione was donne in &thorn;at chirche &thorn;ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;us &thorn;is astere-lomb apered &thorn;ere opynlyche in herre sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey my&yogh;t knowelle &thorn;at he was &thorn;ere w<SUP>t</SUP> herre in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>And he w<SUP>t</SUP> hym bothe day and ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;orw his mercy and his gret grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3135">Bot &thorn;enne was dame Alflede fulle glad y-wys</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at sy&yogh;t &thorn;at he saw &thorn;o in &thorn;at place &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; knewelle &thorn;at hurre soule was in heuene blys</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> angels, &thorn;at weron bothe bry&yogh;t and clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is miracle was &thorn;us at Wyltone y-do</L>
<L N="3140">In &thorn;e astere nexste after hurre body-dyenge,</L>
<L>Nexste after &thorn;at hurre soule departyd hurre body fro,</L>
<L>In astere-day &yogh;erlyche in &thorn;e mornyng. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A nother meracle after &thorn;is &yogh;et god dude wyrche<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>For seynt Woltrudys loue, &thorn;at lady fre,</L>
<L N="3145">At Wylton in seynt Edus chirche,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e mowe in story bothe rede and see.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A worshipfulle woman in &thorn;at contre &thorn;o dwelt</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was twolmonthe seke in &thorn;e palsy,</L>
<L>&amp; so seke he was &thorn;at he speke o dwelthe,</L>
<L N="3150">&thorn;at ychemon of hurre had pety &thorn;at dwelt hurre by;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So seke &amp; so febulle forsothe was &thorn;is gode wyff,</L>
<L>For he hadde bothe palsy &amp; &thorn;e feuere quarteyne,</L>
<L>&thorn;at nomon &thorn;at sye hurre by-hette hurre &thorn;e lyff;</L>
<L>&amp; alle a full &yogh;ere he hadde hade &thorn;at harde peyne.
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="71"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3155">So &thorn;at he was brou&yogh;t so ny&yogh;e to &thorn;e deythe &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t nowthere lyge ny sytte, y-wys.</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et he &thorn;ou&yogh;t to seynt Woltrude on pilgremage go:</L>
<L>And in an horsbere yleyde &thorn;ederwarde forsothe he is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Feynt and feble &amp; fulle seke he was</L>
<L N="3160">By &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at he &thorn;edur &thorn;o come.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;orw hurre help &amp; goddus grace</L>
<L>All-hole vpon hurre fete he went home.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On horse or on fote, whether &thorn;at hurre lust,</L>
<L>Holle and fryke &amp; sounde he went home,</L>
<L N="3165">&thorn;e whyche was fulle seke &amp; feble y-wys</L>
<L>&thorn;e first day &thorn;at he to &thorn;at chirche come.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne thre dayes alle-holle was he &mdash;</L>
<L>Suche grace god for hurre &thorn;ere wrou&yogh;te</L>
<L>By-cause of seynt Woltrud, &thorn;at lady fre,<MILESTONE N="234" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3170">&thorn;e wyche mekelyche god for hurre bysou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;enne glad &amp; blythe was eueryche a lyff</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche dwelton abou&yogh;t Wyltone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>What by-cause of &thorn;e hele of &thorn;is gode wyff,</L>
<L>&amp; also of &thorn;e meracle &thorn;e whiche &thorn;er was do. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3175">And &yogh;et a no&thorn;er miracle ychull &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> telle<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was do after &thorn;is for seynt Woltrude sake &mdash;</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as hit was, ychulle &yogh;ow telle euery delle:</L>
<L>Y nyl &thorn;erof no worde to &yogh;ow of fable make,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot euene &thorn;e very trewthe y chulle &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> say,</L>
<L N="3180">Ry&yogh;t as ychaue in trewe story fulle oft y-redde:</L>
<L>&thorn;at a &yogh;ong lady of seynt Ede abbey</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e blody mensone lay so seke stylle in hurre bedde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at euery mon sayde &thorn;at lokede &thorn;at seke body vpone:</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;yff seynt Woltrude hurre &thorn;e rather holpe, he nysbot dedde.</L>
<L N="3185">&amp; beron hurre to seynte Wultrude tombe anone</L>
<L>Alle-y-fere, ry&yogh;t as he lay, hurre &amp; hurre bedde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; kneledone doune &amp; herre preyour &thorn;ere made</L>
<L>To god &amp; to seynt Woltrude also.</L>
<L>&amp; anone after &thorn;at seke lady suche hele hadde</L>
<L N="3190">&thorn;at he my&yogh;t bothe ryde &amp; eke go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;is seke lady was helede &thorn;ere &thorn;us</L>
<L>&thorn;orow &thorn;e merytte of seynt Woltrude, &thorn;at lady fre,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey thongedon alle &thorn;e hey&yogh;e kynge of blys;</L>
<L>&amp; a gode woman forsothe euer after was he. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3195">A nother gretter miracle &yogh;et &thorn;enne &thorn;is<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Jhesu for seynt Woltrude &thorn;ere dude wyrche.</L>
<L>A lytille childe y-bore &thorn;ere wys</L>
<L>Fast by seynt Edes chirche,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>From &thorn;e whyche, sone after &thorn;at he was bore,</L>
<L N="200">His sy&yogh;t was clene y-take hym fro;</L>
<L>His fette &amp; his leggus also weron forlore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t nowther se ny go;
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="72"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a gretter sekenesse in his body he hadde &thorn;erto,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche hadde y-holden hym, sey&yogh;the he was bore:</L>
<L N="3205">Crokedde and blynde he was also,</L>
<L>&thorn;at ychemon helt hym bot as fore-lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;is childe was in suche degre,</L>
<L>&thorn;at all men sayden &thorn;at he nas bot leste,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et byfore seynt Wultrude tombe y-brou&yogh;t was he:</L>
<L N="3210">&amp; &thorn;ere hadde he his hele &thorn;o at &thorn;e laste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For when &thorn;at litull chylde was leyde a-doune byfore &thorn;e tombe</L>
<L>In his bedde, as forte han &thorn;ere y-slepte,</L>
<L>He womblede &amp; tomblede on bak &amp; wombe,</L>
<L>&amp; lowde he cryed &amp; sore he wepte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3215">Bot &thorn;e ladyes &thorn;at in &thorn;e Quere dudden rede &amp; syng</L>
<L>Hadden grete petey of &thorn;is childes sorwe &amp; wo,</L>
<L>&amp; tokon seynt Wultrude profession-rynge</L>
<L>&amp; abou&yogh;t his nekke &thorn;ey hongedone hit &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as sone as &thorn;ey hadden sayde &thorn;us herre preyours &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="3220">&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;e ryng abou&yogh;t his nek was do,</L>
<L>&thorn;e childe hym-self dude &thorn;o vp rere</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere byfore hem vpone his fete bygon to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;us meraclelyche went &thorn;at litulle childe &thorn;ere</L>
<L>Byfore hem vpone his fete in &thorn;at same place,</L>
<L N="3225">&amp; of his sekenesse was hole &amp; fere;</L>
<L>&amp; had his sey&yogh;t eke &thorn;orow goddus grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when &thorn;is childe was holle &thorn;us bothe fote &amp; y&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&thorn;e sexstenes rong &thorn;e belles anon &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;e ladyes song Te deum fulle hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="3230">&amp; all other pepull made &thorn;ere gret ioy also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So gret grace was w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;is gode womon, seynt Woltrude</L>
<L>&thorn;at, what mon &thorn;at hadde vpon hym herre professione-rynge,</L>
<L>Where-euer he satte, stode or hude,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hude = ede.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hym shulnot harme none hevelle thynge;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3235">For so gret vertu was w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at rynge</L>
<L>&thorn;at eueryche seke creature, childe or mon,</L>
<L>Were hit hede-ache or what other thynge,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. where mit ausrad. h.</NOTE></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at ryng his hele he wonne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So blessud a woman was &thorn;is lady seynt Woltrude</L>
<L N="3240">&thorn;at eueryche mon &thorn;o of hurre godenesse spake.<MILESTONE N="235" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Meke &amp; myelde he was w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t prude,</L>
<L>&amp; mony other vertwys he hadde w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t lake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; mony a gret meracle for hurre god wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Welle mo &thorn;en y con wryte now here</L>
<L N="3245">Or thenk or bere now in my thou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ore mon ore childe to teche or lere.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="73"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore of seynt Wultrude y thenge to stynt here,</L>
<L>&amp; speke more of &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede.</L>
<L>&amp; of hurre godenesse ychulle &yogh;ow lere,</L>
<L N="3250">Of suche thyngus as y dede here-byfore in story rede.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot at kyng Etheldrede ychulle bygynne,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was brother to &thorn;is blessude virgyn seynt Ede;</L>
<L>&amp; also he was kyng of Englonde &yogh;et &thorn;ynne,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e mow feynde in story, whose wolde hit rede:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3255">For he regnyd kyng here seuene &amp; thretty fulle &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>In trauelle, in sorow &amp; in gret wo;&mdash;</L>
<L>For his loue was y-slawe his brother, Edwarde &thorn;e marter,</L>
<L>Of his stepmodur, &thorn;e whyche was his dedly fo;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he bou&yogh;t dure his moder gult:</L>
<L N="3260">For after &thorn;at seynt Dunston vp to heuene was go,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms ago mit durchst. a (Bl. ago).</NOTE></L>
<L>He was neuer in peys, where-euer he dwelt,</L>
<L>Bot euer in werre and in meche wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e Denmarkys drovyn hym in to Normandye,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e Duke of Normandye he dwelt long;</L>
<L N="3265">&amp; come a&yogh;eyn to London, &amp; &thorn;ere dude dye;</L>
<L>&thorn;e Denmarkys werre was vpon hym so strong.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot anone after &thorn;at he was dyde,</L>
<L>His sone Edmunde Yronside was sone made kynge.</L>
<L>Bot he regnede not bot Nyenne monethus, as ychaue redde,</L>
<L N="3270">Bot so anone after he made his hendynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Knoude and he weron kyngus here bothe</L>
<L>In won tyme, as ychaue redde;</L>
<L>&amp; euer bytwyne hem was hate &amp; loth</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at he was &thorn;us deydde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3275">Bot at Durre-hurst &thorn;ey fou&yogh;tone bothe y-fere;</L>
<L>&amp; hurre twey hostes stoden stille &amp; duden no loth;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &thorn;ey acordeden hem in suche a manere</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden regne kyngus here bothe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;en sone after dyede Edmunde Hyronesyde,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Rex Conutus.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3280">Ry&yogh;t as y tolde &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> ry&yogh;t now here byfore.</L>
<L>&thorn;o Knoude was made hole kyng of alle Englonde w<SUP>t</SUP> gret pride,</L>
<L>&amp; regnede nyentene &yogh;ere &amp; sumwhat more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Knowde was &yogh;et no trewe cristen-mon</L>
<L>Ny leuede no-thynge on criston lawe,</L>
<L N="3285">&amp; &thorn;e seyntes of Englonde he hated ychone</L>
<L>Ny set by non of hem an hawe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot sone after &thorn;at he was made kynge,</L>
<L>He come to Wyltone, &amp; &thorn;e bysshop of Canterbury come w<SUP>t</SUP> hym eke,</L>
<L>&amp; mony a no&thorn;er gret lordynge;</L>
<L N="3290">For he hulde his householde &thorn;ere &thorn;e whysson-weke.
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="74"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a grette solemnite &thorn;e kyng Knoude made at Wyltone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; mony gret lordys w<SUP>t</SUP> hym weron &thorn;ere y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; mony bysshopus &amp; abbotus weron &thorn;ere &thorn;at tyme also &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; alle for &thorn;e kyngys profit &thorn;is solemnite was made &thorn;er &thorn;o, ywys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3295">For &thorn;e Archebysshop folewode &thorn;e kyng Knoude euermore</L>
<L>&amp; prechede hym &thorn;e lawe of gode algate where-euer he hede:</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o at Wyltone he was y-cristonyde for &thorn;e grete fore<NOTE PLACE="foot">fore = fere fear.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche he hade &thorn;o &thorn;ere of &thorn;is virgyn seynt Ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; as hit was, ychulle &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> now telle,</L>
<L N="3300">Ry&yogh;t as hit felle &thorn;o &thorn;ere by grace.</L>
<L>For ry&yogh;t as &thorn;use lordes seton in halle &amp; had y-etone &amp; dronkon welle,</L>
<L>&thorn;ere come in a kny&yogh;t ary&yogh;t gode pace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; knelede adoune byfore &thorn;at kynge</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "syre, &yogh;yf hit plese &yogh;ow to here,</L>
<L N="3305">I con &yogh;owe telle a wondre thynge</L>
<L>How hit byfelle ry&yogh;t now w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;is abbey here."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Say on, quod &thorn;e kyng &thorn;o, alle &thorn;y wylle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at is plesyng to &thorn;e!"</L>
<L>"Syre, quod &thorn;e kny&yogh;t, &amp; y chulle &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> telle</L>
<L N="3310">A gret marueylle, as thynkuth me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>My page, my lord, &thorn;e whyche dothe my horses kepe,</L>
<L>Rode to &thorn;e reuere, to watere &thorn;e tone;<MILESTONE N="236" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche cast hym inne &thorn;e reuere depe</L>
<L>&amp; lafte hym ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere &amp; come home hym-self anone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3315">Bot when y sey&yogh;e my horse come rennyng home so,</L>
<L>Y drede me fulle sore for some owterage<NOTE PLACE="foot">owterage ist &uuml;ber Rasur geschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And fast ron to &thorn;at reuere &thorn;o:</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere y-drownyd y fonde my page.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when y sey&yogh;e my page y-drownyd &thorn;ere as dede as stone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser V. ist oben a. R. geschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3320">Y cryede after help w<SUP>t</SUP> sorow and wo.</L>
<L>Bot as y stode &thorn;ere my-self alle-one,</L>
<L>A ry&yogh;t fayre lady come me to &thorn;o,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ry&yogh;t as y dude after help &thorn;o calle,</L>
<L>A lady of dignite as &thorn;aw hit were,</L>
<L N="3325">&amp; sayde: " "syre, what dy(s)eyffe is &yogh;ow byfalle?<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. dyeyffe.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; why make &yogh;e so heuy chere?" "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at lady y onswerede &thorn;o mekely</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: " "ma dame, &yogh;e mow welle se here</L>
<L>How my page leythe dede y-drownyd fast &yogh;ow by;</L>
<L N="3330">How shulde y now ben of gode chere?" "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>" "Take vp &thorn;is childe, quo&thorn; &thorn;at lady &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; ley hit in &thorn;e chirche byfore seynt Ede:</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;y page shalle lyue &amp; bothe ryde &amp; go.</L>
<L>Do &yogh;e, syre kny&yogh;t, as y &yogh;ow now rede!" "
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="75"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3335">&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at &thorn;is lady fanysshede a-way &mdash;</L>
<L>God whot, of hurre saw y nomore.</L>
<L>Bot a &yogh;ong mon &thorn;o come by &thorn;e way</L>
<L>&amp; to &thorn;e chirche &thorn;at page hath bore,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; leyde hym doune byfore &thorn;e chest ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="3340">In &thorn;e whyche &thorn;is blessud virgyn leyth y-closot inne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;e &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e maydones prey&yogh;edone &thorn;o alle y-fere</L>
<L>To &thorn;at blessud virgyn &thorn;at lay &thorn;e chest w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;is childe my&yogh;t haue a&yogh;eyn his lyff,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as &thorn;is lady me sayde byfore;</L>
<L N="3345">To seynt Ede &thorn;us prey&yogh;edone bothe mayde &amp; wyff,</L>
<L>&amp; to Jhesu, &thorn;at was of Mary y-bore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne schortyme, lorde, after &thorn;ys</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e maydenes hadden herre preyours &thorn;us y-made,</L>
<L>&thorn;is childe rose vp, and alyue he ys,</L>
<L N="3350">And now he is bothe mery and glade.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp;, syre, a gret merueylle me thyngyt hit is</L>
<L>&thorn;at ychaue &yogh;ow now y-tolde."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, quod &thorn;e kyng, he nasnot dede &thorn;o, y-wys."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;eysse, for god, quod &thorn;e kny&yogh;t, dede he was &amp; his body golde."<NOTE PLACE="foot">golde = colde.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3355">"&YOGH;oye, syre, quod &thorn;e archebisshop &thorn;o &amp; spake,</L>
<L>Mony grette meracle &thorn;is mayden has do."</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, syre archebysshop, holde &thorn;ou &thorn;y clappe!</L>
<L>For y &yogh;eue no by-leue &thorn;erto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kyng Edgarus dou&yogh;ter yche wene he was,</L>
<L N="3360">Y-kete bot vpon a wenche;<NOTE PLACE="foot">y-kete = y-gotten.</NOTE></L>
<L>How shulde he euer haue suche a grase,</L>
<L>Whose wolde hym-self ry&yogh;t welle by-thenche?"<NOTE PLACE="foot">self ry&yogh;t &uuml;berschr. (Bl. l. &thorn;is st. ry&yogh;t).</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"A, my kyng, quod &thorn;e bysshop, why do &yogh;e so</L>
<L>To &thorn;is blessude virgyn &thorn;at hath y-brou&yogh;t a&yogh;eyn &thorn;is childus lyff?</L>
<L N="3365">Wollede &yogh;e fouchesaue now &thorn;edur to go</L>
<L>And se how hole hurre body &thorn;ere &yogh;et leythe &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; he ley&yogh;e in &thorn;e vrthe &yogh;et &thorn;rettene &yogh;ere &amp; more;</L>
<L>&amp; when he was take vp of &thorn;e vrthe, he was as wholle</L>
<L>And as freysshe as he was ony tyme &thorn;at day byfore &mdash;</L>
<L N="3370">&thorn;e sothe of &thorn;is &yogh;e mowe welle se, &yogh;yf &yogh;e wolle."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Gowe alle &thorn;edur, quod &thorn;e kyng, wollewe go,</L>
<L>To loke wherre hit be so as tolde &thorn;e kny&yogh;t!<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. he tolde mit durchstr. he.</NOTE></L>
<L>For y nelnot byleue &thorn;at hit is redyly so,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;yff y se hit verylyche w<SUP>t</SUP> myn owne sy&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3375">Forthe went &thorn;e kyng &thorn;o thederwarde anone,</L>
<L>And bysshoppus and lordus &amp; abbotes y-fere;</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e chirche &thorn;ey come ry&yogh;t sone</L>
<L>&amp; founden &thorn;e cheste alle-redy &thorn;ere.
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="76"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e bysshop toke &thorn;o a sencere in his honde</L>
<L N="3380">And sensede &thorn;at body, &thorn;ere hit lay,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde "my lord, wolle &yogh;e come heder &amp; nere stonde</L>
<L>&amp; se &thorn;at hit is very trewe &thorn;at y dude &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> say!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en come &thorn;e kyng &amp; stode hym fast by.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e bysshop toke vp &thorn;e lede of &thorn;e chest anone:</L>
<L N="3385">&amp; &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at mayde sawe howe hole he &thorn;er ley&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&amp; to lawe hurre to scorne &thorn;e kyng &thorn;o bygone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;o &thorn;at mayde rerede vp hurre body euery whytte<MILESTONE N="237" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And gederede to-gedere hurre lymmys &thorn;o &yogh;eke<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. lymnys. &yogh;eke = eke.</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; made a sygne as &thorn;aw he wolde &thorn;e kyng haue smytte</L>
<L N="3390">W<SUP>t</SUP> hurre fust vndur his cheke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;e kyng sawe &thorn;at mayden do so,</L>
<L>He was alle assmayhydde &amp; dredde hurre &thorn;o fulle sore</L>
<L>&amp; fell doune to &thorn;e grounde ded asswo &mdash;</L>
<L>Was he neuer so sore agast &thorn;at tyme byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3395">&thorn;e bysshop toke vp &thorn;e kynge &amp; comforde hym w<SUP>t</SUP> alle his my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And sayde: "syre kyng, haue &yogh;e no drede</L>
<L>Bot trust welle god, &thorn;e whyche made bothe day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And mekelyche cry hym mercy &amp; seynt Ede!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"I crye hurre mercy, quod &thorn;e kyng to &thorn;e bysshoppe &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="3400">&amp; bysuche herre mekelyche &thorn;at he wolde hit me for&yogh;eue</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at ychaue to hurre eny tyme amys y-do;<NOTE PLACE="foot">to hurre &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ychulle do herre worshippe euer whyle y leue;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; trewelyche ychulle euer by-leue in gode</L>
<L>&amp; studfastelyche holde me in cristone feythe,</L>
<L N="3405">&amp; do to &thorn;is abbay both worshippe &amp; gode</L>
<L>By-cause of &thorn;is holy virgyn &thorn;at here now leythe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng from knelyng rose vp &thorn;o anone</L>
<L>&amp; went to seynt Gabriellus auter &thorn;ere fast-by</L>
<L>&amp; offerede vp &thorn;ere golde &amp; syluer and ryalle stone:</L>
<L N="3410">&amp; toke his leue &thorn;ere at hem alle &amp; went his wey.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; euer after &thorn;at he louede ry&yogh;t welle seynt Ede</L>
<L>And worshepude hurre name in euery plase;</L>
<L>&amp; what-euer hym nededde, to hurre he bede,</L>
<L>&amp; euer by hurre he hadde help &amp; grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3415">Bot ofto-tymes on pilgremage</L>
<L>&thorn;at blessud virgyn he wolde come to &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;awe he were kyng &amp; of gret lynage,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et mekelyche on fote wolde he to hurre go &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;ere shull neuer non horse of hys</L>
<L N="3420">&thorn;at he &thorn;ou&yogh;t euer vpon to ryde,</L>
<L>Come wt-inne &thorn;at place y-wys</L>
<L>Ny ny&yogh;t ny day &thorn;ere abyde;
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="77"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as sone as he come ny&yogh;e &thorn;at plase,</L>
<L>Adoune on fote he wolde &thorn;en &thorn;ere ley&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3425">&amp; go to hurre tombe vpon his fote a soft pace,</L>
<L>Whether hit were day or ny&yogh;t. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot in short tyme after &thorn;is</L>
<L>His owne contrey visitede he wolde;</L>
<L>For &thorn;edur &thorn;ere weron y-comyn enmys</L>
<L N="3430">&thorn;e whyche weron strong &amp; bolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP> meke hert &thorn;o he prey&yogh;ede &thorn;at may:</L>
<L>As he was virgyn trewe and clene,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde be his help in his iorney&yogh;e</L>
<L>And breng hym sone &amp; sounde a&yogh;ene.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3435">&amp; when he had &thorn;us his preyours y-made,</L>
<L>&thorn;en went he forthe vpon his way;</L>
<L>&amp; seynt Ede in mynde he hade</L>
<L>Bothe by ny&yogh;t &amp; eke by day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And spedde ry&yogh;t welle alle his iournay,</L>
<L N="3440">&amp; scomfede his enmyes &amp; droff hem ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; come hamwarde, when he tyme say,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> gladsome hert, &amp; nothyng prou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he was in &thorn;e gret see hammartwarde,</L>
<L>So gret a storme of wedur on hym fell &thorn;o</L>
<L N="3445">&thorn;at he nas neuer ere so sore aferde</L>
<L>Ny neuer in hert half so wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is tempest was so hoge &amp; so horrible &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Off wynde, off reyne, of thondere y-fere,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle &thorn;e Gables of &thorn;e shippe &thorn;ey broston a-to;</L>
<L N="3450">&amp; ychemon of his deth had &thorn;o gret fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e shipmen losten hurre wytte for drede</L>
<L>And sayden, of shipmonnus craft &thorn;ey cowthe nomore,</L>
<L>And sayden: "syre kyng, we conne no rede,</L>
<L>We trowyn &thorn;at we ben now y-lore."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3455">&thorn;e kyng was carefulle &thorn;o in hys &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&amp; commandede &thorn;e water and &thorn;e wynde to haue reste.</L>
<L>Bot of his commaundyng &thorn;ey &yogh;eue ry&yogh;t nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Ny &thorn;ey a-bey&yogh;edone hem no-thyng to &thorn;e kyngus hest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"What gode is hit, quod &thorn;e kyng &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="3460">Forto be a kynge of remys thre?</L>
<L>&thorn;is tempest obeyeth hym nomore me to,<MILESTONE N="238" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Shipmon, &thorn;en hit dothe to &thorn;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot where art &thorn;ow now, &thorn;ou blessed mayde seynt Ede?</L>
<L>Come hedur, &yogh;yff &thorn;ou mow, &amp; help now me</L>
<L N="3465">And breng me ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is gret drede!</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;yff y may lyue, ychull white hit &thorn;e."<NOTE PLACE="foot">white = quite.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as sone as &thorn;e kyng had sayde &thorn;at worde,</L>
<L>Seynt Ede stode ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere &thorn;is kyng byfore</L>
<L>Fast by &thorn;e shippus borde</L>
<L N="3470">And sayde: "syre kyng, drede &yogh;ow nomore!
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="78"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo ycham here now, &thorn;e same mayde Ede</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche &yogh;e clepton ry&yogh;t now here-byfore.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is wedur take &yogh;e none drede,</L>
<L>For hit shalle greue &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> no-more!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3475">For yche haue preyede to hym &thorn;at diede &thorn;orow Pilatys dome,</L>
<L>To &thorn;e whyche alle wedres obey&yogh;en hem to,</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue &yogh;ow grace to come sounde home;</L>
<L>&amp; he hath me grauntyd &thorn;at hit shalle be so."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;en &thorn;is blessud virgyn, seynt Ede,</L>
<L N="3480">At &thorn;e kyng toke &thorn;o hurre leue,</L>
<L>And byfore his shippe vpon &thorn;e water &yogh;ede</L>
<L>And wayuede &thorn;e wedur away w<SUP>t</SUP> hur sleue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o was &thorn;e wether bothe myelde &amp; stylle</L>
<L>&amp; greuede hem after &thorn;at tyme nomore;</L>
<L N="3485">Bot hadden &thorn;e wedur ry&yogh;t at hurre wylle</L>
<L>And reden hamewarde fast w<SUP>t</SUP> seylle &amp; hore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And saue &amp; sounde he come in to Englonde &thorn;orwe goddus my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> alle his men, kny&yogh;t, squyere, &yogh;omone &amp; page.</L>
<L>And to Wylton sone after &thorn;at he hym dy&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3490">On fote to go to seynt Ede on pylgrymage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He hey&yogh;ede hym &thorn;edurwarde fulle fast</L>
<L>And come to Wiltone bothe mery and gladde,</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t w<SUP>t</SUP> hym of wax a mast;</L>
<L>&amp; mony a gret lorde w<SUP>t</SUP> hym he ladde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3495">And when he to &thorn;at chirche &thorn;ere come,</L>
<L>To seynt Edes tombe &thorn;o he went anon</L>
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP> his mowthe he cust hit oft &amp; lome &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot a ryalle masse was &thorn;enne &thorn;ere y-done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;enne byhulde he &thorn;at body so clene</L>
<L N="3500">How hit lay &thorn;er inne &thorn;at trenne chest,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t freysshe &amp; rody, saue hit was lene,</L>
<L>&amp; euery leyme holle, bothe mest &amp; lest.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Full worthy were &thorn;is body, quod &thorn;e kyng &thorn;o,</L>
<L>To haue a schrene of syluer &amp; golde fulle feyne,</L>
<L N="3505">&thorn;e whyche vpone &thorn;e see to me come so</L>
<L>And delyuerede me &thorn;ere from gret care &amp; peyne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng clepte his treserere to hym &thorn;o anone</L>
<L>&amp; badde &thorn;at he shulde blyue &thorn;en go</L>
<L>And take syluer &amp; golde ry&yogh;t gode wone,</L>
<L N="3510">&amp; to delyuer hit to a goldesmy&yogh;t, to make a shrene &thorn;at body to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is treserere went forth &thorn;o &amp; dud ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e kyng hym badde,</L>
<L>And toke a large somme of golde &amp; delyuered ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at tresery,</L>
<L>&amp; to twey goldsmy&yogh;tus hit was y-ladde,</L>
<L>To make a large shrene for &thorn;at blessud virgynus body.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3515">&thorn;e kyng &yogh;aff also to &thorn;e Goldsmy&yogh;tthus a gret charge &thorn;o</L>
<L>To take golde &amp; syluer ry&yogh;t gret plente,</L>
<L>&amp; bad hem make hit long &amp; large y-now wt-owten ony scate (!)</L>
<L>. . . . .
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="79"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;use goldsmytthus toke &thorn;e golde &amp; syluer y-now w<SUP>t</SUP> hem</L>
<L N="3520">&amp; home to hurre house w<SUP>t</SUP> hem hit ladde.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ey toke &thorn;e cursede feynde to hurre conselere &thorn;en</L>
<L>To stele &thorn;at tresere, &amp; made &thorn;e shrene meche lasse &thorn;en &thorn;e kyng hem bad.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. make?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ey duden after &thorn;at cursede feyndus redde</L>
<L>And maden &thorn;at shrene to short by half a fote &amp; more,</L>
<L N="3525">And stele &thorn;at tresere w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;ten ony manere drede</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at blessud virgyn or of Jhesu, &thorn;at was of Mary y-bore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; off &thorn;e kyngus precepte &thorn;ey token non hede</L>
<L>Ny of no worde &thorn;at &thorn;e kynge to hem dude say,</L>
<L>Bot duden wonlyche after &thorn;e deuellys rede</L>
<L N="3530">And by stelthe toke meche of &thorn;at tresere away.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot all-&thorn;aw &thorn;ay hadde &thorn;is gold &thorn;us y-stole<MILESTONE N="239" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And put hit inne a preuey plase,</L>
<L>&YOGH;et alle &thorn;is dude &thorn;is mayde thole</L>
<L>&amp; to wyrche vp herre werk he &yogh;aff hem space;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3535">&amp; hadden herre hele, to make &thorn;at shrene w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t mayme or herte.</L>
<L>Bot forte reseyue &thorn;at blessude body of &thorn;at mayde &thorn;ynne,</L>
<L>By half a fote &amp; more hit was &thorn;o to sherte:</L>
<L>&thorn;is body by half herre leggys lenthe hit nolde not &thorn;er-inne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is blessud mayde clew&yogh;the vp herre leggus herre to</L>
<L N="3540">And dressud hurre body w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;at shrene fulle honestly.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e kyng gretlyche in his hert meruaylede &thorn;o</L>
<L>When he sey &thorn;at dede body meue alle hurre lemys so delyuerly,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; sayde: "&thorn;e my&yogh;t of god w<SUP>t</SUP> blessud virgyn hit is</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche &yogh;efthe &thorn;is mayde grace to worche on &thorn;is manere;</L>
<L N="3545">For a wonderfulle meracle forsothe &thorn;is now is</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche he has now y-do byfore vs here."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey closede &thorn;e shrene &thorn;o &amp; set hit vp &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as hit stonte &yogh;et in-to &thorn;is same day.</L>
<L>&thorn;e kyng toke his leue of &thorn;at mayde w<SUP>t</SUP> ry&yogh;t gode chere</L>
<L N="3550">&amp; towarde his chambre anone after he toke &thorn;e way.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e lordus pastone forth after also anone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor after ist &thorn;o durchstr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; ladyes &amp; maydeyns &amp; alle other y-fere;</L>
<L>So &thorn;at &thorn;ere lafte neyther childe ny other mone,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e Goldsmy&yogh;tthus &thorn;ey tweyn y-fere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3555">For alle &thorn;e seruyse was clene solemplyche ydone,</L>
<L>Mateyns &amp; masse &amp; alle y-fere,</L>
<L>&amp; alle maner peple home weron gone,</L>
<L>Bothe kny&yogh;ttus &amp; squyers &amp; ladyes clere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e golde-smytthus knewen ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L N="3560">&thorn;at alle &thorn;e peple was &thorn;us ou&yogh;t of chirche a-go,</L>
<L>&thorn;en went &thorn;ey &thorn;ederwarde as &thorn;is tresere lay fulle snelle,</L>
<L>Preuelyche forto han y-stole hit a-way &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach 3517 fehlt 1 Vers (Bl. l&auml;sst ihn nach 3522 fehlen), oder 3517 schliesst mit large (i. R. zu charge) und das Folg. bildet den letzten Vers. scate st. scante?</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="80"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And tokon vp from &thorn;e plase &thorn;at hit was Inne,</L>
<L>&amp; thou&yogh;ton to han y-stole hit away w<SUP>t</SUP> hem so.</L>
<L N="3565">Bot &thorn;ey my&yogh;t no fote &thorn;er-w<SUP>t</SUP> go &thorn;ynne,</L>
<L>For ou&yogh;t &thorn;at euer &thorn;ey my&yogh;t &thorn;o do;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;ey weron as bleynd alle bothe y-wys</L>
<L>As euer was ony stok or stone.</L>
<L>"A, felowe, quod &thorn;e ton, for gode, now w<SUP>t</SUP> vs hit it amys!</L>
<L N="3570">Alas, felowe, alas, what shulle we nowe done?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ey walkede in &thorn;at chirche vp &amp; doune,</L>
<L>Beryng in herre hondys &thorn;at stole tresere &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey nadde no grace other-wyesse to done,</L>
<L>Bot opynlyche in herre hondys &thorn;ey duden hit bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3575">&thorn;en come &thorn;e sexsten to serche &thorn;e chirche</L>
<L>&amp; forto haue closede &thorn;e dorus of &thorn;e chirche to:</L>
<L>&amp; sey hem in an hyron &thorn;ere so lorche.</L>
<L>&amp; askede hem what &thorn;ey dedon &thorn;ere &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Alas, syre, quod &thorn;e tone of hem &amp; bygon to speke,</L>
<L N="3580">&thorn;at euer we weron mene in-to &thorn;e worlde bore!</L>
<L>For seynt Ede has owre falsnesse so sore vpon vs wreke</L>
<L>&thorn;at we ben vndone for euer here-after more.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For deyd i wote welle &thorn;at we shulle be</L>
<L>When &thorn;e kyng knowyth &thorn;at we &thorn;is golde han &thorn;us ystole.</L>
<L N="3585">&amp; also we mowe no-thyng w<SUP>t</SUP> oure ynon see</L>
<L>Ny mow not putte &thorn;is golde of owre honden in to non hole,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot bere hit &thorn;us in ychemonnus opyn sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle men may wondere vpon vs two.</L>
<L>Bot to haue &thorn;is shame we han gret ry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="3590">For &thorn;e gret falsnesse &thorn;at we to &thorn;is mayde han do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot, gode sexsten, now prey&yogh;e we &thorn;e &mdash;</L>
<L>For we durnot speke oure-self for drede &mdash;</L>
<L>To (pray) alle &thorn;e ladyes of &thorn;is plase &amp; maydens fre</L>
<L>To speke to &thorn;e kyng &thorn;at we ben not dede,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3595">Bot &thorn;at we my&yogh;t of owre lyff haue somme grace,</L>
<L>&thorn;at we my&yogh;t oure synnus here amende;</L>
<L>For a gret synne we han y-done here in &thorn;is place,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e whyche now we ben here bleynde;<MILESTONE N="240" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden mekelyche prey also</L>
<L N="3600">To &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue vs grace, henne ere we go,</L>
<L>Vs forto amende of owre mysdede."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is sexsten &thorn;en grauntede hem &thorn;o &thorn;at he wolde so do,</L>
<L>&amp; forthe he went &thorn;enne vpone his way,</L>
<L N="3605">Tylle he come &thorn;ere &thorn;at ladyes to,</L>
<L>And tolde hem alle &thorn;at he had y-sey&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;use ladyes wentone &thorn;o &thorn;e kyng towarde,</L>
<L>Also bleyue as &thorn;ey my&yogh;tone towarde hym go,</L>
<L>To telle hym &thorn;e cause why &thorn;e shrene was so short</L>
<L N="3610">&amp; how &thorn;e goldsmethus hade don<SUP>e</SUP>, also.
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="81"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e kyng had &thorn;use ladyes herde</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e processe of &thorn;e sexsten also,</L>
<L>He merveyllede hym gretlyche in his hert,</L>
<L>&amp; in to &thorn;e chirche he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;en to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3615">&amp; forth he went a ry&yogh;t gode pace,</L>
<L>&amp; in to &thorn;at chirche he come sone &thorn;o:</L>
<L>&amp; fonde &thorn;e goldsmethus mepyng vp &amp; downe in &thorn;at same plase,<NOTE PLACE="foot">mepyng = mopyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>As &thorn;ey hadde long byfore &thorn;at tyme y-do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; spake to hem &thorn;o what hym lust.</L>
<L N="3620">Bot &thorn;ey euer mekelyche prey&yogh;eden hym of his grace;</L>
<L>&amp; he for-&yogh;aff hit hom at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Byfore &thorn;e ladyes ry&yogh;t in &thorn;at place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &yogh;et &thorn;ey my&yogh;t not no fote &thorn;ennys go,</L>
<L>Bot stodon stylle &thorn;ere blynde in &thorn;at place;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. stoden?</NOTE></L>
<L N="3625">Tyll &thorn;e kyng &amp; &thorn;use ladyes also</L>
<L>Hadden prey&yogh;ede seynt Ede to graunte hem somme grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot seynt Ede grauntede hem &thorn;o sone herre wylle</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e goldsmy&yogh;thus shulden &thorn;o ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e chirche &thorn;en go.</L>
<L>&amp; laften &thorn;e golde &thorn;ere leygyng &thorn;o fulle stylle</L>
<L N="3630">&amp; wenton forthe hurre way w<SUP>t</SUP> sorwe &amp; wo,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; eythere of hem went home to his wyff.</L>
<L>Bot as bleynde as a betulle &thorn;ey weron euermore,</L>
<L>&amp; beggers &thorn;ey weron also alle herre lyffe,</L>
<L>For alle grace and worship &thorn;ey hadden forlore. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3635">And when &thorn;e kyng had y-sey&yogh;e alle &thorn;is meracles &thorn;us y-do<NOTE PLACE="marg">Legenda Edithe.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;at seynt Ede was so forthe-fult &thorn;orowe goddus grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. forthe-fulle, in forthe-fult corr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Meche worshepe &amp; gret cost to &thorn;at plase he dude &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And euer after &thorn;at tyme a fulle gode leuer he was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; meche gode he &yogh;aff &thorn;is abbay of Wyltone to</L>
<L N="3640">&amp; confermede alle thyng &thorn;e wheche was y-&yogh;eue &thorn;erto byfore,</L>
<L>&amp; repayrede &thorn;e chirche &amp; &thorn;e abbay also &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was by werre almost forlore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And mony werkemen he sette to amende &thorn;at chirche,</L>
<L>&amp; masonus &amp; carpenters &amp; blemmeres also,</L>
<L N="3645">&amp; mony o&thorn;er men, diuerse werkes &thorn;ere to wyrche &mdash;</L>
<L>For gret cost he sette vpon &thorn;at abbay &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot among &thorn;e werkemen &thorn;e whyche wrou&yogh;tone &thorn;ere &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche weron &thorn;us y-hyred by Knoude &thorn;e kyng,</L>
<L>A nother gret meracle &thorn;ere was y-do,</L>
<L N="3650">Sone after &thorn;is blessed virgynes shrynyng. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hit byfelle in a litull toune &thorn;at was &thorn;e abbay byside</L>
<L>&thorn;at a domme childe &thorn;er-inne was of his moder y-bore,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche &thorn;at tyme couthe bothe go and ryde</L>
<L>&amp; werche what werk &thorn;at he my&yogh;t haue, hys fode fore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">hys fode fore &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="82"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3655">&thorn;e whyche amonge &thorn;use werkemen yche day dud wyrche:</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> an hors &thorn;e wheche he hadde, of lytulle pryse,</L>
<L>He ladde stones from &thorn;e quarey to &thorn;e chirche,</L>
<L>Late &amp; erlyche &mdash; &thorn;at was his labour &amp; his vse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot worde spake he neuer none byfore,</L>
<L N="3660">Whether men dude to hym ry&yogh;t o&thorn;er wronge &mdash;</L>
<L>For of his modur doume he was y-bore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. doume st. domme.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; also he was w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te ony tonge;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tong ny speche, as y &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> nowe say,</L>
<L>Hadde he neuer none byfore, securly.</L>
<L N="3665">Bot hit byfelle sone after vpon a day</L>
<L>&thorn;at he and his horse weron bothe wery:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; in to a medwe &thorn;at was &thorn;ere byside</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> his horse &thorn;o &thorn;edur went he</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t a whyle &thorn;ere to abyde &mdash;</L>
<L N="3670">For &thorn;ere was gras ry&yogh;t gode plente;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And leyde doun hys hede &thorn;ere to a stone,<MILESTONE N="241" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Somme rest or slepe &thorn;ere to haue,</L>
<L>For he was seke and wery &amp; euylle bygone &mdash;</L>
<L>For meche trauelle had &thorn;at knaue; &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3675">For see &amp; here he my&yogh;t ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L>&amp; wolde do alle werkus &thorn;e wyche men hym tau&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot he couthe nowther tale ny telle</L>
<L>What &thorn;at euer was in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he was leyde &thorn;ere &thorn;us doun to slepe,</L>
<L N="3680">A fulle graciose sweuene &thorn;o mette &thorn;ere he:</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at a fayre lady stode at his fete</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "Syric, herken &thorn;ou well &amp; take hede to me,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;at &thorn;ou thenk vpon &amp; do ry&yogh;t as y &thorn;e say:<NOTE PLACE="foot">ry&yogh;t &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou shalt haue &thorn;y tong &amp; &thorn;y speche also.</L>
<L N="3685">Bot in &thorn;e ny&yogh;t &thorn;at cometh nexste byfore seynt Jonys day</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e chapelle byfore seynt Ede tombe &thorn;ou most go,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;ere &thorn;ou most abyde alle &thorn;at ny&yogh;te</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;y hert &thorn;ou most prey&yogh;e seynt Ede to be &thorn;i leche:</L>
<L>&amp; othemorwe, or hit be day-ly&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3690">&thorn;ou shalte haue &thorn;y tong &amp; eke &thorn;y speche."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot sone after &thorn;at Syryc a-woke of his slepe,</L>
<L>&amp; of his sweuene gret merueylle he hadde,</L>
<L>&amp; in his hert for gladnesse sore he wepe,</L>
<L>&amp; in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t to seynt Ede his preyours he made</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3695">&amp; prey&yogh;ede seynt Ede of hurre godenesse</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde fouchesaue to be to hym suche a leche,</L>
<L>So &thorn;at he my&yogh;t han in &thorn;at forsayde plase</L>
<L>As &thorn;e lady to hym sayde, bothe his tong &amp; his speche.
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="83"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when he hadde made his preyours &thorn;us<NOTE PLACE="foot">made &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3700">To &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L>He toke his horse &thorn;o anone y-wys</L>
<L>&amp; mekelyche towarde his werke he &yogh;ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; euery day wrou&yogh;t he fulle trewely, y-wys,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;e tyme was comen clene &amp; gone also,</L>
<L N="3705">&amp; seynt Jonys ny&yogh;t also y-comen hit is</L>
<L>In &thorn;e whiche to &thorn;e chirche he shulde haue go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &yogh;owthe of hym-self &amp; heygyng of other children also<NOTE PLACE="foot">heygyng = eggyng.</NOTE></L>
<L>Maden hym to for&yogh;ete his sweuene &amp; go to sey&yogh;e hem play;</L>
<L>Wherfore he sone for&yogh;ate in to &thorn;e chapell to go</L>
<L N="3710">&thorn;ere as seynt Edus blessud body &thorn;o lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he hadde a while walkude &thorn;us</L>
<L>Among &thorn;e children &amp; sey&yogh;e hem play,</L>
<L>A grete ache in to his hede y-comen ys;</L>
<L>Wherfore he nadde no delyte in no gamme &thorn;at he sey&yogh;e,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3715">Bot &thorn;ou&yogh;t to his bedde to go &thorn;o fulle heuene.</L>
<L>&amp; when he was towarde his bedde goyng,</L>
<L>&thorn;o he &thorn;ou&yogh;t first vpone &thorn;e sweuene</L>
<L>&thorn;at he hadde mette, in &thorn;e medwe slepynge. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot almy&yogh;ty god, &thorn;at alle hathe wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3720">&thorn;orowe &thorn;e desire of &thorn;at virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L>Put &thorn;at mynde in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;e ache, &thorn;at god put for &thorn;at cause in to his hede. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he had &thorn;is sweuene &thorn;us y-comen in to his meynde,</L>
<L>Towarde &thorn;e chapelle he hym drawe &amp; come &thorn;edur at &thorn;e last.</L>
<L N="3725">Bot &thorn;e durus of &thorn;at chapelle weron &thorn;o y-teynde</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e &yogh;atus abou&yogh;t &thorn;at place weron y-stoke fast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he clomb vp by a walle y-made of stone</L>
<L>&amp; in to &thorn;at chapell full sone come he &thorn;o.</L>
<L>Bot w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;at chapelle ly&yogh;t of candelle &thorn;er nas none,</L>
<L N="3730">Ny mon ny womon bot he hym-self, no mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot his hedde woke so sore, y-wys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">woke st. oke schmerzte.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he &thorn;ou&yogh;t somme-where forto leyge doune to slepe:</L>
<L>&amp; in a hyron y-leyde to slepe forsothe he is.</L>
<L>Bot a wondre sweuene &thorn;ere con he &thorn;o mete:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3735">Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at a semely lady come &thorn;ere inne,</L>
<L>In to &thorn;at same plase &thorn;ere-as he to slepe &thorn;o lay.</L>
<L>&amp; from his fore-toppe doune to his chynne</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> hurre ry&yogh;t honde he mette &thorn;at way;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as he streke doune hurre honde by his face so,</L>
<L N="3740">Somwhat ou&yogh;t of his mowth, hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t, he toke.</L>
<L>He slepte not fast byfore &thorn;at tyme, for wo,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en his hert fullyche a-woke.
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="84"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; to his mowthe &thorn;o his honde he dode,</L>
<L>To loke what-manere thyng hadde be &thorn;ere.</L>
<L N="3745">Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at his mowthe was &thorn;o fulle of blode &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o in his hert he hadde grete fere!<MILESTONE N="242" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; lest &thorn;at holy plase w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at blode y-folude shulde be,<NOTE PLACE="foot">y-folud = fouled, defiled.</NOTE></L>
<L>Byfore his mowthe his owne hond he dede;</L>
<L>&amp; stylle his hond ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere forsothe so hulte he</L>
<L N="3750">&amp; ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at chapelle in gret hast he hedde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In to a fayre medwe &thorn;e whyche was &thorn;ere-byside &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere ron a broke, bothe fayre &amp; clere,</L>
<L>&amp; he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he wolde &thorn;ere a stounde abyde</L>
<L>&amp; wasshe his honden &amp; his mowthe fulle clene &thorn;ere;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3755">&amp; towarde &thorn;at broke fulle fast he ron,</L>
<L>His mowthe &amp; his honden &thorn;er to wasshe.</L>
<L>Bot beside in &thorn;e medwe &thorn;er stode a mone</L>
<L>&amp;, how he was, anon he dude hym asshe.<NOTE PLACE="foot">how = who.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A prest w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;at abbay dude dwelle,</L>
<L N="3760">Sire Brytric men duden hym &thorn;ere calle &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was be-louede &amp; byleuede ry&yogh;t welle</L>
<L>Bothe in chirche, cloystre &amp; eke in halle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e cause of syre Brytryc beynge &thorn;er &thorn;at tyme was &thorn;is &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche y thenk now to &yogh;owe telle &mdash;:</L>
<L N="3765">Sire Brytric hadde a gode horse, y-wys,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche he louede ry&yogh;te welle:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Forsothe, to pastere &thorn;at horse he was &thorn;ere &thorn;o;</L>
<L>&amp; for he was &yogh;ong, &amp; bothe wylde &amp; ley&yogh;t,</L>
<L>He hadde y-fedryde to-gedur his leygus two;</L>
<L N="3770">&amp; for drede of thefus he hadde y-kepte hym &thorn;er meche of &thorn;at ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as he stode &thorn;ere by his horse so,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is Syric Mute he hadde a sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; askede how he was &thorn;at was &thorn;ere &thorn;o<NOTE PLACE="foot">how = who.</NOTE></L>
<L>In suche tyme of &thorn;e ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3775">"I cham Syric Mute, quod he &thorn;o &amp; spake anone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at am here nowe, &thorn;e wheche here &yogh;e see."</L>
<L>Syre Britric stode stylle as ony stone</L>
<L>&amp; merueylede hym muche &thorn;at hit was he;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayde: "Siric sone, what dostow &thorn;ere by &thorn;at broke?</L>
<L N="3780">How may&yogh;te &thorn;ow speke now &thorn;us to me?"</L>
<L>"&YOGH;ey&yogh;e, sire, quod he, &yogh;yf &yogh;e ben in ony dou&yogh;t, come hedur &amp; loke!</L>
<L>And trewlyche alle ry&yogh;t as hit ys, y chull telle &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Britric merueylede &thorn;o greteliche in his thou&yogh;t</L>
<L>And come to Syric &thorn;o ry&yogh;t anone;</L>
<L N="3785">&amp; Syric tolde syre Britric ry&yogh;t so as he hadde wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;yng ry&yogh;t as he hadde y-done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&YOGH;e, quod Brytric, seynt Ede is cause of &thorn;is.</L>
<L>Bot gowe to &thorn;e abbay now bothe anone</L>
<L>&amp; bydde alle &thorn;e ladyes &thorn;at &thorn;ey vp rys</L>
<L N="3790">&amp; ryng herre bellus now euerichone."
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="85"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot forth &thorn;ey wentone &thorn;o vpone herre gate</L>
<L>&amp; comen &thorn;edur anone bothe two,</L>
<L>&amp; knokkede fast &amp; lou&yogh;de at &thorn;e &yogh;ate.</L>
<L>Bot twey ladyes come &thorn;edur &thorn;o anone &amp; speke hem to</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3795">&amp; askede who was &thorn;ere &amp; whomme &thorn;ey wolden haue.</L>
<L>"Opon &thorn;e durre, my lady! quod Britric &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. vpon.</NOTE></L>
<L>For here nys bot Syric, &thorn;e mute knaue,</L>
<L>&amp; y my-self, lady, and nomo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Syric hathe his speche, my lady, &mdash; what is &yogh;our rede? &mdash;</L>
<L N="3800">&amp; his tong also &amp; may speke ry&yogh;t welle,</L>
<L>&thorn;orow &thorn;e grace of god &amp; of seynt Ede;</L>
<L>Shalle not &thorn;e sexsten reng &thorn;e belle?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Why, may Siric speke?" quod &thorn;is lady &thorn;o.</L>
<L>"&YOGH;e, for god, quod Siryc, my lady, &thorn;at y may,</L>
<L N="3805">&amp; my tong ychaue nowe also,</L>
<L>&thorn;orow grace of seynt Ede, &thorn;at blessud may."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;use ladyes herden hym speke &amp; eke hym sy&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; mony other men &thorn;at knew hym fulle welle,</L>
<L>&thorn;is ladyes song &thorn;o Te deum an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="3810">And &thorn;e sexstens rong &thorn;o &thorn;e belle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ioyfulle &thorn;ey weron &amp; grete myrthus made</L>
<L>By-cause of &thorn;is meracle &thorn;at &thorn;ere was y-do,</L>
<L>&amp; gret gladnesse in hert ychemon hadde,</L>
<L>Mon &amp; womon &amp; children also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3815">&amp; to shewe &thorn;at &thorn;is meracle was verelyche so,</L>
<L>Syric dwelte euer after in &thorn;at place,</L>
<L>And neuer ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at plase dude he go,<NOTE PLACE="foot">ist hinter 3186 geschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot euer seynt Edus seruande &thorn;ere he wase. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thys myracle was do by-for seynt Ede<MILESTONE N="243" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">Dieser V. ist oben a. R. zugesetzt.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3820">Of kyng Knowde &thorn;e nyentethe &yogh;ere, y-wys.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at same &yogh;ere &thorn;e kyng dyede, as y dude rede;</L>
<L>And at Lundone y-buryed he ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when he had made &thorn;us his endyng<NOTE PLACE="foot">3822-3 sind a. R. nachgetragen.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; his soule to heuene was past,</L>
<L N="3825">Haralde, his sone, was made &thorn;o kyng</L>
<L>After &thorn;at tyme in ry&yogh;t grette hast. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; in Haraldus tyme a nother gret myracle &thorn;er felle, y-wys,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche, ry&yogh;t as hit felle, y chulle &yogh;ow telle.<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>For hit byfelle in Haraldus tyme ry&yogh;t tys</L>
<L N="3830">&thorn;at a gret lorde dude w<SUP>t</SUP> hym dwelle:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Agamundus men clepte hym &thorn;o;</L>
<L>A lord of &thorn;e kyngus conselle forsothe was he,</L>
<L>&amp; seruede he dude quene Emme also,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche was &thorn;e kyngus modur &amp; lady fre.
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="86"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3835">&thorn;is gret lord Agamundus, of &thorn;e wheche y spake of byfore,</L>
<L>Was a false, couetyse mon, y-wys, &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; so was his fadre hym by-fore,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche tau&yogh;t hym euer to don amys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is Agamundus to &thorn;e abbay of Wylton had gret enuy<NOTE PLACE="foot">gret &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3840">&amp; &thorn;e lordshepe of Ferlande couetede fast &mdash;</L>
<L>For hit lay ney&yogh;e his plase &thorn;er bye</L>
<L>&amp; to his lordshepe &thorn;e merus duden last.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; long for hit, for-sothe, he pladde.</L>
<L>Bot when he sey&yogh;e &thorn;at he my&yogh;t not haue hit by no way of ry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3845">By lordshepe &amp; maystry he hit hulte &amp; hadde,</L>
<L>&amp; quene Emme to &thorn;at lordshepe he herre dy&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so he hulde hit twey &yogh;ere and more,</L>
<L>By strenghte &amp; lordeshepe of quene Emme,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Enme.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche had maynteynyd hym gretly byfore</L>
<L N="3850">By-cause he &thorn;ou&yogh;t to ben heyre &thorn;erof after hym.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot sone afterwarde he felle in to suche dygre</L>
<L>&thorn;at gret sekenesse come his body to;</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle his frendus of hym hadden gret pyte,</L>
<L>And of his dethe &thorn;ey dou&yogh;teden gretlyche also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3855">And drowyn abou&yogh;t hym theke and faste,</L>
<L>For he drowe &yogh;erne towarde his last hende.</L>
<L>Bot sone after &thorn;ey weron fulle sore agaste</L>
<L>When he was clene ou&yogh;t of his myende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he cryedde &amp; rorede as &thorn;aw he were wode,</L>
<L N="3860">&amp; badde alle his frendys help hym &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "alas, &thorn;at euere y toke seynt Edus gode,</L>
<L>&thorn;at my body is nowe &thorn;erfore sorwefulle &amp; wo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Helpe me now, frendus, alle y &yogh;ow mekelyche prey,<NOTE PLACE="foot">alle &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> alle &yogh;our powere &amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> alle &yogh;our my&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="3865">&amp; &thorn;at &yogh;e wolden gon to quene Emme &amp; to hurre sey</L>
<L>&thorn;at Ferelande is seynt Edus lordshepe by ry&yogh;t;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; say &thorn;at hurre maystry is so gret ouer me</L>
<L>&amp; herre chere so horrible to my sy&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at y shalle neuer dede ere be</L>
<L N="3870">Tylle he haue a&yogh;eyn hurre londe &amp; herre ry&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For in euery plase he is &thorn;ere redy</L>
<L>When my soule wolde passe me fro,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hit nys no tyme so hardy</L>
<L>Ou&yogh;t of my body forto go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3875">And &thorn;us y shalle lyue here in peyne,</L>
<L>For y shall neuer deyde here be</L>
<L>Tylle seynt Ede haue hurre lond a&yogh;eyne.</L>
<L>&thorn;erfore go &yogh;e to quene Emme &amp; prey hurre &thorn;at he come to me!"
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="87"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Towarde quene Emme &thorn;ey token herre way,</L>
<L N="3880">W<SUP>t</SUP> carefulle hert &amp; drewry chere;</L>
<L>&amp; sone after to quene Emme &thorn;o come &thorn;ay<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne in sone u. to &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>And tolden herre &thorn;e case ry&yogh;t as hit was, alle y-fere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. his st. hit.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And prey&yogh;eden herre &thorn;at he wolde fouchesaue to come hym to</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> alle &thorn;e hast &thorn;at he well my&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="3885">Bot he nadde no gret wylle to hym to go,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde &thorn;at seynt Ede to &thorn;at londe hadde no ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;ey prey&yogh;eden so ofte &amp; so lome,</L>
<L>&thorn;at at &thorn;e last he grauntede &thorn;erto</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde to hym &thorn;edur come</L>
<L N="3890">And help hym ou&yogh;t of his grette wo.<MILESTONE N="244" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o come Emme &thorn;edere after sone, as he hem sayde.</L>
<L>And when he sey hym peyne so, of hym he had gret pete</L>
<L>And prey&yogh;ede seynte Ede, &thorn;at blessud mayde,</L>
<L>To haue mercy vpone him, as he was mayden fre;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hem st. him.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3895">And restored &thorn;e lordshepe of Ferlande a&yogh;eyn</L>
<L>To seynt Edus abbay, y-wys.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en was &thorn;is wrechede mon fulle fayne</L>
<L>And mekelyche &thorn;ongede &thorn;e kyng of blys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And mekeliche he cryed seynt Ede mercy &thorn;o</L>
<L N="3900">&amp; prey&yogh;ede herre on hym to haue rewthe &amp; pete.</L>
<L>And so dude quene Emme &thorn;o also,</L>
<L>&amp; knelyng full sore &thorn;o wepte he</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; made hurre preyours on &thorn;is manere:</L>
<L>"Blessed virgyn, quod &thorn;e quene Emme &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="3905">Haue mercy vpone &thorn;is synfull mon here</L>
<L>&amp; suffre his soule ou&yogh;t of his body go!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also on me, blessud virgyn, haue somme pyte,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche mayntenede &thorn;is synfulle wreche longe,</L>
<L>&amp; let me neuer y-dampned &thorn;erfore y-be:</L>
<L N="3910">&amp; y chull amende to &yogh;ow, mayde, &thorn;at y dude wronge."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e quene hadde made hurre prey&yogh;erus &thorn;us,</L>
<L>Anone after &thorn;o dyede &thorn;at seke wreche mon;</L>
<L>&amp; his soule sone after towarde heuene-blys</L>
<L>Ou&yogh;t of his body forthe dude &thorn;o gon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3915">And quene Emme mekely &thorn;onged god &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; also &thorn;is blessude virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L>And meche tresere he &yogh;aff &thorn;at abbay to &mdash;</L>
<L>Wherfore he meche &thorn;e better dude spede. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And anone after kyng Haralde dyede &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="3920">&amp; his brother Hardeknowde was made kyng &thorn;o anone.</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche regnede here bot &yogh;eres two,</L>
<L>&amp; Haralde regnede byfore hym foure &yogh;ere &amp; won. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &yogh;et in Hardeknowdus tyme a nother meracle was do</L>
<L>In &thorn;e chirche off Wyltone by-fore seynt Ede, so fulle of grase,</L>
<L N="3925">And byfore seynt Wultrude, hurre blessud modur, also.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e meracle y chull &yogh;ow tell ry&yogh;t as hit wase.
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="88"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ere was a mynchun w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne &thorn;at abbay &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche was come off hey&yogh;e lynage;</L>
<L>And a gret lorde he hadde to Cosyn also,</L>
<L N="3930">&thorn;at dude to &thorn;at abbay gret ou&yogh;trage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For a parcell of londe he toke away</L>
<L>A&yogh;eyne &thorn;e ladyes wylles ychon,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche ry&yogh;twyslyche to &thorn;at abbay lay;</L>
<L>And drede of seynt Ede also he nadde non.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3935">Bot sone after &thorn;at hit felle by cas</L>
<L>&thorn;at a grette sekenesse come hym to,</L>
<L>&thorn;at to his dey&yogh;the ny&yogh;e brou&yogh;te he was.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e lady, his Cosyn, was send to hym &thorn;o,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he was w<SUP>t</SUP> hym best y-knowe, y-wys,</L>
<L N="3940">And sayde: "Bryxyn cosyn, y prey&yogh;e &yogh;owe mekely</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e wolden fouchesaue to &yogh;eue vs &thorn;e londe a&yogh;eyn &thorn;at ouren is,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. ouron?</NOTE></L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of god almy&yogh;ty;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And thenk on, Bryxyn cosyn, how dredfulle hit is<NOTE PLACE="foot">cosyn &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>To by-reue holy chirche his possessione;</L>
<L N="3945">For he shall neuer come in blys</L>
<L>Tyll he haue made restitucione."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Pes! Elburwe Cosyn, quod Bryxyn &thorn;one,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou angrus me &thorn;at y am ney&yogh;e wode!</L>
<L>For of &thorn;at londe &yogh;e gette neuere none,</L>
<L N="3950">Ny of myn non other gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For of my gode &yogh;e gete ry&yogh;t none,</L>
<L>Non y my-self nyl not be y-buryed &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>&thorn;aw y shulde now ou&yogh;t of &thorn;is worde gone,</L>
<L>My body shalle neuer come &thorn;edur on bere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3955">&thorn;erfore, Elburwe, speke &yogh;e of &thorn;at mater nomore</L>
<L>And angur me no-more, now y &thorn;e pray!</L>
<L>For ychulle holde &thorn;e othe &thorn;at iche haue swore:</L>
<L>&YOGH;e get neuer none &thorn;ere, by my fay!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">by &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when Elburwe sye non other wone,</L>
<L N="3960">&thorn;at he my&yogh;t no thyng haue atte hurre wylle,<MILESTONE N="245" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He rose vp &thorn;o sone after &amp; home dude gon,</L>
<L>&amp; spake nomore, bot hult hurre &thorn;o stylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is wreche lay stylle, &amp; sone after dede he was,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche set no prise by &thorn;is virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L N="3965">&amp; was y-buryed in a nother plase, &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; for his synne afterwarde fulle euelle dude spede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For gret sorwe &amp; gret pyne afterwarde hadde he,</L>
<L>As hit was ry&yogh;t welle y-knowe to mony a mone</L>
<L>&amp; as by visionus hit was ofte y-sey &amp; also y-prouyd in verite:</L>
<L N="3970">For after his deythe his spirite in peyne abou&yogh;t dude gone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And agast sore men bothe ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>Abou&yogh;t &thorn;at contrey in mony a place,</L>
<L>&amp; ladyes also in seynt Ede abbay &mdash;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e whyche Elburwe, his owne Cosyn, forsothe on was.
<PB REF="00000097.tif" N="89"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3975">For to herre he apparede so horribyliche, y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; in so meche peyne &amp; in so meche wo,</L>
<L>&thorn;at gret pyte, to here hit y-tolde, hit ys &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; so he dude ofte to mony one mo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For vpone a ny&yogh;t he apparede to hurre ry&yogh;t &thorn;us,</L>
<L N="3980">As y challe &yogh;owe telle veriliche in dede:</L>
<L>He mette in slepe &thorn;at he was in &thorn;e chirche, y-wys,</L>
<L>Stondyng byfore &thorn;e shrene of seynt Ede,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mony other men &amp; wemmen, hurre bedus to bydde.</L>
<L>Amonge &thorn;e whyche he sey&yogh;e &thorn;at cursede Bryxin come,</L>
<L N="3985">&thorn;e wheche was hurre owne cosyn fulle sybbe,</L>
<L>Stondyng in an heyron &thorn;ere, an horribulle, foulle grome,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In an heyron &thorn;ere byfore &thorn;e auter of seynt Ede,</L>
<L>&amp; hoggyliche lokede vpone herre w<SUP>t</SUP> horrible chere</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "help, Elburwe! help me now in &thorn;is nede!</L>
<L N="3990">Seystow &thorn;ou not what sorwe y haue &amp; how gret fere?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now, dure cosyn, w<SUP>t</SUP> alle my my&yogh;t y prey now &thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e wolden stonde by-twynne me &amp; seynt Ede!</L>
<L>For fore all &thorn;e gode in &thorn;e worlde y nolde herre se &mdash;</L>
<L>Of hurre ychaue so gret fere &amp; so gret drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="3995">Hurre my&yogh;t and hurre maystry so grete nowe ys,</L>
<L>Hurre hate is peyne, sorwe and gret wo.</L>
<L>Alas, &thorn;at euer y dude to hurre ony thyng amys!</L>
<L>For ou&yogh;t of herre sy&yogh;t y not whodere to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot hurre lofsom chere were now leuere to me</L>
<L N="4000">&thorn;en alle &thorn;e gode &thorn;at euer on vrthe was wrou&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L>So meche sorwe &amp; peyn ychaue euery day hurre to se,</L>
<L>&amp; where-euer &thorn;at y hyde me, y cham ou&yogh;t-sou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;en for &thorn;e pete &thorn;at he hadde of hurre cosines sorwe &amp; wo</L>
<L>Fulle sore a-fry&yogh;t he a-woke &amp; brayde ou&yogh;t hurre slepe,</L>
<L N="4005">&amp; by-hulte how horribiliche Bryxin from hurre dude go;</L>
<L>&amp; for sorwe &amp; pyte he brake ou&yogh;t &thorn;o &amp; sore wepe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; sayde: "lo, Bryxin Cosyn, &thorn;ou noldust not after me werche</L>
<L>Bot euer-more haue &thorn;yn owne wylle,</L>
<L>&amp; setteste nou&yogh;t by seynt Ede ny by hurre chirche</L>
<L N="4010">Bot &thorn;ou toke hurre londe from hurre w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ony resone or skylle;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And now &thorn;ou leyste in gret sorwe &amp; in gret peyne,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e falffenesse &thorn;at &thorn;ou duste &thorn;is abbay &thorn;o to,</L>
<L>And now hit nysnot in &thorn;y powere to &yogh;eue &thorn;at londe a&yogh;eyn.</L>
<L>Alas, Bryxin Cosyn, what woltowe now for sorwe do?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4015">Bot when Elburwe hadde made &thorn;us herre moyn</L>
<L>To god of heuene &amp; to &thorn;is blessede mayde seynt Ede,</L>
<L>Towarde hurre chambre he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;o to gone &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere he durst no lengur abyde for drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e ladyes &thorn;at weron &thorn;at tyme w<SUP>t</SUP> Elburwe &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="4020">Of &thorn;is grete fraye &thorn;e wheche &thorn;ey sie and herden, weron sore agast,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ey durst not abyde no lengur &thorn;ere for fere</L>
<L>Bot hey&yogh;edone hem towarde hurre chamburs fast.
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="90"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;use ladyes weron a-resone vp, to han y-gon on &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Towarde herre chambrus for gast euerychon,</L>
<L N="4025">&thorn;ey herdyn Bryxin make a schryke, w<SUP>t</SUP> routhefulle chere,</L>
<L>And sayde: "abyde, ladyes, &amp; saythe a Pater noster, or &yogh;e gone!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Abyde, Elburwe Cosyn, now mekeliche y prey &thorn;e,</L>
<L>&amp; make &thorn;y preyours mekelyche to seynt Ede,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde haue pyte &amp; rewthe of me &mdash;</L>
<L N="4030">For y darre nowhere abyde to speke w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre for drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For my peyne is euer more and more<MILESTONE N="246" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And my sorwe encresseth euery day.</L>
<L>Alas &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at y was inne y-bore</L>
<L>Or &thorn;at y euere &thorn;at lond of seynt Edus knewe or sy&yogh;e!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4035">And w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at Bryxin vanysshede away &amp; spake nomore,</L>
<L>Bot grundede &amp; gronede he dude fulle sore &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And went forthe lyke as &thorn;aw he were forlore,</L>
<L>&amp; long afterwarde in sorwe &amp; peyne abou&yogh;t dude go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e heyres &thorn;e wheche hadde &thorn;at londe, sie welle &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="4040">&thorn;at Bryxin hadde so meche peyne &amp; sorwe &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>&thorn;ay restoredone hit a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;at abbay, y-wys,</L>
<L>And cryede mekeliche &thorn;o seynt Ede mercy &amp; hore,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayden: "blessede lady, haue &yogh;e mercy &amp; pite of vs,</L>
<L>&amp; also on Bryxin, &thorn;e wheche is in so gret peyne &amp; wo!</L>
<L N="4045">For we wylle neuer displese &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> after thus,</L>
<L>Bot ben &yogh;owre seruaundys for euer &amp; hoo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so &thorn;ey made herre prey&yogh;erys after &thorn;at euery day</L>
<L>&amp; kneledone full oft seynt Edus shrene byfore:</L>
<L>Tylle Bryxin was clene ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at contre y-go away,</L>
<L N="4050">&thorn;at &thorn;ey herdyn of hym in &thorn;at contre nomore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot to say &thorn;at his soule is dampned for euer-more,</L>
<L>Hit is a poynte of owre byleue;</L>
<L>Bot y nyl not &thorn;erof speke now to &yogh;ow no lore,</L>
<L>For y nyl not deme nomon here.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4055">Bot &thorn;e best we shulle ratherest byleue to,</L>
<L>For goddus mercy passeth alle &thorn;e gode werkus &thorn;at he dude wyrche.</L>
<L>Bot depe dampnacyon god byhetuth alle &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at by-reuy&yogh;the ony possessione from holy chirche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For he dyede w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;te ony repentaunce,</L>
<L N="4060">As &thorn;e story telluth to me:</L>
<L>Wherfore, y chod welle, he hath meche myschaunce,</L>
<L>Where-euer he dwelle or be. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot of hym y nyl now speke nomore</L>
<L>Bot speke of a nother meracle as gret as &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="4065">How hit byfelle in kyng Edwardus tyme Confessore &mdash;</L>
<L>For in kyng Hardeconutus tyme forsothe was &thorn;is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot kyng Hardeknowde deyde after &thorn;is grete wondur anone;</L>
<L>&amp; seynt Edwarde, his brother, was cronyd &thorn;o kynge.</L>
<L>And &thorn;is gret meracle in his tyme was donne,</L>
<L N="4070">&thorn;e XVII &yogh;ere of his regnynge;
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="91"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e tyme of Henry &thorn;e Imperour hit was also,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e &thorn;ousonde &amp; two &amp; sixsty &yogh;ere after &thorn;at goddus son was bore,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e bysshop (Bruno) of Culayne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Nach bysshop fehlt der Name Bruno; s. 4207. &mdash; Bl. Tulayne?</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is gret meracle was y-donne &thorn;e wheche y touchede byfore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4075">In Almayne &thorn;er was a toune, y-wys,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Colebek hit hadde &thorn;at tyme to name,</L>
<L>&amp; a chirche of seynt Magne &thorn;er-inne &thorn;o wes:</L>
<L>&thorn;ere on mydwyntrus ny&yogh;t &thorn;is meracle was done of so grete fame.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e parysshe of seynt Magne in Colebek &thorn;er dwelt a mone,</L>
<L N="4080">And Gerleyne was &thorn;at monnus name y-wys:</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche in mydwyntrus-&yogh;evyn to &thorn;at chirche dude gone &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot sone after by hym hit felle alle amys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For by-cause of a womon he &thorn;o &thorn;edur went</L>
<L>&amp; purposede hym to abyde &thorn;er w<SUP>t</SUP> herre alle &thorn;at ny&yogh;t &mdash;</L>
<L N="4085">For vpone &thorn;at mayde was alle his loue &amp; his entent,</L>
<L>To haue hurre to paramour, &yogh;yf &thorn;at he my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he come in to &thorn;at chirche-lyttone &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Twey wemen he founde tere, &amp; priede hem fayche &thorn;at mayde ou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. tere st. &thorn;ere.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; when he was come, he toke hurre on his honde, and XII men mo,</L>
<L N="4090">&amp; daunceden w<SUP>t</SUP> a caralle &thorn;e chirche abou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e daunce he hym-selfen went byfore</L>
<L>&amp; ladde &thorn;at mayden vpon his ry&yogh;t honde;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;us &thorn;ey song &amp; daunceden &thorn;o &thorn;ore,</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle men &thorn;at weron &thorn;ere merueyllede hem, bothe fre &amp; bounde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4095">Bot euer &thorn;ey song &amp; dauncede yliche fast</L>
<L>&amp; nolde not stonte &thorn;ere for no-mone.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e parson hym-self come ou&yogh;t at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>&amp; badde hem &thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde stent hurre song or ellus &thorn;ens gone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey nolde not stynt, for alle &thorn;at &thorn;e parsone my&yogh;t do,</L>
<L N="4100">Bot euer dauncede &amp; songon y-liche fast &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et &thorn;e mayden was &thorn;e parsons <I>dou&yogh;ter &thorn;at</I> Gerlen louede so,</L>
<L>For he wheche &thorn;is daunce so long dude last.<MILESTONE N="247" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;e refret of &thorn;at caroulle, y wene,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche Gerlen &amp; &thorn;is mayden song byfore:</L>
<L N="4105">"Bono rodde be &thorn;e wode so grene,</L>
<L>&amp; mette he w<SUP>t</SUP> Merfunden, &thorn;at semely mayden, &thorn;ore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wharto shulde we langur tary here?</L>
<L>Hey&yogh;e we now fast &amp; go we henne!"</L>
<L>&thorn;is was &thorn;e refryd of &thorn;e caroulle &thorn;at &thorn;ey song &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="4110">&thorn;use thre wemen &amp; &thorn;use threttene men.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;e parson sye &thorn;at &thorn;ey nolde not stent</L>
<L>Bot euer &thorn;ey dauncede yliche fast,</L>
<L>Anon a&yogh;eyn in to &thorn;e chirche &thorn;o he went</L>
<L>&amp; for angur &thorn;us he prey&yogh;ede at &thorn;e last:
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="92"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4115">He pray&yogh;ede to god &amp; seynt Magne, &thorn;at holy marter,</L>
<L>&thorn;at god &amp; seynt Magne wolden gra&umacr;nte &thorn;orow herre grace</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde not rest hem of alle &thorn;at &yogh;ere</L>
<L>To daunce so ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere in &thorn;at same plase.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e parson badde A&yogh;one, his <I>sone</I>, &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="4120">&thorn;at he shulde anon his sustre &thorn;ynne fayche.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o A&yogh;on forthe anon after he dude go</L>
<L>And anon by &thorn;e harme his sustre dude cayche.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Gerleyn hulte hurre honde so fast</L>
<L>&thorn;at o fote my&yogh;t he &thorn;ennys from Gerleyn &thorn;o go.</L>
<L N="4125">Hurre brother wratthede hym &thorn;o at &thorn;e last<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. wracchede.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; askede Gerleyn why he dude holde hurre so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Garleyn no worde my&yogh;t speke to hym &thorn;o</L>
<L>Bot daunce &amp; song euer yliche fast.</L>
<L>&amp; A&yogh;one drowe his sustre by &thorn;e harme so,</L>
<L N="4130">&thorn;at euene by &thorn;e shuldre atwo hit barst.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when he sye his sustre haue suche an harme,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> carefulle hert he sykede fulle sore &amp; sayde alas,</L>
<L>&amp; merueyllede gretlyche in hert &thorn;at &thorn;e arme</L>
<L>So clene from hurre body y-cloue so was.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. cloue st. clene.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4135">For &thorn;ere felle a-way no blodus drope,</L>
<L>Ny no blodus drope was senene &thorn;o &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Ny he toke non hedde &thorn;erof, bot dauncede forthe &amp; song here note</L>
<L>As &yogh;erne and as bysiliche as he dude ere,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And of hurre hurt he toke nomore hede</L>
<L N="4140">Ny &thorn;aw he hadde y-hade no harme.</L>
<L>Bot hurre brother anon in to &thorn;e chirche he &yogh;ede</L>
<L>And to his <I>fader</I> he toke his sustre arme<NOTE PLACE="foot">ist unten a. R. nachgetragen.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And tolde his <I>fader</I> alle &thorn;e processe,</L>
<L>Euery delle ry&yogh;t as hit y-do &thorn;ere was,</L>
<L N="4145">And how of herre song &amp; of herre daunce &thorn;ey my&yogh;t not seysse</L>
<L>Bot songen and dauncedon stylle in &thorn;at same place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e parson merueyllede &thorn;en hym meche of &thorn;is</L>
<L>And sy&yogh;e welle &thorn;at seynt Magne had taken one hem vengaunce,</L>
<L>And dredde hym sore leste he had ou&yogh;te done amys</L>
<L N="4150">To prey&yogh;e so &thorn;at alle &thorn;e &yogh;ere continu&amacr;lyche &thorn;at &thorn;ey shulden so syng &amp; daunce.<NOTE PLACE="foot">tilge &thorn;at vor &thorn;ey.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so &thorn;ey duden synge &amp; daunce so continuanlyche alle &thorn;at &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere in &thorn;at same plase,</L>
<L>And neuer etone ny dronken ny maden other chere,</L>
<L>Ny to sytte ny stonde &thorn;ay nadde no grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4155">&thorn;e parson toke his <I>sone</I> &thorn;o his <I>dou&yogh;ter</I> arme<NOTE PLACE="foot">hier ist cosyn u. systers &uuml;ber radirtem sone und dou&yogh;ter &uuml;bergeschrieben.</NOTE></L>
<L>And badde hym &thorn;at he shulde make a hole in &thorn;e vrthe &amp; &thorn;er-in hit cast,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde &thorn;at hym merueyledde &thorn;at he toke none hede of hurre harme</L>
<L>Bot euer douncede &amp; song y-lyche fast.
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="93"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A&yogh;one toke &thorn;o his sustre arme to hym anone</L>
<L N="4160">&amp; in &thorn;e vrthe w<SUP>t</SUP> a mattok he made a hole &amp; cast hit in &thorn;o,</L>
<L>And leyde &thorn;ere vpon hit a marbulle-stone;</L>
<L>And went to his <I>fader</I> &amp; tolde hym ry&yogh;t so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot on &thorn;e morow, also sone as hit was day,</L>
<L>He went a&yogh;eyn to &thorn;at same place</L>
<L N="4165">&thorn;ere-as he wende his sustre arme hadde y-lay.</L>
<L>Bot, furgode, &thorn;o &thorn;ere hit nace,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. furgode = for god.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot ou&yogh;t of &thorn;e vrthe hit was y-take</L>
<L>And lay a litulle bysyde &thorn;at place.</L>
<L>Bot he toke &thorn;e mattok &amp; a&yogh;eyn &thorn;e putte dude make</L>
<L N="4170">&amp; leyde hit &thorn;o &thorn;ere a&yogh;eyn, ry&yogh;t as hit byfore was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot one &thorn;e morwe he come &yogh;et a&yogh;eyne:</L>
<L>&amp; founde hit lygyng aboue &thorn;e vrthe, ry&yogh;t as hit dude &thorn;e day byfore;</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "now haue y trauellede twey in feynne;<NOTE PLACE="foot">twey in feynne = twice in vain.</NOTE></L>
<L>For god, now nylle y not burye hit nomore."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4175">And in to an hyron he hit &thorn;o cast</L>
<L>Amonge olde ymagys &thorn;at &thorn;o were &thorn;ere. &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot Harry &thorn;e Emperour &thorn;o at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>Made hem hit vp to &thorn;e auter &thorn;ere bere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And close hit in syluer gode and newe<MILESTONE N="248" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4180">And bad hem set hit vp vpone &thorn;e auuter,</L>
<L>In memory of &thorn;is meracle so trewe &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et in-to &thorn;is day hit stont ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en dude &thorn;is wonder spryng so wyde</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle cristen men duden &thorn;erof speke;</L>
<L N="4185">&amp; Harry &thorn;e Emperour dude &thorn;edur &thorn;o ryde,</L>
<L>For to know &thorn;e sothe, &amp; sey hit eke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;ey dauncedone &amp; songen euer yliche fast,</L>
<L>&amp; restede hem neuer, ny&yogh;t ny day,</L>
<L>Ny eton ny dronken, bot euer duden fast,</L>
<L N="4190">Euere-more in on aray;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hem lettede neuer nomonere thynge,</L>
<L>Snowe, forste, wynde, ny reynne,</L>
<L>Bot euer stille &thorn;ey duden daunce &amp; synge,</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;at ny&yogh;t twelmowth were comen a&yogh;eynne.<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. twelmonth. </NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4195">Bot Harry, &thorn;e gode Emperour, hadde gret pyte</L>
<L>When he sawe &thorn;is foulke &thorn;us merueyllyche peynet &thorn;ere:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere u. &thorn;o arere &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; tymbere &amp; carpynters anon &thorn;o ordeynede he</L>
<L>And ouere hem an house he let &thorn;o arere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere u. &thorn;o arere &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when &thorn;is tymbre was fullyche y-dy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4200">And duden hit ouer hem &thorn;er &thorn;o vp rere,</L>
<L>Hit was so clene y-take a-way w<SUP>t</SUP>-inne one ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ere was neuer a pynne stondyng &thorn;ere.
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="94"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as ofto as hit was rerede vp &thorn;ere ouer hem,</L>
<L>As ofto in &thorn;e ny&yogh;t hit was cast doune a&yogh;eyne;</L>
<L N="4205">So &thorn;at hit prophitede &thorn;ere no-thyng hem,</L>
<L>Bot alle &thorn;at trauelle was in veyne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;is bysshop Bruno was made sone after &thorn;at pope &thorn;en;</L>
<L>&amp; when he was y-sacryd pope, he was clepte Leo.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e Emperour Harry went to Rome &thorn;en &mdash;</L>
<L N="4210">Bot &thorn;ey abydden &thorn;er stylle &amp; dauncedon fast &amp; song to.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e nexste mydwynter after, &thorn;e same tyme of &thorn;e ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>In &thorn;e wheche &thorn;e prest hadde cursede hem so,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey styntone herre song &thorn;orow goddus my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&amp; come in to &thorn;e chirche alle-y-fere &thorn;o.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. in to, in ist ausradirt?</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4215">&amp; when &thorn;ey in to &thorn;e chirche y-comen were,</L>
<L>Strey&yogh;t vpon &thorn;e pament &thorn;ey leyden hem a-doune,</L>
<L>And thre dayes &amp; thre ny&yogh;tys &thorn;ey slepten &thorn;ere,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. splepten.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ore euer ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at place &thorn;ey duden gone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;at mayden dyede anon ry&yogh;t &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="4220">And in same place y-buryede he was.</L>
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e remanent forthe &thorn;en alyue duden go</L>
<L>On pilgremage in to mony a place &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &thorn;at tyme &thorn;ere dyede nomo<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere &uuml;bschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at mayden, &thorn;e parsons dou&yogh;ter, alle-one.</L>
<L N="4225">And alle herre clothus as clene were &thorn;o</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey weron &thorn;e same day &thorn;at &thorn;ey duden hem one,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; as hole &amp; as freysshe &thorn;ey weron also<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. Memoldus.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; as clene w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t spotte ore wemme</L>
<L>As &thorn;ey weron &thorn;at same day &thorn;o</L>
<L N="4230">When &thorn;ey duden hem furst vpone hemme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot herre lymmus shokone euermore</L>
<L>&amp; alle herre body was euer mevynge,</L>
<L>And nere neuer so able as &thorn;ey werone byfore,</L>
<L>For euer, where-euer &thorn;ey hedone, &thorn;ey wentone dauncynge;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4235">Herre song &thorn;ey laftone &amp; songon nomore</L>
<L>Bot clene weron deliueryd of &thorn;at wo,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ey shokon welle-ney&yogh;e as fast as &thorn;ey duden byfore:</L>
<L>Wherfore on pilgremage ychon of hem boskede hem to go.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; wenton so on pilgremage abou&yogh;t in to euery londe,</L>
<L N="4240">&amp; euery mon by hym-self dude &thorn;o go,</L>
<L>Hopyng &thorn;orowe gode preyours of gode seyntus of herre sekenes to be vnbounde&mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at was &thorn;e cause &thorn;at &thorn;ey wentone on pylgremage &thorn;o so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e nomes of hem &yogh;yf hit lust &yogh;ow to here,</L>
<L>Y chulle hem to &yogh;ow wryte euerichone,</L>
<L N="4245">Of men &amp; wemen bothe y-fere:</L>
<L>Gerleyn was &thorn;e name of &thorn;e first mone,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thedericus, Meinoldus, Obberte, &amp; Bono,</L>
<L>Gerardus, A&yogh;elene, Folpolde, Hilbronde, &amp; Wet&yogh;elo,</L>
<L>Alwarde, Benne, &amp; Odoricus also &mdash;</L>
<L N="4250">&amp; of men dauncyng &thorn;ere nere nomo;
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="95"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Anna was &thorn;e maydenus name,</L>
<L>Merfunden, Vmbecynam &thorn;e to&thorn;er two were calde, y-wys;</L>
<L>A&yogh;one was hurre brother name,</L>
<L>Robarde &thorn;e parson y-clepud he weys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4255">Bot Theodoricus into Englond on pilgremage come &thorn;o:<MILESTONE N="249" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>For knowlage of seynt Edwarde forsothe had he,</L>
<L>And of seynt Ede meche he herde speke &thorn;ere also;</L>
<L>Wherfore on pilgremage he come to &thorn;at mayde fre.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To Wyltone, to hurre owne place,</L>
<L N="4260">On pylgremage forsothe &thorn;o sone come he,</L>
<L>To prey&yogh;e herre of herre blessud grace,</L>
<L>And &thorn;at he my&yogh;t by herre &thorn;ere y-helyd be</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;at gret quakyng &thorn;e whyche he hadde in his lemys ichone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms. ist &thorn;ey durchstr. u. he &uuml;bschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; when he come to Wyltone in to seynt Ede abbay,</L>
<L N="4265">Byfore hurre shrene mekeliche he knelede doune vpone a stone</L>
<L>&amp; mekeliche bysou&yogh;t seynt Ede, &thorn;at blessede may,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To send hym rest &amp; hele, &yogh;if hit were herre wylle,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at grete peyne &amp; wo &thorn;e whiche he hadde suffrede longe.</L>
<L>And &thorn;e cause of alle his sorwe to &thorn;e ladyes &thorn;er dude he telle,</L>
<L N="4270">&amp; how &thorn;ey dauncedone alle a &yogh;ere &amp; also a caroulle songe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en hadde &thorn;use ladyes gret pyte of hym</L>
<L>&amp; of his felowys bothe, &amp; gret merueylle &thorn;ey hadden also;</L>
<L>And bysiliche &thorn;ey prey&yogh;eden to seynt Ede &thorn;o for hym</L>
<L>To sende to &thorn;at seke wreche hele &amp; rest of his gret wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4275">&amp; ychemon &thorn;at hym sye, hadde gret pyte</L>
<L>Of his gret sorwe &amp; of his gret wo,</L>
<L>And prey&yogh;eden to god &amp; to seynt Ede for hym fulle bisiliche;</L>
<L>And euer askede hym what countrey he come fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; he hem tolde euer among</L>
<L N="4280">&thorn;e cause of his sorow &amp; of his wo,</L>
<L>&amp; of &thorn;e dauncyng &amp; of herre songe,</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;e Emperour dude to hem also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;re dayes &amp; &thorn;re ny&yogh;tus he lay ry&yogh;t so,</L>
<L>&thorn;e most parte flatte byfore seynt Ede vpone &thorn;e grounde.</L>
<L N="4285">Bot &thorn;e fourthe day god &amp; seynt Ede token hede hym to</L>
<L>&amp; maden hym of his sekenesse bothe hole &amp; sounde,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As hole as euer he was ony tyme byfore;</L>
<L>&amp; his lemys weron heuene &amp; strey&yogh;te &thorn;o euerychone,</L>
<L>Ny his body meuyd ny shoke after &thorn;at nomore</L>
<L N="4290">Bot was as stable &amp; styll as ony stone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he was gladde &amp; ioyfulle in his hert &thorn;o!</L>
<L>And so weron all &thorn;e pepull &thorn;o &thorn;e whyche weron in &thorn;at plase,</L>
<L>&amp; gretliche &amp; hey&yogh;elyche &thorn;ey thongedon god also</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde to seynt Ede graunte so grette grace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4295">And &thorn;e ladyes song &thorn;o Te deum an hey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; sexstenus rong &thorn;e bellus &thorn;o also;</L>
<L>&amp; Thedoricus for ioy &amp; gladnesse wepte w<SUP>t</SUP> his ey&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&amp; euerymon was gladde for &thorn;is miracle, &thorn;ere &thorn;us y-do.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere &thorn;us &uuml;bschr.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="96"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bry&yogh;twythe was abbas &thorn;o of &thorn;at plase</L>
<L N="4300">When &thorn;is meracle &thorn;ere &thorn;us was y-do;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. scheinbar whon.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e fest of &thorn;e Annunciacyone of owre lady hit was,</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e thre &amp; twentithe &yogh;ere of seynt Edwarde also. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e nexste &yogh;ere after &thorn;at &thorn;o dyede &thorn;at blessud thynge,</L>
<L>Seynt Edwarde, &thorn;at worthy confessour.</L>
<L N="4305">And Haralde, Godwynus sone, was made &thorn;o kynge,</L>
<L>To alle Englonde gret doloure.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He regnede here bot nyne monethus, y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; was y-slawe at Hastyngus off Willyham Conquerour,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hastyng<GAP>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere as &thorn;e Abbey of Batelle &yogh;et is &mdash;</L>
<L N="4310">To all &thorn;e reme &thorn;o of gret dishonour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; anon after &thorn;at Haralde was &thorn;ere y-slawe,</L>
<L>Willyham Conquerour was made here kyng,</L>
<L>&amp; made newe lordus &amp; eke new lawe</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e tyme of his regnynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4315">After &thorn;at goddus sone of Mary was bore</L>
<L>A thousande &amp; sixsty &amp; sixse hole &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Willyham Conquerour to &thorn;e kyndam of Englonde was core;</L>
<L>&amp; on &amp; twenty wynter he regnede here. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">4075-4318) Dieses auf deutschem Boden spielende Mir. betrifft die Sage vom Veitstanz. &mdash; In 4101 ist dou&yogh;ter, 4119 sone, 4142 u. 3 u. 4162 fader ausradirt und von sp&auml;terer Hand <I>cosyn</I> &uuml;bergeschrie|ben, nur in 4224 ist dou&yogh;ter stehen geblieben. Es schien anst&ouml;ssig dass der Pfarrer Kinder hatte.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of a nother miracle now ychulle &yogh;owe telle,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4320">&thorn;e whiche felle in &thorn;e tyme of Will. Conquerour.</L>
<L>A crebulle byside &thorn;e Abbay of Wyltone &thorn;at tyme dude dwelle,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche was a seke, maymot wreche, lyuyng in gret dolour.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e whiche hadde no mo lemys &thorn;en hadde a stoke,</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;e tyme &thorn;e whiche he was y-bore in-to &thorn;at day;</L>
<L N="4325">Bot he hadde a gret hedde leyge to a gret blok;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e flesshe from &thorn;e stobbus of his lymus was clene a-way.<NOTE PLACE="foot">of his lymus a. R. nebengeschrieben.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A foule difformed creature forsothe was &thorn;is,</L>
<L>Leyge to a foule lompe of caren, w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t lemys leygyng &thorn;er!</L>
<L>And iche day leygyng at &thorn;e chirche-dure in a couche he was,</L>
<L N="4330">To aske almys of pylgremys; &thorn;erfore men duden hym &thorn;edur bere.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;erfore &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>His body was smalle, leyge to a childe of &thorn;re &yogh;ere age,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor smalle ist gret ausgestr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot his hedde was gret, leyge to a gret malle;</L>
<L>For-sothe, he was an vnlofsom page<MILESTONE N="250" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="foot">vor page ist grome aus|punktirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And a foule difformede creature &thorn;orow-ou&yogh;t alle!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4335">Bot in a ny&yogh;t by swene forsothe he mette,</L>
<L>As he lay in his couche one slepe:</L>
<L>&thorn;at, &yogh;yff ony mon his couche wolde byfore seynt Ede sette,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shulde haue alle his lymus &amp; his hele eke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is sweuene in his &thorn;ou&yogh;t he bare forth &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="4340">Tylle othe morwe &thorn;at men beron to &thorn;e chirche-durre &thorn;at febulle heyne;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;is wreche prey&yogh;ede &thorn;e men mekelyche &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden bryng hym byfore seynt Edus shryne,
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="97"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; tolde hem &thorn;o fulle securly anone</L>
<L>&thorn;at, &yogh;yf &thorn;ey wolden fouchesaue so to do,</L>
<L N="4345">&thorn;at he shulde haue his lemys euerychone</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he shulde haue his hele also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;use men weren credeable of seynt Edus godenasse</L>
<L>And duden ry&yogh;t as &thorn;e crebulle hem badde:</L>
<L>&amp; byfore seynt Edus shryne y-sette he was.</L>
<L N="4350">And thre dayes and thre ny&yogh;tus he &thorn;ere a-badde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is sweuene he met &thorn;e thryd ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As he lay in his couche &thorn;ere a-slepe:</L>
<L>Hym &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at (he) sye a lady bry&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">he fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>Stondyng at his beddus fete,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4355">&amp; sayde; "Huchyn! slepustow fast!</L>
<L>A-wake ande herken what y say,</L>
<L>&amp; be &thorn;ou no-thyng of me agast:</L>
<L>Bot loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou ryse vp as sone as hit is day!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;orowe his godenesse</L>
<L N="4360">&amp; &thorn;orow &thorn;e besechyng of seynt Ede, &thorn;at leythe in shryne here,</L>
<L>Hathe grauntyd &thorn;e hele of &thorn;i sekenesse</L>
<L>&amp; ry&yogh;t shappe of &thorn;y lemys y-fere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at &thorn;is semely lady vanysshede a-way,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is crepull mon a-woke of his slepe:</L>
<L N="4365">&amp; as sone as hit was day,</L>
<L>Ou&yogh;te off his bedde ley&yogh;tlyche he lepe,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hole &amp; sounde in yche degre,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> lemys clene &amp; welle-shape.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;en in hert fulle gladde was he</L>
<L N="4370">&amp; ron vp &amp; doune in myrthe &amp; Jape;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And bare a-way his couche anone,</L>
<L>And mekeliche thonged god &amp; seynt Ede,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o he hammarde vpon his fete dude gon</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche was brou&yogh;t &thorn;edur by-twene foure men in his bede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. bedde, ein d ist ausradirt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4375">&amp; leuede longe ten &yogh;ere after &thorn;at</L>
<L>In gode prosperite &amp; in gode hele,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> his trauell his lyf-lode kat,<NOTE PLACE="foot">kat = gat.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; euer louede seynt Ede ry&yogh;t welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; when kyng Williham herd of &thorn;is meracle &thorn;us y-do</L>
<L N="4380">&thorn;orow &thorn;e meryde of &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L>He louede welle seynt Edus abbay after &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; meche gode to hit he oft-tymes dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; alle &thorn;e reme was ry&yogh;t glad also</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at gret meracle &thorn;at god dude &thorn;er wirche;</L>
<L N="4385">&amp; come &thorn;edur on pilgremage monyon &thorn;o</L>
<L>In worshepe of seynt Ede, of &thorn;e whiche &thorn;e body is shryned in &thorn;e chirche.&mdash;
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="98"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also of a nother meracle ychull &yogh;o<SUP>u</SUP> &yogh;et telle<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche felle in &thorn;e tyme of &thorn;e same kynge,</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as hit &thorn;ere in seynt Edus chirche &thorn;at tyme byfelle,</L>
<L N="4390">&thorn;e twolft &yogh;ere of his regnynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In &thorn;e kyngus house a worthy mon &thorn;er was,</L>
<L>&thorn;e whyche hade offendyd &thorn;e kyng so gretly</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t gete of hym nomoner grace</L>
<L>Bot in depe preson he was commaundyde to ly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4395">&amp; so in strong preson he was &thorn;er putte,</L>
<L>&amp; gret gyus of hyrone y-leyde hym vpone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">4396 ff.) Bl. unrichtig gyns, 4409 gynyd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; cast doun in to &thorn;e deppust putte</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e gret castellys of Salisbury dunchone;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; so of his deth he hadde gret drede.</L>
<L N="4400">&amp; ny&yogh;t and day his preyours he dude make</L>
<L>To &thorn;at blessud virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L>To sende hym grace &thorn;at he my&yogh;t ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at presone stape.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; sone after &thorn;orow goddus help &thorn;e preson he brake.</L>
<L>&amp; to seynt Edus chirche ful sone &thorn;o dude he go.</L>
<L N="4405">&thorn;e ladyes weron redy &thorn;o &amp; sone hym duden inne take &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; fulle ioyfulle in hert was &thorn;at mon &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; vp to seynt Edus shryne &thorn;o dude he go</L>
<L>&amp; knelede doune byfore &thorn;e shryne vpone a stone &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot fast y-gyuyd &yogh;et was he &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
<L N="4410">Bot sone after &thorn;at &thorn;ey brekon a-to ychone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;en comen his kepers and pursueden hym fast<MILESTONE N="251" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> alle herre mayne &amp; alle herre my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;e gyuys duden &thorn;o anon alle to-barst</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere in &thorn;e chirche in ychemonnus sy&yogh;t;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4415">&thorn;e fedrus hem-self &thorn;ey burst &thorn;ere &thorn;o ato</L>
<L>&amp; hurtuldone so a&yogh;eynne &thorn;e walle of stone</L>
<L>&amp; fulle to gobetus &thorn;ey dudone &thorn;ere &thorn;o also,</L>
<L>&amp; &yogh;et nomon hem leyde honde vpone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;ey sye &amp; herden &thorn;o euerichone</L>
<L N="4420">How &thorn;use fedrus werone y-broke a-two</L>
<L>&amp; how &thorn;ey rosshetone a&yogh;eynne &thorn;e walle of stone,</L>
<L>&amp; gret merueylle &amp; gret drede in hert &thorn;ey hadden &thorn;o.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore &thorn;ey durste note hond ley hym vpone</L>
<L>For fere of &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede;</L>
<L N="4425">Bot anon to &thorn;e kyng &thorn;ei duden gon</L>
<L>&amp; tolde hym alle &thorn;at &thorn;ey syen &amp; herden, worde &amp; dede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;e kyng &thorn;o merueyllede hym gretliche of &thorn;is</L>
<L>&amp; sayde &thorn;at &thorn;at blessud mayde oft grete meracles hadde y-do,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> god full welle bylouede forsothe he is,</L>
<L N="4430">&amp; badde hem letten hym be stille &thorn;ere ry&yogh;t so.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en was &thorn;is worthy mon in hert fulle gladde</L>
<L>&amp; heyliche thongede &thorn;is blessede mayde seynt Ede &mdash;</L>
<L>A fulle gret cause forsothe he hadde:</L>
<L>For, nad he ben, he hadde be &thorn;o dede.
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="99"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4435">&amp; &thorn;e pesus of &thorn;e fedrys weron gedirde to-gedur anone</L>
<L>&amp; hongede vp &thorn;at blessud shryne byfore,</L>
<L>In wittwnasse of &thorn;at meracle &thorn;at was &thorn;ere &thorn;o y-done.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e mon dwelto stylle in &thorn;e abbay for euermore. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;e kyng dyede anon &thorn;o after &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="4440">&amp; Wylliham Rufus was made &thorn;o kynge;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche dude eueriche day here amys,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e dayes of his leuynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On &amp; twenty &yogh;ere Will. Conquerour lyued here</L>
<L>&amp; monfullyche kept his reme in pese and rest;</L>
<L N="4445">Bot Will. Rufus leuede not here bot &thorn;rettene &yogh;ere,</L>
<L>&amp; was y-slawe of Walter Turell in &thorn;e New-Foreste. &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot in his tyme mo meracles weron &yogh;et y-do</L>
<L>For &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede,</L>
<L>And mony men weron delyuerde ou&yogh;t of preson also</L>
<L N="4450">By &thorn;e grace of seynt Ede, as &yogh;e mowe in story rede.<NOTE PLACE="foot">mowe &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As hit fell in &thorn;e twolthe &yogh;ere of his regnynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at a mon horribilyche y-boundone in preson was,</L>
<L>By-cause of hawkyng &amp; of boke-hondynge;<NOTE PLACE="foot">buck|hunting.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wherfore &thorn;e kyng by-hedde hym no grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4455">Bot ded sone after, &thorn;e kyng sayde, he shulde be</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;at he shulde haue no remedy.</L>
<L>Bot euer &thorn;e sely mon prey&yogh;ede to seynt Ede</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde graunt hym grace to past (!) a-wye.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. paft (l. pafc?) st. pass.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he lye euer y-presonede stylle in &thorn;at castelle,</L>
<L N="4460">For alle &thorn;at euer ony mon my&yogh;t for hym do,</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e day of &thorn;e Conuersion of seynt Paule appostelle.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o seynt Ede come hym by vision &thorn;us to,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; clepte his name &amp; sayde: "Ordulf, slepustow fast!</L>
<L>A-wake, Ordulf, quod he, &amp; do now after my redde:</L>
<L N="4465">Arys vp blyue &mdash; &amp; be &thorn;ou no-thyng a-gast &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; hey&yogh;e &thorn;e fast &amp; come to me: &amp; &thorn;ou shalt not be dedde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Ordulf wake of his slepe &thorn;o after anone</L>
<L>&amp; lokede welle abou&yogh;t hym on ycha syde:</L>
<L>&thorn;en sye he how his fedris weron lewesode ychone</L>
<L N="4470">&amp; &thorn;at he my&yogh;t for hem, whether he wolde, go or ryde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot he styrt vp &thorn;enne w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ony more:</L>
<L>&amp; sy&yogh;e &thorn;at &thorn;e &yogh;ates were opon &thorn;o euerychon,</L>
<L>&amp; also sy&yogh;e &thorn;at &thorn;er was nomon to lette hym &thorn;ore.</L>
<L>Bot to seynt Edus chirche &thorn;o fulle fast he ron</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4475">&amp; mekeliche knelede doune by-fore hurre shryne</L>
<L>&amp; thongede hurre hey&yogh;elyche of hurre blessede grace,</L>
<L>&thorn;at hee had delyueryd hym ou&yogh;t of his peynne</L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t hym in to a mirgurre plase.
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="100"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot his kepers &thorn;o anone after &thorn;at reden to &thorn;e kynge</L>
<L N="4480">&amp; tolden hym alle &thorn;e processe ry&yogh;t as hit was.</L>
<L>Bot a&yogh;eyn seynt Ede &thorn;e kyng durst make no manysshinge<NOTE PLACE="foot">manysshinge = menacing.</NOTE></L>
<L>Nowther to herre ny to hurre place,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; lette Ordulf abyde ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>For he durst not displese seynt Ede</L>
<L N="4485">Ny hym a&yogh;eynus hurre no-thyng mys-bere &mdash;</L>
<L>Forto donn hurre wrong he hadde gret drede.<MILESTONE N="252" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;us &thorn;is selymone Ordulf y-sauyd &thorn;o was</L>
<L>By &thorn;e help of &thorn;is blessede virgyn seynt Ede;</L>
<L>&amp; dwelt styll euer in hurre blessud plase,</L>
<L N="4490">&amp; of his deythe he nad nomore drede. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot ano&thorn;er mon was cast in preson sone after &thorn;o,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche was take in &thorn;e parke of Clarindone hondyng,</L>
<L>&amp; was delyueryd &thorn;orow help of seynt Ede also,</L>
<L>&thorn;e thretteneth &yogh;ere of Williham Rufus regnyng. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4495">For Williham was a fulle sputusmon, y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; nomely bokke-hunters in his tyme nad no rest;</L>
<L>And to holy chirche &amp; to pore men fulle oft he dude amys</L>
<L>In makyng of newe foreste.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot for vengaunce of &thorn;at gret synne, as ychaue redde,</L>
<L N="4500">Of destruccione of holy chirche &amp; of pore men &thorn;at &thorn;ere duden dwelle,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at same forest after forsothe he was dede &mdash;</L>
<L>Y-slawe he was of Walter Turrelle. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot in &thorn;e vtauce of &thorn;e nexste aster-day<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. vtance.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;is mon &thorn;at y spake of, y-presonot here byfore,</L>
<L N="4505">Was delyueryd by help of &thorn;at blessed maye</L>
<L>Ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at preson for euermore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For by help of &thorn;at mayde so fulle of grace</L>
<L>His fedrys weron alle to gobetus y-broke;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;en he badde hym come ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at place<NOTE PLACE="foot">of &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4510">When alle &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;e castelle weron vnloke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In slepyng &thorn;at blessud virgyn apperede hym to</L>
<L>&amp; badde hym arys radeliche &amp; blyue,</L>
<L>&amp; go to hurre chirche he shulle also,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yf he wolde han lengur his lyue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4515">&amp; he dude &thorn;o radeliche as he hym badde,</L>
<L>&amp; hy&yogh;ede hym fast ou&yogh;t of &thorn;at place &mdash;</L>
<L>For of nomon he was &thorn;o a-dredde</L>
<L>When he knew &thorn;at he had hurre help &amp; hurre grace.<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;at &uuml;bersch.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot to hurre chirche fulle fast he ron</L>
<L N="4520">&amp; knelede a-doune byfore hurre shryne</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> meke hert he &thorn;ongude herre &thorn;on</L>
<L>For he hadde delyueryd hym from his pyne. &mdash;
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="101"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mony a monnus lyff he sauede y-wys,</L>
<L>Bothe by hurre lyff &amp; after hurre deythe also;</L>
<L N="4525">For by nomon hit fell ony tyme amys</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;e whyche hadden loue &amp; trust hurre to. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot when Williham Rufus was &thorn;us forthe agone</L>
<L>&amp; in &thorn;e newe forest hadde lost &thorn;us his lyue,</L>
<L>Harry, his brother, was made kyng &thorn;o after hym anone,</L>
<L N="4530">&amp; regnede here &thorn;retty wyntre and fyue. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; in his tyme hit felle by case<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;e archebysshop of &YOGH;orke went to Jerusalem on pilgremage:</L>
<L>&amp; vpon &thorn;e grete see in suche a tempest forsothe he was</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wende to han be lest &amp; alle his men, &yogh;omon &amp; page;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4535">&thorn;at tempest was so hoge &thorn;ere &thorn;o y-wys,</L>
<L>And raynede, &amp; blew &thorn;e wynde so spitusly,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he set not by his lyff a rysshe</L>
<L>Ny by none of his mennus lyfus &thorn;e wheche stoden hym by.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;o in to his help he clepte &thorn;at blessud mayde seynt Ede</L>
<L N="4540">&amp; prey&yogh;ede hurre of hurre help &amp; of hurre grace,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he wolde fouchesaue to be his help in &thorn;at gret nede:</L>
<L>And he wolde mekelyche on pylgremage visete hurre place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot as-sone as &thorn;e bysshop had &thorn;us his preyours made,</L>
<L>&thorn;at blessede virgyn seynt Ede stode fast hym by</L>
<L N="4545">And sayde: "syre bysshop, haue &yogh;e no dradde!</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shall come home saue &amp; sounde, securly"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And went forthe bodiliche vpon &thorn;e see &thorn;e bysshop byfore &mdash;</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t as he dude somme tyme byfore kyng Knowde.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e wynde stonchede &amp; blew nomore,</L>
<L N="4550">&amp; &thorn;e meyst turde in to a bry&yogh;t cloude,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; woxse in to so fayre &amp; so bry&yogh;t a day</L>
<L>&thorn;at iche mone my&yogh;t se alle &thorn;e see abou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;is blessed virgyn vanysshede &thorn;o a-way &mdash;</L>
<L>For &thorn;o &thorn;ey neron in nomore dou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4555">Bot past home w<SUP>t</SUP>-ou&yogh;t ony drede or fere;</L>
<L>&amp; come to Wyltone anone on pilgremage,</L>
<L>&amp; prechede &thorn;ere &thorn;at miracle, &thorn;at ichemon dud here,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dud &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE></L>
<L>Kny&yogh;t, squiere, &yogh;omon &amp; page. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Jhesu, &thorn;at &thorn;is blessede virgyn was euer bysy<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. blesslede.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4560">To help eueryche mon in his gret nede, ferre or nye;</L>
<L>For &thorn;ere nas nomone &thorn;at askede hurre ony thyng hertly,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he hit nadde, &yogh;if he hit askede resnably.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And to alle hurre sustren so gret comforde was he,</L>
<L>And apparede oft to hem bothe day and ny&yogh;t;<MILESTONE N="253" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4565">Notte onlyche in swenynge &thorn;ey dude hurre see,</L>
<L>Bot also &thorn;ey sye hurre bodyliche w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre hy&yogh;e-sy&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="102"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;at &thorn;us visiones nere not fantomysliche y-do,<NOTE PLACE="marg">Miraculum.</NOTE></L>
<L>A gret ensampulle y chulle &yogh;ow telle</L>
<L>By a lady &thorn;e whiche dwelt in &thorn;at abbay &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="4570">&thorn;e whiche louede &thorn;at blessud virgyn euer ry&yogh;t welle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alfyne men &thorn;o duden clepe &thorn;e same,</L>
<L>&amp; abbas of &thorn;at plase &thorn;at tyme was;</L>
<L>&amp; as ofte as he herde seynt Edus name,</L>
<L>He wolde anone &thorn;en make a cres byfore hurre face,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4575">&amp; wepe he wolde for gladnesse &thorn;en also</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> mylde hert &amp; wepyng hy&yogh;e &mdash;</L>
<L>So gode hert he hadde &thorn;at blessudde virgyn to<NOTE PLACE="foot">blessude &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; in hurre hert hurre louede so entyerly.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot on a tyme hit felle by &thorn;at lady so</L>
<L N="4580">&thorn;at hurre hy&yogh;e was waxson so seke</L>
<L>&thorn;at of hurre sey&yogh;t he dredde sore &thorn;o,</L>
<L>&amp; also in gret dou&yogh;t he was of herre lyf eke;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre ry&yogh;t hey&yogh;e and hurre body weron seke bothe two:</L>
<L>For a feruent mygreyn was in &thorn;e ry&yogh;t syde of hurre hedde;</L>
<L N="4585">&amp; a feuer quarteyne he hadde &thorn;o also:</L>
<L>So &thorn;at tyme of hurre lyff no trust he nadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &yogh;erne he pray&yogh;ede to seynt Ede to send hurre help &amp; grace,</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at hit were hurre blessude wylle.</L>
<L>&amp; sone he falle a-slepe ry&yogh;t in &thorn;at same place</L>
<L N="4590">&amp; a litulle space he slept &thorn;ere fulle stylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot sone after &thorn;is blessud virgyn come hurre to,</L>
<L>As he hadde hurre prey&yogh;ede fulle oft-tymes byfore,</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre feyre honde blessud herre body &thorn;ere &thorn;o</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre thome touchede herre hey&yogh;e &thorn;at was sore,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4595">&amp; sayde: "dame Alfyne, drede &thorn;ou nomore</L>
<L>Of no sekenesse &thorn;at &yogh;e here-byfore han y-hadde!</L>
<L>For &yogh;e shalle not fele &thorn;erof nomore sore,</L>
<L>Nowther in &yogh;our body ny in &yogh;our hedde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;en &thorn;is blessud virgyn vanysshede away, when he hadde &thorn;is do.</L>
<L N="4600">&amp; dame Alfyne woke of hurre slepe &thorn;o after anone:</L>
<L>And mony shalus he sy&yogh;e falle from hurre hey&yogh;e &thorn;o &mdash;</L>
<L>&thorn;en my&yogh;t he sy&yogh;e welle, &amp; alle hurre sekenesse was agone.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;en was he in hert mery and gladde</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ongede mekelyche &thorn;at blessud virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L N="4605">&thorn;at he so gode hele hurre y-&yogh;eue &thorn;o hadde;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hole st. hele.</NOTE></L>
<L>And forthe vpone hurre wey alle-holle &thorn;en he hede. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &yogh;et Alfine hadde a nother cause to loue ry&yogh;t welle seynte Ede:</L>
<L>For seynt Ede dude for hurre &yogh;et meche godnesse more,</L>
<L>As &yogh;e mow in story of hem, &yogh;if &yogh;e lust, welle rede,</L>
<L N="4610">&thorn;at he dude fyue &amp; twenty &yogh;ere hurre prelacione byfore.
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="103"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For by visione seynt Ede come to a womon vpon a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche was a worthy wyff &amp; dwelt in Wyltone &thorn;o; &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; he hurre-self sy&yogh;e &thorn;at same sy&yogh;t</L>
<L>&thorn;at same tyme &thorn;ere also.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4615">Ry&yogh;t by vision &thorn;ey sy&yogh;e &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L>Come doune from hurre shryne a ry&yogh;t gode pase</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t to hurre modur tombe he hede;</L>
<L>And Alfyne, as hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t, stode &thorn;o &thorn;ere in &thorn;at same place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And vpon &thorn;e ry&yogh;t syde of &thorn;e tombe, hem &thorn;ou&yogh;t, &thorn;at mayde dude go</L>
<L N="4620">And w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre fote he metede &thorn;e lengthe of &thorn;at space</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e brede &thorn;erof he mette &thorn;o also,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. &thorn;o st. &thorn;e? &thorn;o vor also &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre ry&yogh;t honde &thorn;o he blessede &thorn;at place;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;o went to Alfyne &amp; stode hurre &thorn;er by,</L>
<L>&amp; of hurre owne hede he toke &thorn;e veylle away y-wys</L>
<L N="4625">&amp; vpon Alfynus hedde he dude hit &thorn;o lay,</L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "come hydur &amp; haue, dou&yogh;ter! &thorn;ou shalt haue &thorn;is."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre ryng from hurre feyngure he toke also</L>
<L>&amp; vpon Alfynus feyngre he put &thorn;at ryng anone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor anone ist vpone ausgestr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; sayde: "haue, sustre, &thorn;is ryng &thorn;e to</L>
<L N="4630">&amp; where &thorn;ou hit stylle &thorn;y fyngur vpone!<NOTE PLACE="foot">l. were.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For abbas of &thorn;is house &thorn;ou shalt here-after be,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> gret habundauns of gode &amp; gode rest and pes also,</L>
<L>&amp; lyff &thorn;ou shalt here in gret prosperite;</L>
<L>Bot in schorte tyme after &thorn;ou shalle hennys go.<NOTE PLACE="foot">tyme &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4635">&thorn;us shalt &thorn;ou lyue here in gret prosperite,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ou schalt not long here after &thorn;at a-byde;</L>
<L>Bot ry&yogh;t here in &thorn;is plase y-buryed &thorn;ou schalt be</L>
<L>Fast by my modur ry&yogh;t syde"<NOTE PLACE="foot">my &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And when &thorn;is blessud virgyn Ede &thorn;use wordus hadde sayde,<MILESTONE N="254" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4640">Into hurre shryne he went a&yogh;eyne anone.</L>
<L>Anon &thorn;o in &thorn;e mortyde Alfildus tolde &thorn;at mayde</L>
<L>All hurre sweuene ry&yogh;t as hit was done.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Alfyne thongede god &thorn;o &amp; seynt Ede,</L>
<L>And sayde: "sothely, dame, y sie my-self &thorn;at same sey&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="4645">And when he a&yogh;eyne in to hurre shryne hede,</L>
<L>Abou&yogh;t hurre &thorn;o y sie &thorn;o a fulle gret ley&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And hurre modur Woltrude y sie &thorn;ere also</L>
<L>Vpon seynt Gabriellus auter honestelyche lygynge,</L>
<L>And he badde &thorn;at y shulde come thedur hurre to</L>
<L N="4650">&amp; &thorn;ere w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre make my dwellynge;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He badde &thorn;at y shulde come &thorn;ere to hurre &thorn;o anone</L>
<L>&amp; lyge w<SUP>t</SUP> herre &thorn;ere in &thorn;at honest plase;</L>
<L>Bot y sayde: " "nay, lady, y nam not worthy so to done,</L>
<L>I prey &yogh;ow, lady, mekeliche of &yogh;our grace." "
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="104"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4655">Bot he toke me by my ry&yogh;t honde anone &thorn;o</L>
<L>And to hurre so he pulde me &thorn;o anone<NOTE PLACE="foot">steht hinter 4655.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; doune by herre he layde me &thorn;ere also</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t &thorn;ere vpon &thorn;at auter-stone,<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;ere &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayde: ""dou&yogh;ter, &thorn;ou shalt haue of god grete grace,<NOTE PLACE="foot">dou&yogh;ter &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4660">For abbas &thorn;ou shalt be here nexste after &thorn;is,</L>
<L>And also here &thorn;ou schalt lyge by me in &thorn;is same plase</L>
<L>When &thorn;i soule is past to heuene-blys.""</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And w<SUP>t</SUP> &thorn;at Woltrud vanysshede awey anone</L>
<L>&amp; of hurre &thorn;en sawe y nomore,</L>
<L N="4665">Bot a&yogh;eyne he went in to &thorn;at same stone</L>
<L>From &thorn;e whiche he come &thorn;at tyme byfore."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;us in &thorn;is manere to Alfyne shewyd hit was,</L>
<L>Bothe by seynt Ede &amp; seynt Woltrude, hurre modur dure,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he shulde ben abbas of &thorn;at same plase,<NOTE PLACE="foot">same &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4670">And &thorn;at he shulde be buryede fast by Woltrude &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;en sone after &thorn;at diede Bry&yogh;tyne, &thorn;at blessude abbas,</L>
<L>&amp; hurre soule past vp to heuene an hy&yogh;e:</L>
<L>And &thorn;en was Alfyne y-blessud abbas of &thorn;at plase.<NOTE PLACE="foot">y &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; twey &yogh;ere &amp; an half he gouernede hit fulle honestly:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4675">Won &yogh;ere in &thorn;e tyme of seynt Edwarde &thorn;e Confessoure</L>
<L>He gouerde &thorn;e abbay of Wyltone, fulle honestlyche, y-wys,</L>
<L>And a nother &yogh;ere in tyme of Willyham Conquerour;</L>
<L>And &thorn;en hurre soule past vp to heuene-blys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in hurre tyme gret pes &thorn;ere was</L>
<L N="4680">Among hurre sustren &thorn;ere euerichone,</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> all manere prosperite, spede and grace,</L>
<L>Ny godus ny catell &thorn;ey fayledon &thorn;o non;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And so grete householde he hulde &thorn;o also,</L>
<L>Gretter &thorn;en was ony y-holden &thorn;ere &thorn;at tyme byfore:</L>
<L N="4685">For pore and ryche &amp; also for hosere wolde come &thorn;edur &thorn;o,</L>
<L>Meyte &amp; drynk w<SUP>t</SUP> other sport &thorn;ey shulde haue redily &thorn;ore;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; also a fulle devou&yogh;t womon he was, y-wys,</L>
<L>&amp; meche he louede &amp; worshepede seynt Ede.</L>
<L>Bot he woxce seke &thorn;o sone after &thorn;is</L>
<L N="4690">&amp; sone afterwarde he dyede &amp; to heuene hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;an, when he in hurre deyth-bedde lay,</L>
<L>Full &yogh;erne he prey&yogh;ede &amp; cryede vpone seynt Ede:</L>
<L>"Help me now, he sayde, &thorn;ou blessud may,</L>
<L>Help me, lady, now in &thorn;is houre of so gret drede!"<NOTE PLACE="foot">ist unten a. R. erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4695">&amp; &thorn;en twey prestes weron reuysshede at hurre byddyng</L>
<L>&amp; fetten &thorn;e shryne &amp; sette hit doune &thorn;ere hurre bedde byfore;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;e ladyes tokon hurre vpon herre armys a&yogh;eyne herre comynge,</L>
<L>And for hurre weptone &amp; sykede &thorn;ey dude fulsore.
<PB REF="00000113.tif" N="105"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot on of &thorn;o ladyes hadde y-waket all ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="4700">&amp; to slepe a litull he &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he wolde go;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;o he leyde hurre doune &thorn;ere to slepe a litulle why&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot a fulle feyre sweuene anon he met &thorn;ere &thorn;o:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he sie an angel &thorn;er, &thorn;at &thorn;us to herre sayde:<NOTE PLACE="foot">&thorn;er &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>"Seyste &thorn;ou not where owre lady, goddus modur, stont alredy,</L>
<L N="4705">&thorn;orowe &thorn;e preyer of seynt Ede, &thorn;at blessud mayde,</L>
<L>To haue &thorn;e soule of Alfyne w<SUP>t</SUP> herre vp to ioy of heuene an hey&yogh;e?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Seyste &thorn;ou not where he stont, &thorn;at is of alle maydenus floure.</L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> hurre a gret nowmbre of other maydenus also,</L>
<L>Alle-redy stondyng aboue &thorn;e chirche in &thorn;e heyxst toure</L>
<L N="4710">To resayue &thorn;ere Alfynus soule, when hit ou&yogh;t hurre body dothe go?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And a nother lady &yogh;et, &thorn;e whiche lay &thorn;o herre by slepyng &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>Mette &yogh;et a nother sweuene, as feyre as &thorn;is fulle ney:</L>
<L>Hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he sye &thorn;use blessud maydenus alle thre:</L>
<L>Agas, Luce, &amp; Cicyly, stondyng &thorn;ere fast herre by,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4715">&thorn;e whyche sayden to Alfyne: "loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be of ry&yogh;t gode chere!</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou shalt go to heuene now w<SUP>t</SUP> vs,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. heuone?</NOTE></L>
<L>&amp; w<SUP>t</SUP> mony other maydenus, &thorn;e wheche ben now here,</L>
<L>&amp; dwelle &thorn;ere for euer in ioy &amp; blys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o sone after &thorn;is dyede &thorn;is lady Alfyne, y-wys &mdash;</L>
<L N="4720">&amp; &thorn;at was gret sorowe to mony amone!</L>
<L>&amp; hurre body sone afterwarde y-buriede ys</L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;e ry&yogh;t syde of seynt Woltrude in a ston;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bytwene Woltrude &amp; Bry&yogh;thyne y-buriede he was,</L>
<L>By-fore &thorn;e auter off angelle Gabrielle.<MILESTONE N="255" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4725">Bot &thorn;aw hurre body were buryed in &thorn;at plase,</L>
<L>Hurre soule sone after in heuene dude dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For a lady, &thorn;e whyche was nexst after hurre y-blessud abbas,</L>
<L>&thorn;is sweuene he mette, as he lay to slepe vpon a ny&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at seynt Ede come to hurre in to &thorn;at place &thorn;er as he was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">hurre &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4730">W<SUP>t</SUP> mony maydonus &amp; angelus bry&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. maydenus.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; badde &thorn;at he shulde preyen hurre sustren ychone</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey wolden prey&yogh;e for Alfynes soule enterly</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t haue for&yogh;euenesse of hurre synnes ichone,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t come to hurre in to heuene an hy&yogh;e;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4735">"For y haue preyede for hurre, quod seynt Ede, to god so fast</L>
<L>&thorn;at alle hurre synnus ben for&yogh;eue hurre, saue one;</L>
<L>Bot y nyl neuer from preynge here-after rast</L>
<L>Tylle &thorn;ey ben for&yogh;eue to herre euerichon."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, for what-monere cause my&yogh;t we say &thorn;at synne were</L>
<L N="4740">Bot &yogh;if hit were by-cause of to gret excesse of householde,</L>
<L>Forto make to euery mon &amp; womon ry&yogh;t gode chere,</L>
<L>&amp; euer to &yogh;if hem mette &amp; drynk he was fulle bolde. &mdash;
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="106"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo, what grace &thorn;is lady, dame Alfyne, hadde</L>
<L>By-cause &thorn;at he louede &amp; worshippud so myche seynt Ede:</L>
<L N="4745">For in alle hurre doyng fulle welle he spadde</L>
<L>&amp; hadde heuene at &thorn;e last to hurre mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For, wosere loued &amp; worshippud seynt Ede, y-wys,</L>
<L>His trauelle shalle be ry&yogh;t welle y-quytte;</L>
<L>&amp; wosere dothe also to hurre ony thyng amys,</L>
<L N="4750">Aftre as he hath deseruede, he shalle fynde hit.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hurre grace &amp; hurre godenesse ys euer redy,</L>
<L>And nomely to hurre sustren &thorn;at dwelt in herre abbay,</L>
<L>&amp; also he preyth to god bothe ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>To &yogh;elde godenesse to alle hem &thorn;at dothe hem helpy.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4755">Bot &yogh;et oftymes he wolde suffre men to done hem wronge &mdash;</L>
<L>&amp; so Jhesu suffrede &thorn;e Juys hym to slen,</L>
<L>&amp; toke vpone hem vengance afterwarde longe:</L>
<L>As euery gode-friday men may &yogh;et welle seyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot holy writte telle &yogh;ow alle &amp; som,</L>
<L N="4760">Whose wolle hit w<SUP>t</SUP> vnderstondyng rede:</L>
<L>Dedit illis obprobrium sempiternum:</L>
<L>For euery gode-friday at herre fundement &thorn;ey done blede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; a nother gret vengaunce &thorn;ey hadden also:</L>
<L>When Jerusalem of Titus by-seygyd was,<NOTE PLACE="foot">b in by vorgesetzt; Bl. y seygyd.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4765">For hongurre &thorn;ey etone hurre owne children &thorn;o</L>
<L>For vengance of fourty wynter byfore trespas &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As &thorn;e prophet makuth to vs mencion of &thorn;is</L>
<L>&amp; saythe to vs on &thorn;is monere:</L>
<L>Saturati sunt filijs &amp; dimiserunt reliquias paruulis suis &mdash;</L>
<L N="4770">Long after suche vengance god dude on hem &thorn;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Suche vengaunce he toke not for hym-self only,</L>
<L>Bot for his discipullus he toke hit also,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;ey nolde not leue herre foly</L>
<L>And amende hem and bettre do. &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4775">And so wolle seynt Ede &amp; other seyntus mo</L>
<L>Abyde long, or &thorn;ey desire of god vengance to sende</L>
<L>To pepull &thorn;at hath to hem mys-do,</L>
<L>To loke where &thorn;ey wolle amende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And also god wolle suffre men to haue gret heuynasse,</L>
<L N="4780">&thorn;aw he loue hem ry&yogh;t welle,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ey shulden desire of hym &thorn;e more grace,</L>
<L>And also for &thorn;ey shulden in &thorn;e more mekenesse dwelle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;et he wolle delyuer hem at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>And sette hym a&yogh;eyne in hurre furst prosperite,</L>
<L N="4785">&amp; herre enmyes sodenly doune cast</L>
<L>W<SUP>t</SUP> all hurre power and magiste. &mdash;
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="107"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And ensampull meuyd me of seynt Ede</L>
<L>To write &thorn;use wordus &amp; hem now to &yogh;ow say.</L>
<L>For hit byfell some tyme, as y dude rede,</L>
<L N="4790">At Wylton in hurre owne abbay</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at ladyes werone seke &amp; dede mony one;</L>
<L>So gret dysese was &thorn;ere among hem &thorn;o</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ey weron seke and sorwefulle ney ichone.</L>
<L>And merueleddone &thorn;at Ede wolde suffre hem so,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4795">&amp; sayden: "what is &thorn;e cause, lady dere,</L>
<L>We prey &yogh;ow mekeliche to tell hit vs,</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e wyl not now here owre preyere</L>
<L>Bot suffre vs to leyge so long in payne thus?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For &yogh;e ben redy to help ichemone in his nede,</L>
<L N="4800">In water or londe or where-euer he be,</L>
<L>Bot &yogh;e let vs leyge here in sorwe, sekenesse and drede,</L>
<L>And to vs help ny comforde non do &yogh;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To seynt Ede &thorn;use ladyes maden this herre mone,</L>
<L>For seynt Ede nolde not help hem anone at herre wille.</L>
<L N="4805">Bot &thorn;at blessud virgyn wist fulle welle what he hadde to done!</L>
<L>&amp; by vision certeyn ladyes he come &thorn;o tille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And sayde: "sustren, ychaue herd fulle welle</L>
<L>&thorn;e gret mone &thorn;at &yogh;e han nowe to me y-made;<MILESTONE N="256" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot, my dere sustren, ychulle &yogh;ow now telle</L>
<L N="4810">Why y come not to helpe &yogh;ow as sone as &yogh;e me badde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For hit longethe, sustren, specyallyche to vs</L>
<L>To help euery cristone mon in his nede &mdash;</L>
<L>Wherfore, sustren, &yogh;e done amys</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e desire me to leue &thorn;at dede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4815">Euery criston-mon we ben y-bounde to help in his nede,</L>
<L>And as welle we moten help &thorn;e frende as &thorn;e sybbe,</L>
<L>&amp; euery mon we moten loue &amp; desire hem well to spede</L>
<L>And do hym prophet, &yogh;yf &thorn;at &thorn;ey vs bydde &mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ist u. a. R. erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For we mow cast nomon ou&yogh;t, &thorn;aw he be stranger,</L>
<L N="4820">Ny we mow not wolne hym &thorn;e lasse gode;</L>
<L>For alle we ben brethron &amp; sustren here</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at ben &thorn;e children of god.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And in as myche as he is more parfitur in charite,</L>
<L>So meche &thorn;e more nerre he is to vs.</L>
<L N="4825">Bot &yogh;e ben myn owne propre mayne;</L>
<L>Bot hym &thorn;at is most parfite in charite, y loue most y-wys.<NOTE PLACE="foot">most &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot in what-monere dyseyse &thorn;at &yogh;e ben Inne,</L>
<L>Y presente &yogh;owre preyours vp to almyghty god.</L>
<L>Bot myche more y prey for &yogh;owre synne</L>
<L N="4830">&thorn;en for &yogh;owre other wordelyche gode;
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="108"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot euer y prey&yogh;e bothe first &amp; laft</L>
<L>To god &thorn;at he wolde sende &yogh;ow suche grace</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ere be no shepe of &yogh;our flok y-laft,</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;at &thorn;ey may come to vs in to &thorn;is ioyfulle place.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4835">And &thorn;at schull &yogh;e not gete w<SUP>t</SUP> heyssy leuynge</L>
<L>Ny w<SUP>t</SUP> no lust ny lykynge of &yogh;owre fleysshe so freille,</L>
<L>Bot w<SUP>t</SUP> dyseyse and penaunce suffrynge,</L>
<L>And to loue god &amp; serue hym wyle.<NOTE PLACE="foot">wile = wele.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For while &yogh;e ben in myrthe &amp; in grette lykynge,</L>
<L N="4840">&thorn;e vndefoutere &yogh;e wollen be to &yogh;our gode<NOTE PLACE="foot">vndefoutere = less devout.</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e ley&yogh;tlocure falle in to euelle leuyng;</L>
<L>Wherfore to haue diseyse, hit dothe &yogh;ow oft gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And mekeliche suffryth what-euer god &yogh;ow sende,</L>
<L>For he nyl sende no thyng to &yogh;ow bot for &thorn;e best;</L>
<L N="4845">And preythe hym euer w<SUP>t</SUP> alle &yogh;our entent</L>
<L>To send &yogh;ow grace &thorn;at &yogh;our soule may haue gode rest!" &mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;us by vision come &thorn;is blessud virgyn seynt Ede</L>
<L>To hurre sustren, &thorn;at &thorn;o in sorowe &amp; sekenesse were,</L>
<L>And comford hem thus in hurre gret nede,</L>
<L N="4850">&thorn;at &thorn;ey shulde not falle in to no dispere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;us by vision he was as conuersaunte among hem y-wys</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t a-lyue as &thorn;aw he hadde among hem &yogh;et be.</L>
<L>For &yogh;et by a nother visione he was y-seye sone after &thorn;is,</L>
<L>To a nother lady of &thorn;e abbay &thorn;us apparede he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4855">Of &thorn;at place a lady was sente of gret honour<NOTE PLACE="marg">Sompnium miraculosum.</NOTE></L>
<L>To Herman, &thorn;at was bysshop of Salysbury &thorn;o,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e tyme of Willyham &thorn;e Conquerour,</L>
<L>To aske of hym somme help for wrong &thorn;at was to hem y-do.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. hym st. hem, vgl. 4862.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So &thorn;is lady was ocupyed &amp; tariede fulle long</L>
<L N="4860">&thorn;at he most nede at Salisbury abyde alle ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To purswe for &thorn;is grette wronge</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche was done to hem &thorn;at tyme a&yogh;eyn resone &amp; ry&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;is lady was a-angryd &amp; a-greuyd fulle sore<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. .a. angryd.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;at he my&yogh;t not of hurre hernde no sannere spede;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Bl. saunere.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4865">And blamede he dude seynt Ede &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>&amp; sayde &thorn;at he my&yogh;t not help hurre nede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Of no powere, he sayde, y traw he nys,</L>
<L>&thorn;at he nylnot mayntene hurre owne place</L>
<L>Bot suffre hit y-wrongud (be) of fals men thys,<NOTE PLACE="foot">be fehlt im Ms.</NOTE></L>
<L N="4870">Ny nylle not a-venge hurre ny &yogh;eue hem hard grace."<NOTE PLACE="foot">hem &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Algide men clept &thorn;at lady &thorn;on,</L>
<L>&thorn;e wheche sayde &thorn;at seynt Ede hadde no my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Bot &thorn;o by visione seynt Ede apperede to &thorn;at lady (sustre) anon<NOTE PLACE="foot">im Ms. ist &thorn;<SUP>t</SUP> durchstr., v. a. H.? doch fehlt wohl sustre.</NOTE></L>
<L>Sone afterwarde in &thorn;at same ny&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">u. a. R. erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="109"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4875">&thorn;e whyche lady was y-clepte &thorn;at tyme Tole &mdash;</L>
<L>And sustre to &thorn;e abbas Alfyne forsothe was he;</L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche at Wyltone lay &thorn;o alle sole;</L>
<L>And nou&yogh;t fast slepyng a wondur visione dude he se:</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In chirche he mette &thorn;at he &thorn;o was</L>
<L N="4880">Byfore seynt Edes shryne stondyng,</L>
<L>And a gret ley&yogh;t hurre &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;at he saw in &thorn;at plase,</L>
<L>&amp; a fayre company of maydenus abou&yogh;t &thorn;e shryne dauncyng;<NOTE PLACE="foot">abou&yogh;t &thorn;e shryne a. R.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot on of &thorn;e maydenus &thorn;at dauncede &thorn;ere &thorn;o</L>
<L>Clepte hurre by hurre name fulle shrylle</L>
<L N="4885">And sayde: "Tole, Tole, come hedur &mdash; why stonstow so? &mdash;</L>
<L>And speke w<SUP>t</SUP> seynt Ede &amp; here hurre wylle!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;o durst he no lengur abyde &thorn;ere<MILESTONE N="257" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Bot come to hem vp anon ry&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And &thorn;ey opondon a&yogh;eynus herre &thorn;e shryne dere,</L>
<L N="4890">&amp; he saw seynt Ede leyche &thorn;ere all-holl in herre sy&yogh;t,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; sayde: "why sayde Algide, &thorn;i sustre dere,</L>
<L>To-ny&yogh;t at Salysbury, &thorn;ere as he &thorn;o was,</L>
<L>&thorn;at y nas not of no powere,</L>
<L>Ny &yogh;ow to help of strenthe ny my&yogh;ty nas?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4895">Lowe! see here my hondone and my fete also,</L>
<L>How holle and sounde my body ys</L>
<L>And how my&yogh;ty &amp; how quyke ycham nowe also:</L>
<L>For of body ny of leme no corrupcyon &thorn;er nys;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Se me &amp; fele me at &thorn;y nowne wylle,</L>
<L N="4900">&amp; loke &thorn;at hit be so as y &yogh;ow say!</L>
<L>&amp; what-euer y bydde of god, lowde or stylle,</L>
<L>Trewelyche of hym anone hit haue y may.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wherfore Algide, &thorn;y sustre, dude amys</L>
<L>To blame me &thorn;us in ony-manere degre;</L>
<L N="4905">For in me, forsothe, no fau&yogh;t &thorn;ere nys</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at &thorn;at he fore blamede me."<NOTE PLACE="foot">fore &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot Tole a-woke &thorn;o of hurre slepe;</L>
<L>&amp; on &thorn;is sweuene meche he &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; in hurre hert sore a-dredde he was eke</L>
<L N="4910">Lest Algide hadde ony thyng a&yogh;eyne seynt Edus wille y-wrou&yogh;t.<NOTE PLACE="foot">y &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot in &thorn;e mortyde, when hit was day,</L>
<L>Algide come after &thorn;at home anone.</L>
<L>And when Tole hurre &thorn;o in &thorn;e chirche say,</L>
<L>Anon to hurre &thorn;o dude he gone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4915">&amp; sayde: "sustre, y prey &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e trewelyche telle me</L>
<L>What &yogh;e sayden or duden to-ny&yogh;t a&yogh;eyn seynt Ede;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. saydon?</NOTE></L>
<L>Hertlyche, gode sustre, now prey&yogh;e y &thorn;e</L>
<L>&thorn;at &yogh;e wolde tell me euery dele ry&yogh;t as &yogh;e dede."<NOTE PLACE="foot">&yogh;e dede &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="110"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Algide stode stylle &thorn;o in a thou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="4920">And in hurre hert fulle sore he dude drede</L>
<L>By-cause &thorn;at hurre sustre so besselyche of hurre sou&yogh;t<NOTE PLACE="foot">of hurre &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>What he hadde y-done a&yogh;eyne seynte Ede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot &thorn;en hit felle in hurre thou&yogh;t</L>
<L>What he hadde sayde &amp; thou&yogh;t &thorn;e ny&yogh;t byfore:</L>
<L N="4925">&thorn;at seynt Edus power was nought</L>
<L>Ny &thorn;at god nolde not do no wreche herre fore.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. urspr. werche? re &uuml;ber Rasur.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &thorn;en he tolde hurre sustre ry&yogh;t as hit was,</L>
<L>And no-thyng from hurre he dude hele,<NOTE PLACE="foot">vor hele ist holde auspunktirt.</NOTE></L>
<L>And sayde: "sustre, &thorn;us hit felle by cas</L>
<L N="4930">&thorn;at suche a &thorn;ou&yogh;t in my hert fele.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot y nas nere so sorwefull &thorn;is tyme byfore,</L>
<L>Bothe in hert &amp; eke in my thou&yogh;t,<NOTE PLACE="foot">my &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
<L>Lest ychaue greuede seynt Ede sore &mdash;</L>
<L>And he so meche godenesse for me hathe wrou&yogh;t!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4935">"&YOGH;eys, forsothe, sustre, quod Tole anon &thorn;o ry&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Y drede lest &yogh;e han y-wrou&yogh;t somme-what a&yogh;eyne hurre wylle;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. <ABBR>y</ABBR> wrou&yogh;t, y mit nachtr&auml;glich gesetztem H&auml;kchen; l. &thorn;er st. y?</NOTE></L>
<L>For suche a sweuene of hurre y mette to-ny&yogh;t"<NOTE PLACE="foot">ne in sweuene ist &uuml;berschrieben, urspr. swene.</NOTE></L>
<L>And all &thorn;e processe &thorn;o dame Tole dude hurre telle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And tolde hurre alle &thorn;e sweuene ry&yogh;t as he mette</L>
<L N="4940">&amp; what seynt Ede spake to hurre, also.</L>
<L>Bot when Algide hadde herde &thorn;at, fulsore he wepte,</L>
<L>And towarde seynt Edus shryne sore wepyng he went &thorn;o</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And knelede don vpone a stone &thorn;e shryne byfore</L>
<L>And mekeliche he askede mercy of seynt Ede;</L>
<L N="4945">He sayde: "blessude virgyn, y crie &yogh;ow mercy &amp; hore</L>
<L>. &amp; beseche &yogh;ow to for&yogh;eue me now &thorn;is mysdede;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For y know ry&yogh;t welle &thorn;at y dude to &yogh;ow amys.</L>
<L>Bot, blessude virgyn, haue mercy on me</L>
<L>&amp; for almy&yogh;ty goddus loue for&yogh;eue me thys!</L>
<L N="4950">For y nolle nomore here-after trespas to &thorn;e."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bot vp he rose &thorn;o, &amp; sore he wepte,</L>
<L>And towarde hurre chambre he dude &thorn;o gon.<NOTE PLACE="foot">nach And ist kneledone doune durchstrichen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot for sorwe &amp; trauelle &thorn;ere &thorn;o he felle a-slepe.</L>
<L>&amp; seynt Ede &thorn;o come to hurre anone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4955">And sayde: "Algyde, slepustow fast!</L>
<L>A-wake &amp; herken welle what y &thorn;e say,</L>
<L>&amp; be &thorn;ou of me, Algyde, no-thyng agast:</L>
<L>For ychaue for&yogh;eue &thorn;e &thorn;y trespas for euer and ay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And &yogh;e shulle knowell after &thorn;is</L>
<L N="4960">&thorn;at &thorn;orow goddus grace ychaue gret my&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;erfore &thorn;enk &yogh;e nomore amys,</L>
<L>For y chull prey for &yogh;ow euer at &yogh;our nede, wherre hit be day or ny&yogh;t."&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="foot">ist u. a. R. R. erg&auml;nzt.</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000119.tif" N="111"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;us fulle he was of godenesse and grace</L>
<L>To euery mon &thorn;at of hurre ony ry&yogh;twys thyng bydde!</L>
<L N="4965">&amp; to donn ony diseyse to hurre owne place</L>
<L>Euery godemon hadde &thorn;o gret drydde. &mdash;<MILESTONE N="258" UNIT="folio"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>All &thorn;use meracles god wrou&yogh;t for loue (of) seynt Ede<NOTE PLACE="foot">loue &uuml;berschr. v. ders. H. (Bl. l&auml;sst es aus). of fehlt.</NOTE></L>
<L>&thorn;e whiche y chaue y-wrytone in &thorn;is boke here;</L>
<L>And well mony mo &thorn;en y euer dude wryte or rede &mdash;</L>
<L N="4970">For thus weron wryton here-byfore CCC &amp; fourty &yogh;ere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For mony a meracle he hathe seythe y-wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&YOGH;yff men wolden han y-wrytone hem in to story &mdash;</L>
<L>For he hathe done mony mo &thorn;en ony o mon may bere in &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>And also meracles ben now nou&yogh;t sette by.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="4975">For nomon nyl leue no meracle now;</L>
<L>Bot when hit falluthe to ony mon for vengance amys,</L>
<L>&thorn;ey seyn &thorn;at hit nys bot a mys-happe or a mys-prowe;<NOTE PLACE="foot">Ms. amys prowe.</NOTE></L>
<L>Bot &thorn;ey nyl not say &thorn;at hit for vengance ys.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mony mon nylnot lerne forto do welle &mdash;</L>
<L N="4980">&thorn;ey ben obstynatyde so meche in couetyse;</L>
<L>Bot to here euelle y-spoke &thorn;ey ben full snelle.</L>
<L>Wherfore &thorn;e prophet sayth to hem ry&yogh;t tys:<NOTE PLACE="foot">sayth &uuml;berschr.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Noluit intelligere vt bene ageret. &mdash;</L>
<L>Bot prey we Jhesu &thorn;at he graunt vs</L>
<L N="4985">&thorn;at we mow come aftere owre deythe</L>
<L>To &thorn;e same plase &thorn;er-as seynt Ede ys. amen.</L>
</LG>
